Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: And whose fault's that?

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: How was I to know those prawns were dodgy?

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Usually, the sell-by date's a clue.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I said I'm sorry.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I notice you didn't have any.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Never trust prawns. They

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Let you cook? Take a look at me. You think it's a good idea?

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You can't do it on your own.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I'm fine.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I'd do egg mayonnaise and all. You'll probably need to boil about 25 eggs, mash them up with some mayo... Or you could stick with the ham.
Seat's taken.
Who by?
I'll think of someone.
Word of advice.
From you?
You're wasting your time.
Sorry?
I know what you're doing. Offering Tanya a shoulder to cry on. Reliable. Mr Nice. You tell her how beautiful she looks yet? Or you saving that one up?
Think you know it all, don't you?
I know a transitional man when I see him.
Worried, are we?
Don't take me on. You will lose.
You think?
She'll come back to me.
Sure of that?
Those are my kids in there.
You mean, the place you've been locked out of?
I was making Mum some tea.
She okay? What're you looking for?
Biscuits. The one's Mum likes. Thin. Chewy with, I don't know, raisins or something...I mean, how hard can it be to--
Garibaldis. They're called Garibaldis. And it's Kevin that really likes them.
Liked.
You should be in bed.
Probably. You took the decorations down.
Yeah, seemed the right thing to do.
House is quiet.
Chelsea went out earlier. Get some air.
And Carly?
Um...busy.
She's arranging the funeral, isn't she.
Yes.
Oh.
I'll go.
Come on.
Someone should speak toIan about the house. Let him know we're...
It's done. Back to bed.
Denise.
Come on, Mum. Let's get you upstairs.
Nice one. Seeing you. Just what Denise needed.
The police came round again this morning. It's only a matter of time.
I'll talk to Yolande.
Lister was looking for you. I don't think--
You've crossed the line.
What?
Your stall. You're in the wrong place.
Come on.
You have to observe the allocation.
Fine. I'll remember that tomorrow.
You'll do it today.
It's not that important, is it?
When I next come by. Okay?

...that's the thing, you see. You've gotta let the teabag do its work and then take it out before putting in the milk. On account of the fact that the fat molecules in the milk are bigger than the holes in the teabag, which clogs up the bag and stops it working. Common mistake. And while we're on the subject, you should actually put the milk in last because--
Dad.
Yeah?
I don't care. I don't care about tea. Or Rorke's Drift. Or how kidneys work. Or anything else you've been banging on about today, okay?
I was just trying to, you know...
Take my mind of things.
Yeah. Is it working?
No.
Darren...
I'm doing my best, Darren.
Great.
What do you want, son?
I don't know. I don't want to feel like this. I can't help Libby. I can't do anything. I just want it back the way it was. I want to stop feeling like this. Can you do that?
I don't know how to.
Kevin would.
I over-reacted yesterday. I'm sorry.
If you hadn't sacked me, I'd've probably quit. I've felt...like this for a while. Yesterday just...made me realise.
What?
That there's gotta be something, you know, more. Different.
Like running your own place?
I need a manager. I need you, Preeti. Give me another chance.
I'll think about it.
Dad!
Hey.
Are you gonna have tea with us again?
Soon.
Today?
I don't think so. Where's your Mum?
Had to go in to work. I'm with Ben, Lauren's gone over to Lucy's.
Oh yeah?
I wish you were still at home.
Me, too, darling.
I miss you.
See what we can do about that, eh? Off you go.
See anything funny?
Don't, Bradley...
Allocation.
Jack. You can have your sofa back. I'm moving out.
You sure you're not just saying that to make me feel good?
I'll be gone by tonight.
Where're you going?
Like you said, I've got options. The flat is all yours again. Enjoy.
I intend to.
...Mrs Masood came into the shop earlier. She said they were going round later with a big curry.
That's really kind of them.
So I thought I'd do a stew. Something that you just reheat...
Yolande...
It's the basic things people forget sometimes. Practical help, like food...
Yolande. I need to let you in on a few things.
How d'you mean?
Why Kevin was driving your car. Why he was in such a hurry. Why we all have to tell the police the same thing.
The police? I don't understand.
Do you know what a cut and shut is?
No-one was ever meant to know. Yours was the last car.
I see.
All he was doing was trying to make things right.
The car was a death trap.
Yes. And the minute Kevin found out...
You said something about talking to the police.
They can never know where you bought the car. Right now, there's no paper trail to Kevin and that's how it must stay.
I see. You want me to lie.
For the kids' sake. Knowing Kevin was involved in something illegal. That--in some way--it killed him...how will that help them?
An accessory, I think they call it. After the fact.
I wouldn't put it like that.
It's not really about how you'd put it, is it? I should go.
Yolande. You know what it'll cost the kids. I'm sorry you're in this position.
You gonna make a habit of leaving the kids with other people?
Go away, Max.
Only...Dot yesterday, Ben Mitchelland Lucy Bealetoday.
If you're looking for a fight...
I'm not. Believe me.
Then what're you doing here?
I'm moving back in.
I'm serious.
I know. That's what's so funny.

I'm thinking of the children. I want to see them, be with them. All this, it's not their fault. Things are bad enough without them being punished and all. Your fight's with me, Tan. Not them. I thought we agreed to keep them out of it. Don't use them to get at me. It's not fair.
And what was yesterday, when you accused me of being an unfit mother?
I'm just trying to save us some pain. Let's not fight. Not when we're so good together.
Good?
You know we are.
Don't...
We've got history. I know you. Everything you like...what you need...We fit. You gonna throw that away?
Stop it. Just...stop it. True. You know me better than anyone. But it wasn't me who threw it away, Max. And you're not moving back in.
Ronnie around?
Upstairs.
Can I see her?
She's...busy.
Won't take a minute.
Really busy.
Oh.
I can give her a message.
We're meant to be getting together later. We've got an 18th in the club coming up. Need to go over a few things. Tell her to come round later, yeah?
She wants to make me a manager.
Great.
I just don't know if it's enough to make me want to stay. I mean... if there was another reason to stay...
Such as?
You know how sometimes there're things that you really...long for...and you're prepared to wait forever to get them?
Yeah...I think so.
Have you ever felt like that? Longed for something?
Yeah.
What?
A Gameboy. To play Donkey Kong. I'd've killed for one of them.
Donkey Kong.
You've gotta love that little fella.
Gotta run.
No, it's okay. You've been a big help.
How did she take it?
Knocked her a bit.
She gonna play ball? It's not just the kids who could do with her keeping her mouth shut.
How'd you mean?
Where d'you think Kevin got the cars in the first place?
See those bags? This is a market, not the local dump. Get rid of them or there'll be trouble.
I know him. He won't stop there.
What can he do? You've changed the locks.
I can't fight him.
Sure you can.
I'm afraid I'm not strong enough.
Look at me. You gonna let him take your house?
No.
You gonna let him take the kids?
No.
He gonna make a fool of you again?
Never.
You're strong enough.
Putting a lot of stick about
It's my job.
If you say so.
You don't get anywhere by being nice, Mickey. I've learned that.
I dunno, I've always found it works.
And you are where?
Fair point.
Look after number one, mate. No-one else is going to.
Tanya.
I've thought about what you said. I'm sorry.
I see. Is there anything I can do to change your mind?
Time to move on.
Yes?
You know the Police're asking questions about what happened to Kevin Wicks.
So?
Watch your back, that's all I'm saying.
Why? What've I got to worry about?
It's important we speak to her.
Can't it wait?
We've waited already.
Two days. Have a heart.
Her husband may have been involved in something very serious.
Got proof of that?
Maybe he told her something...
When she wakes up, and is done, you know, grieving, perhaps you can talk to her then.
We don't need your permission.
She's unconscious.
I brought that stew. Officers.
It's okay. They were just leaving.
Mrs Trueman, isn't it?
That's right.
Do you mind if I ask you a few questions?
Can't this wait until tomorrow?
Just routine.
You'd be better off talking to--
No. It's okay. Ask away.
You knew Mr Wicks well?
Pretty well, I'd say.
The car he was in at the time of the accident. Have you any idea where he got it from?
Why would she know?
Simple question. Mrs Trueman?
I'm sorry Officer. I don't know anything about the car. Kevin never said a word.
Tomorrow. Ten o'clock. Please see to it Mrs Wicks is awake.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Something about an 18th?

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: That's right. I said I'd go over.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Whoa, there, not so fast.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: What?

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You don't want him to see you like this.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Then you'll have to go.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Me?

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Your prawns. Your bad.
Mum?
...I want them to start right away. Tomorrow. Yes, I know what time it is. You're an agency, aren't you? With people on your books? Then how about opening them?
Mum. Marge needs her tea.
What? Not you. Hang on. Pellets are in the cupboard.
She needs lettuce.
Since when?
Fresh greens. Ever so important.
I'll remind you of that next time we have broccoli. In the fridge.
We haven't got any. I need to get some.
Sorry. Two minutes. You must have someone.
You haven't moved.
We'll remember tomorrow. How's that?
Not good enough, I'm afraid.
Okay?
Nobody knows.
Good girl. Lettuce.
Keys. You think Mum'll be okay?
She's a bit confused right now, but give her time. You're doing the right thing.
You've had enough chances. I'm shutting you down.
What?
Don't do this, Bradley.
You should have a bit more respect.
Come on...
I'm serious. Put everything away. Shut everything up. It's over.
Okay. You win.
What are you doing?
I thought you were away this afternoon.
I changed plans. Why're they shutting up?
Nothing. It's fine.
He's closing us down.
No, I--
Who?
Bradley. Apparently someone complained and--
He can't.
What?
I sacked him.
What?
I've had enough. Everyday, more complaints from the stallholders. I've had enough. You need some help.
Bradley?
I'm sorry. I just wanted you to... Is that too much to ask?
No, sweetheart. It's not.
Mum?
Come here.
Oh, Mum...
Hush, now. Dot called me yesterday. Told me you needed some help. I'm here, now.
You're coming home with me. Tomorrow. We'll go first thing.
I was expecting Ronnie.
Ah.
Yes.
Isn't this awkward.
A bit.
Shame to let it go to waste. Now I'm here. Like I said...I know what's what.
How do fishfingers sound?
Had them yesterday with Grandma.
Haven't got anything else.
We could always go out.
Maybe.
Please, Mum. We've hardly seen you.
I know...
We didn't get our pyjama day yesterday. You've been on the phone all afternoon... We've been ever so good, haven't we?
Go on then. Tell Lauren to get her things...
You should eat.
Later. But thank you. It was delicious.
Pat says people have been bringing food all day. Mrs Masood...Jane...
Kind.
The police came again.
I heard. Persistent, aren't they.
Denise...they're going to ask you questions about...the car.
Yolande's?
We've talked...and, for the sake of the kids, it'd probably be best if--
--if I said I had no idea where it came from. The car was wrong, wasn't it.
Yes.
I've been lying here, these last two days, thinking. It's the only thing that makes sense.
It was two cars, welded together.
An accident waiting to happen. I'm so sorry. I had no idea.
I understand.
Kevin didn't know either. Not to start with. But the minute he found out...
He had to put it right. That's all he would've been thinking about. All he cared about was me, and the kids.
You meant the world to him.

The day we got married, we sat on the stairs there and joked about...how we'd be when we were eighty. You know, blind as bats, no teeth and still fancying the pants-- --the big, incontinence pants--off each other. Didn't get much time, did we? I miss him. My best boy. I'm so glad I knew him.
I'm so sorry.
That's okay.
‚Preeti'?
Yeah.
By name and nature.
That's terrible.
It was wasn't it. Where're you headed?
I don't know. Away from here.
Me, too. After you?
You're in the clear.
Come again?
There's nothing to link you with the cars. Nothing to even show that Kevin was selling them.
Thanks.
I didn't do it for you. I'm looking after the kids, and their memory of Kevin. You just got lucky.
What the--?
Happy now?
What're you doing?
Come on...
What sort of day have you had? Happy? Normal? He never did you any harm. How could you?
Darren.
It was Phil.
Shut up.
He made Kevin sell those cars. He never would've got into it if it wasn't for Phil.
I said--
He died clearing up Phil's mess.
Stop. It was a tragic accident and any unanswered questions died with Kevin.
Phil Mitchell--
Died with Kevin, understand? Do you really want to take on Phil Mitchell?
I thought she'd finished.
She was saving it till last. Isn't that right? Abi?
Yeah.
How was I to know?
Abi always saves the barbecue dip till last.
You say that like I'm meant to know.
Abi? Is everything okay?
Fine.
Look...I know it's been
...but I'll make it up to you.

Starting right now. Get your pyjamas on and we'll watch TV. Just us, all snuggly on the sofa. And I've got a replacement for Preeti and I'm on top of everything. Things're gonna calm down, okay? I promise.
I think I'm gonna go upstairs.
Honey, I'm home.
Mum? What you doing?
Just going through Kevin's CDs. Find some music for the... what d'you call it? Wake? Party?... Reception?
Wake.
Wake, right... think he'd like it?
What's funny?
Sorry?
Tell you a joke, did he?
I was just pointing out -
Was I talking to you? Water off a duck's back to you, all this -
No...
Tears and tiaras, one minute, then it's business as usual... well, at least Bradley won't have to put up with it much longer.
What d'you mean?
He's leaving this cesspit... I'm taking him home. Today.
No, he's not violent - have you been listening to a word I've said?... ...so, I've just got to put up with this, have I? So what am I paying you for?... oh, just forget it!
Are you alright, Mum?
Yes, fine.
Who was on the phone?
Mum's lawyer, Abi.
Told you, I don't want to hear your voice.
I'm talking to my kids -
Don't care. Anything you've got to say, write it down.
Mum -
Stay out of this, please, Lauren.
What is it, Mum?
Nothing, Abi... nothing at all.
Bradley's jumpers. I did a wool wash last night, wrapped ‚em round the hot water tank, so they shouldn't be too damp.
Thanks, Dot.
I'm gonna miss him something awful.
I know... and he'll miss you, but he can always visit.
Of course.
And you can come stay with us in Tring whenever you like... but this is the right move, Dot, it's best for Bradley.
What's best for Bradley?
Leaving -
Did I say I was leaving?
We discussed -
No. You talked, I listened.
Your mother just thinks -
I know what she thinks. I just haven't decided if what she thinks is right for anyone except her.
Pat said I might find you here. Heard from your brother?
Yeah, we talked for hours last night... what kind of stupid question is that?
I thought you might have got word on when he's arriving.
Hearse is due at 12, Deano at 12.30. Or the other way round.
Look, Carly, just let me look after you today -
I don't need looking after.
Bacon roll, my treat?... I'll even throw in a cup of tea. Come on, Carly, what d'you say?
So I said, I've always had a discount, so don't call me a liar when I ain't. I was right, don't you reckon? Sean?
Got to take this, Stace -
Steven!
Will you mind my stall for half an hour?
Half an hour? Why?
Look, just tell me yes or no.
Morning...

Here she is, the face that fried a thousand chips... Can you believe that Ronnie Mitchell? Steals the catering for Kevin's funeral, then comes in to borrow an egg-slicer. I mean, what sort of caterer doesn't have basic equipment? Me and you, we've got to put that buffet through its paces later, probe for weaknesses -
I don't care, Ian... I don't care if her puff pastry has got the consistency of a brick... I. Don't. Care.
You going to do a reading today?
Nah, Pat is.
Pat can read?
You ain't funny.
Sorry, sorry... ...should've been you though.
Why?
‚Cause you're his daughter. If I ever snuffed it, I'd want the people closest to me saying their piece.
And who'd that be? The bloke from the off licence?
You really know how to get that knife under the ribs, don't you, Carly? This is a difficult day for me too.
Yeah?
Yeah, I really... ... I thought a lot of your Dad.
Should've known...
Carly -
This ain't about you looking after me... you want me to hold your hand, tell you what's done is done and everything's fine. Well, it ain't fine. None of it.
Is this about Steven?
Steven? Why should it be about Steven?... Yes, it's about Steven.
You see? And people say I don't understand women.
It's like you're inside my head...
We're not open.
Came to see you.
Well, I'm up to my armpits in egg mayonnaise, so make it quick.
What time will you be finished?
Roxy scarpered into town and left me on my tod, so I dunno - midnight?
But you might be free for lunch?
Lunch? Why?
We need to talk.
Do we?
Yeah. Business stuff.
Business stuff?
Yeah.
As opposed to any other stuff.
That's right.
Okay. I'll get Philand Auntie Peg to take the buffet to Pat's.
One o'clock at the club?
And will you be dressed for... business?
I most certainly will.
Any news on Louise?
Not yet, no.
So why you in here
I wasn't chatting anyone up, and I was under the impression that whatever I'm doing to find your daughter, I'm doing as a favour.
And I'm grateful, but tell you what, why don't you give me the contact details for whoever you've got working this -
No.
Why?
He's a serving police officer.
Well it sounds like he needs a bit of motivation - what's he need, money? He can have money.
He isn't doing this for money, he's doing this for me. And you'd do well to remember that.
Bradley? Saw your mum... she said you were leaving. So. Is it true?
Why are you here?
I don't...
What d'you want to do, talk?
I don't know...
‚Cause I'm not feeling very talkative.
I'm not saying you can't come round the flat -
Why are you so being so shifty? What would I find?
It's a mess.
Some twenty year old with her ankles round her ears, I'll bet.
You know I'm only attracted to older women. Have I ever told you how much I fancy you?
Yes, Sean...
Pinning a divorce petition on the front door? Who d'you think you are, Martin Luther?
I know that's meant to
Nah, I'm pretty stupid too.
Oh, Sean's here. Hello mate, didn't see you there. What brings you round then?
The biscuits.
What's wrong, Tan? Disappointed?
I don't know what you mean.
Should I have my fist in his face round about now? You're being played, mate. She's hoping I'll storm in here, see you, see red, see you in court... Am I close?
Sean just came round for a chat.
Yeah? Enjoy your biscuits...
Did you know he washere?
So, are you using me?
A little bit... but not half as much as I'd like to...
Don't go.
Sorry?
Don't go. If you're going ‚cause of me, I can leave, stay with Little Mo and Freddy for a while.
That's very... thoughtful. Don't really see what it solves though, do you?
It'd give you a week or two, chance to think things through.
Oh, think things through... good idea... a bit more thinking time, that's just what I need, more time to conjure up images of my father rutting away on my wife.
If you're just going to -
I'm sorry, I didn't want to sound angry, ‚cause I'm not... I'm really not.
Well, if you're not angry, maybe there's a chance... you know? A chance to talk properly.
No.
But -

I'm not angry... but when I look at you, I don't feel anything anymore, you're just this pretty mess of hair and skin... and that link, the link I know we had... it's gone. I don't feel love or hate or any of the stuff in between... it's just nothing. Empty.
Where are you going?
Carly, scared the life out of me...
Sorry... can I have a quick word?... This was addressed to Dad... I opened it.
What is it?
His travel tickets.
D'you really think this is the time to discuss -
Yes, I think it is...
Everything alright over there?
As well as can be expected.
About time. We're late. We'll take these last two over.
Thanks, Auntie Peg.
Seeing your bloke later?
I haven't got a bloke.
Jack then.
We're meeting about business, yes.
Look, I couldn't care what you pair get up to, long as he ain't distracted from the real business in hand.
Which is?
Finding Louise. So when you see him, make sure that's top of his agenda...
I'm not sure I like the way you're asking me.
I'm not asking. You're a member of this family. So's Louise. You do what you have to do to get her home.
We should go...
Yeah, we should. Ready?
Why you both grinning?
‚Cause we've made a decision.
What?
I'll tell you in the car...
There you are, been looking everywhere for you.
I'll come.
Sorry?
I said, I'll come.
Not now, Rachel, eh? I'm gonna be late for a funeral.
I knew you'd screw it up.
Sorry?
All you needed was time. He's coming back to live with me, Max.
You don't have to pretend you're looking for something to avoid talking to me... if you want me to go, I'll go.
No...
I won't go to the funeral if you don't want me to.
Sorry?
I'm only going for Nana anyhow, hardly knew Kevin.
No, you must go.
Look, I know I can't make it right between us... but, if it's alright with you, I'm going to keep on trying.
Dean shown up yet?
Not yet.
You sure he's not being taken straight to the crematorium?
I'm not sure of anything... ‚cause no-one saw fit to include me in the arrangements.
Where's your mate? Youneed sorting out.
I've told Hev to stay away. I don't need her.
How much have you had?
What?
Drink. How much have you had to drink?
Don't go playing pot and kettle, Phil, it don't suit you.
You're gonna embarrass yourself.
Me? No-one'd notice if I did. ‚Cause I don't count.
And why should you, eh?
Because I loved him first and I loved him most...
How is everyone?
Much as you'd expect.
How are you all getting to the crematorium?
Phil's driving, Masood too. We're meant to be cadging a lift with Max, only he ain't showed.
D'you want to ride with us?
No sign?
No...
I'm really sorry, but we're going to have to go without him, Carly.
Fine.
Do you really need the cuffs? This is his father's funeral.
Don't, Mum.
Bradley? Bradley!

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Jack?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You made it then.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yeah... are you ready to go?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Go? Thought we'd just eat here...you know... working lunch?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Oh, right.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Is that a problem?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No, ‚course not...

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Can you grab the blue file that I've left in the

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: And not an egg mayo sarnie in sight..
Cam belt's bust. Thrown a connecting rod through the side wall.
In English?
That car's going nowhere.
Have they got another hearse?
Won't be free ‚til four o'clock
This is ridiculous, they'll have to get another car... Oy! Yeah, you, the Chuckle Brothers!
We'll take everyone back to mine whilst we get this sorted.
Mum?
I'm sorry...
You do understand what's happening don't you?
Oh yeah, I understand alright... the fates are conspiring... Kevin was always looking to get away... and he never could... not even in his box...
Mum? What are you doing?
Pat's right. You take everyone back to ours. But I'm staying right here.
With Kevin...

Your mum says you're headed back to Tring. Sure this is the best move for you right now? What about Dot? She'll miss you with your Grandad away- and besides, it's Tring, Bradley, Tring... you're a young man, you don't want to be cooped up in a place like that... Your sisters, they'll miss you like crazy... little Oscar... and me... I'm so sorry, son.

When I was growing up, I imagined you saying sorry to me all the time... sorry, I wasn't at the football match, sorry I couldn't make your speech day... but this apology, it doesn't mean anything, ‚cause the only bit of me that'd care...you cut that out with a bloody great chisel when you slept with my wife. So now everything you say, it's all just white noise... ‚cause I don't care... not about you or your family, not about me... nothing.
You don't want to listen to me? Can't say I blame you... but going back to your Mum's? That's a step backwards, Bradley, and, deep down, you know it...

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Proper little game-player, aren't you, Jack?

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Don't know what you mean.

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You told me business, made me think it's more -

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I never said it was more.

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Trying to knock me off-balance... And then this.

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I thought women liked surprises.

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Sometimes...

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You've only been here five minutes, and here you are, playing me, playing Phil -

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I'm not playing you. Not saying I wouldn't like to...

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: But Phil?

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Not guilty.

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Promising you can get Louise's address? What's that all about?

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I can.

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Don't be daft, you saw where he's vulnerable, and you pounced -

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: And why would I promise something I couldn't deliver?

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Gives you power, keeps him under control.

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Whatever you think -

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I think you like people in your pocket. I think you like pulling strings. I think you'd offer someone the earth if you thought they wanted it badly enough... I'm just not sure you're the kind of man who can deliver.

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I think you know that I can.

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: The books look fine. Thanks for lunch. I'll see you later.

Scene_info: R AND R/OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: It's me. Got any updates on the mother and daughter?... Do not try and fob me off! I don't care, just drop everything else, or I'll be round to drop you.

I'm not much good at speaking in public... actually that would make my Dad laugh, ‚cause he reckoned speaking in public... or shouting in public... was one of the things I do best... but anyway, here I am... and he ain't... this isn't a eulogy, I'll save that for Denise later, but my Dad would've wanted me to say thanks... so, thanks... thanks for coming. And please, eat now, ‚cause it looks like we're having the wake before the funeral... The thing about my Dad is... he was just a normal bloke... but something inside him was always telling him he should be something else, somewhere else... he shouldn't be selling cars in Walford, he should be tramping up some mountain on the other side of the world. But he never did.

This morning I opened the post - special delivery - pair of round the world tickets for him and Dean... the trip he'd always dreamt of... and I was sad, ‚cause I know how much that trip meant to him. So, that's why me and Denise have decided to go, and we're gonna take his as he's too... and we leave tomorrow. So, if you could all raise your glasses, I'd like to propose a toast - to my dad, Kevin Wicks, one of life's great travellers.
You didn't even ask me!
Thought it'd be a nice surprise.
No, Car, you just didn't think my opinion counts.
So, what do you think, Dean? D'you think Dad'd prefer to be scattered in Hackney or Honolulu?
I don't know... I don't care...
Can we have a moment please?
Dean?
I can't do this.
What d'you mean? You're worried about going back to prison?
I'm worried about coming out -
You can't be institutionalised after two months -
No, you idiot - I mean, coming back here, without Dad... I mean that's all that was keeping me going.
You're not coming back here. You're coming with us.
Slight problem for me there...
I talked it through with Denise. Soon as you're released, you fly out and hook up with us.
How'm I gonna afford that?
I've got a few savings put by from when I was with Nico.
Serious?
That enough to keep you going?
Carly, it's the funeral directors. They've had a call from the crematorium.... if we don't get your Dad over there within the hour, they'll have to put it off until tomorrow.
I'm going now, Grandma.
Oh, right... you got all your stuff?
Everything I need.
Expect your mum can always pop back, pick up any bits and bobs.
Yeah... Anyway, give Grandad a big hug for me... tell him I'll pop over to see him when I can.
He'd like that...
Thank you.
No, thank you...
‚Leave the girls alone. They're upset.'? What's that supposed to mean?
Clear enough, isn't it?
Since when did you win the right to tell me what I can and can't do with my children?
Erm... Let me see... that'd be around the time you slept with your son's wife.
And what about bringing Sean Slater round here? Thinking of the girls then, were you?
Sean's got nothing to do with this.
He has if he starts sleeping with their mother.
How d'you know he hasn't
My son's just told me he's leaving, that he don't want anything else to do with me, and I have to come home to this!
Stop it! Stop it!
Lauren, darlin' -
No, Dad! We can hear every word.
It's not as bad as it seems, your mum and me, we're going to calm down now -
No. You have to go, Dad. You have to go now.
Have you seen him?
Bradley? He's inside. I only popped out to fill up with petrol.
No, he ain't. He's taken his suitcase, said his goodbyes... and he left me this... I'm sorry, Rachel, but he's gone on his own...
Haven't you got any contingency plans for this kind of thing?
It won't do any good, Chelsea. I've been sat out here, talking to them for the past hour.
Surprised you weren't packing your suitcase.
What've I done now?
Carly announced your trip...
He'll have to share a room with Peter and Bobby.
What?
Steven. If he moves in. Ain't fair to make Lucy share, not at her age.
Hang on, are you saying?
I'm saying, I'll give it a try...
But... why?
‚Cause in the end, no matter what he's done, he's family...
We could push it there?
That's a lot of car to shift.
Especially with a back like mine.
What about dialling 999?
This isn't an emergency.
Hang on, what are we doing?... How far's the crematorium?
A mile or thereabouts.
Follow me.
What are you doing?
We're going to carry him...
Why d'you bring me in here?
So you could buy me a drink.
I'm in the middle of a funeral -
I found her, Phil. I found your daughter.
It's definitely Louise... Where did you get this?
It was emailed this morning. Friend of mine, he staked out the address yesterday afternoon.
So you know where she lives? You've got an address?
Yeah, I gave it to Phil last night. Didn't he tell you?
Can't find Phil anywhere.
No. You won't.
Did you get them?
Yeah...
Oh, Carly, love, come here...
Yeah?... ...I'm just picking up a car from Dave Stanway's -
And that's definitely him?
Yeah...
But how can we be sure?
I dunno, Libby, I suppose some things you just got to take on trust.
If it is, Kevin, I expect that's just a representative sample... be quite interesting to devise an experiment -
Shut up! That's Kevin you're talking about. Ain't some ingredient in a chemistry lab!
I'm sorry...
What's the problem?
My fault, Mum. I was
That ain't like you, Libby.
I know, I'm sorry.
Don't worry... now I've been to see Yolande, she's so excited about you staying there... Is that...?
Yeah... Carly got back whilst you were out.
Right... right. I dunno what I should feel right now... anyone got any ideas?
Sad?... Kind of a safe bet.
Yeah, sad... you
Well, you're off on an adventure, aren't you?
Yeah, I suppose I am... you know if you've got a problem with me going on this trip, Chelsea, we need to talk about it now, cause I'm going to have to start packing soon.
I haven't.
‚Cause tell the truth, I'm not so sure my decision making's what it should be right now, so if you think this one stinks -
It doesn't, Mum.
‚Cause in the end, it's only ashes... don't matter
You're not upsetting us, Mum. It's good for you, it's good for Carly, and we'll be fine.
Chelsea?
Yeah, we'll be fine...
Okay, I've got things I need to buy. Either of you want to come with me?
I'm gonna stay, start taking my stuff over the road.
Me too. Sounds like fun...
You'll be bunking up with Pete and Bobby, hope that's okay.
Yeah, only fair, I mean a girl's got to have some privacy.
Yeah, I think so.Far as I can see, the only way this is going to work, is if you treat that house as your home, isn't that right, Jane?
‚Course.
Come on, I'll take you over.
Kicked you out?
No. I walked.
‚Course you did. See, it's all coming back on you, Max.
You and me both. Oh, that reminds me, seen your brother recently?
Just say what you want to say and clear off.
Okay... only I heard he's got a new girl on the go.
So?
Hasn't he told you?
I ain't seen him today.
What about yesterday?... No? Blimey, he must really like this one.
What are you trying to do, Max?
Me? Nothing... but talk to your brother, ask him about his love-life...
Girls are having their supper at Dot's tonight...
Is that right?
Yeah, that's right.
What?
The scar... I want to see it.
You got a kinky side I should know about?
Someone shot you...
I was wondering what that was.
Don't joke, Sean... seeing it like this... to think someone wanted you dead... You never talk about the army.
Not much to say.
Because it's painful?
Painful? Nah. I liked it. The world made sense.
With people trying to kill you?
That's the job... You have a pop at them, they have a pop at you.
But you never shot anyone, did you?
Yes, I did.
But you didn't kill them?
You get shot in the head with an SA80, it's gonna sting a bit.
You killed someone? I can't... I mean... what does that feel like?
It felt like... I dunno... it felt straightforward... like I was doing my job... it felt like nothing.
No anger... no hate?
Nothing. And that's good, ‚cause if you're going to kill someone, it's best if you're dead too. Inside. And that's what I was. For years. Dead. But now? I'm breathing again...
It's a much better photo.
... Eightflamin' miles away! Can't believe our little girl's been living so close all this time. Wonder what school she goes to? Can't tell from that uniform.
No... I just sat outside the flat in the car...
What were you going to do?
I dunno... didn't have a plan... just wanted to see her again.
I know, darlin'...
She's living in some poxy little flat. She should be here...
I know.
...With me. With her brother.
Where are you going?
To see her with my own eyes.
Louise won't be there, she'll be at school.
So I'll talk to Lisa.
You knock on that door, she'll slam it in your face -
Like to see her try.
And then she'll bolt -
She won't get a chance.
Sit. Down. You listen to me. Not a day's gone by when I haven't dreamt of this, not a single day... but you go knocking on that door, and it ends there. We've got to be cleverer than that.
Like?
We call Ritchie Scott, tell her what we know -
Sniff of a lawyer, she's packing her bags.
She won't know.
And she won't know I'm coming ‚til I've got my boot in her lying, cheating -
Which is exactly why you ain't going anywhere! This is too important to mess up, Phil. Needs to be done right. Give me an hour to speak to Ritchie, and then we'll talk again, okay?
Carly? I know you're in there!...
Carly?... Carly?
That racket's gonna give me a migraine.
Why don't you want to speak to her?
‚Cause I'll only have to sit through her pathetic attempts to talk me out of it -
But she understands why you're going, doesn't she?
Maybe. But she won't understand why I'm not coming back.

Yeah, we just moved here from Loughton and my missus asked me to check out all the primary schools in the area... are your kids the ones with the greenbook bags?...yeah, I've seen them... come out about three, don't they?... Three fifteen. Thanks.
Ian! I'm going to pick Bobby up from school, d'you want anything from the supermarket?
Sorry if I scared you...
You didn't. It's fine.
Jane... I want to thank you... for giving me a second chance...
Yeah, well... not me you've got to thank, it's Ian.
Carly doesn't want to see you, but there's something I think you need to know...
Phil?
Who let you in?
Libby... She says you ain't planning on coming back. That true?
...Yes.
Why d'you want to go?
Not exactly a lot left for me round here, is there...
Thanks, Auntie Kim... So if I come round tomorrow morning, that be okay?... Nah, Libby's staying in Walford... thanks. See you then.
Making alternative arrangements?
I'm going to stay at Auntie Kim's.
Excuse me?
I don't want to stay at Patrick and Yolande's.
So why didn't you tell me before? I was counting on you staying with your sister.
Well, maybe you should've spent a little bit less time thinking about what you need, and a little bit more thinking what we need.
You don't think that if it helps Carly to say goodbye to her father -
Oh, flamin' Carly!
She's your step-sister, and she's just lost her father!
I lost my Dad twenty years ago, and I can't remember you forking out to take me round the world.
You were a baby, and your Dad ain't dead.
Might as well be... no-one ever talks about him.
You know why that is.
Do I?
Your Dad... he didn't behave very well.
Well, we've only got your word for that.

Your Dad was a horrible man, Chelsea, and I was glad to see the back of him! I'm sorry... look, I don't pretend to know what it was like in prison for you, but I know it's shaken a lot of things to the surface. Losing Kevin, it's bound to make you think about your father...
You don't know what you're talking about. Enjoy your holiday.
No. I've just lost my husband. I'm not losing you. I'm staying put.
I promised your Dad, I'd look after you.
I'll bet you promised him a lot of things over the years. This is just one more for you to break.
The last wishes of a dying man.
Funny that, ‚cause when he was alive he couldn't stand you.
That ain't true.
‚Course it is. He hated you.
You don't understand about me and Kevin -
But I understood him. And I sure as hell understand you.
He wanted me to look out for you, how'm I gonna do that if you're a plane ride away?
D'you know what? Something tells me I'm gonna do just fine without you.
Why are you so angry?
D'you want a list?
I'm familiar with the list, thanks... but here, right now, what's at the front of your mind?
I don't need this -
You'd hit me if you could, why?
Just go away -
You want to put your fist in my face, I can see it - why?
‚Cause it was you holding his hand - you! - and it should've been someone he loved, it should've been me!

The last thing Kevin saw was a face that loved him. And he wanted me to step up, to look after you and Dean. And he trusted me to do that, ‚cause he knew I was the only person on this earth who'd be on your side, no matter what -

Oh, just shut up... shut up! D'you want to know how I see that scene? My Dad's in pain, he's dying... and who does he get to spend his dying moments with? His doting kids? The wife he loved? No. He gets a lying, manipulative, clapped-out old booze-hound.
So, this is it then, this is how it ends... I'll still be here if you ever come back...I ain't giving up on you.
I'm your Mum...
I don't know where toput him...
Why've you been keeping your phone turned off?
Have I? I dunno, battery, maybe....
So you ain't got a new girlfriend or nothing.
What?
‚Cause you'd tell me -
‚Course - what is this?
This is nothing... it's just Bradley leaving, sent me a bit loopy... feel like everything's falling apart...
Well, you still got me. C'mere...
She really wants to go.
I know.
She'd do anything for us... look how she stood by you when you got sent away.
I know.
All the relationships she's had... they flew out of her control. And now Kevin. This trip gives her a chance to find an end on her terms. But she won't go, unless she knows you think it's okay...
Sean and Tanya?
He's always fancied her.
But he wouldn't do that, would he?
Didn't think so... but there's definitely something going on. He's acting really weird.
But Tanya?
Max said he was seeing some woman.
If it was Tanya, why wouldn't he just tell you?
You don't know Max. He likes his little games.
Well, I don't believe it. It'd be like the ultimate betrayal.
What if she's trying to
What's she doing here?
I've got a name.
Yeah, you have, only I'm trying not to use it in front of Bobby.
‚Scuse me?
Bobby, go through there, darlin'.
I'm sorry, it was my fault, I didn't know there was a problem between you two.
You want to stay here, Steven? Rule number one: the only tarts in my kitchen have got jam on top.
You cow!
Get her out of my kitchen, she ain't hygienic.
See that's what I have to put up with, and the only people I could guarantee wouldn't judge me were my Mum and Sean.
Come here - Your mum, Sean and me.
I don't want to get you in trouble...
So it's true then? About Louise?
Phil thinks she's coming to stay for a while, yes.
How's that work then?
I don't know... I think he got in touch with Lisa and they came to some sort of arrangement.
I knew it! Ron was worried that he was going to snatch her but he's paid her off, hasn't he?
I don't know... but
Cab's here... Got you this. Thought about getting you a St. Christopher, you know, keep you safe on your travels... but it didn't feel right... Open it.
... Thank you.
Love never ends, Carly. Just you remember that.
Louise? You're good at catching, aren't you?
Can I have my ball back?
D'you know who I am?
Mummy says I shouldn't talk to strangers.
Mummy Lisa? Your mummy and me, we used to be best friends.
I'm your daddy, darlin'. I know you ain't seen me in a long time, but I swear on my life, I'm your daddy.
No, you're not.
You used to live with me and your Mum, d'you remember? In Walford? I'm your daddy.
You're not my daddy.
Louise, darlin', please...
You're not my daddy, ‚cause that's my daddy.
Can I have my ball back now? Daddy!
You keep your work up, understand?
Yes, Mum.

‚Cause I'll always find out. And that goes for Darren Miller too. He tries any funny business, tell him it doesn't matter where I am on the planet, I can have my boot up his backside within twenty four hours.
Yes, Mum.
You forgot Kevin.
Thanks, Chelsea... and thanks for seeing this matters.
You have a good time. And when it comes to presents, don't go buying cheap knock-off from some dodgy stall. Think label, think quality.
That's my girl.
Bye then.
Bye. I'll miss you.
Me too. Take care of yourself and give summer a kiss from me.
I will...
I'm going to miss you.
I'll miss you too.
You change your mind, you've always got a home here.
Thanks, Pat... thanks for everything...
All set?
Yeah, I think so...
Is that all you're taking?
This is all I need.
I'm just nipping out for some food. Don't even know what she likes... got my phone, so you ring me if they show.
You're drinking too much, too quick. Go home.
What?
You know Peggy don't like staff drinking here.
Stuff Peggy.
Home. Now.
Well, if it ain't Walford's very own Bloodhound...
Pint. Phil around?
He popped out.
Where?
We don't know exactly, but thanks to you, Ronnie reckons we may have one more for breakfast...
That was delicious. Where d'you learn to cook like that?
Didn't have much choice over in New Zealand.
Simon didn't cook then?
No, I mean, some of the women did, but they never stayed long -
Women?
Yeah, you know, girlfriends.
How many girlfriends?
I dunno... Maybe six or seven in the time I was there.
Six or seven? Living with
Nah, only two moved in.
Still, a bit irresponsible, isn't it? When you've got a child in the house?
I was hardly a child...
Just leave them there.
The thing I don't understand is - if you don't want me here, why agree to it?
It's not that I don't want you here, Steven... I've just got to get used to having someone new around.
You're lying.

I'm lying... well, takes one to know one, I s'pose. D'you know what? You're right. I don't want you anywhere near me, let alone in my house. You make my skin crawl. But if I didn't let you, it would never stop.
The kids, Ian, looking at me like I'm the only barrier stopping us having the perfect family... so, I thought, fine, I'll throw him a rope... just enough rope to hang himself.
What d'you mean?
You can play the poor little boy if you like, but you can't keep it up forever. Sooner or later the mask's going to slip... and then you'll be packing your bags, and I get my family back...
I need to talk to my brother!
You lied to me?
Get out.
Think you've got him good, don't you?
Can't stop him having feelings for me -
Feelings for you? Don't fool yourself.
Don't you think this is all a bit pathetic? Girl your age mooning over her brother?
Tan -
You smug cow. Look at you, standing there, thinking you've got one over... tell you this, if Sean really cared about you, don't you think he'd've told you about me and Max?
Sorry?
That's right. He knew about it all... he knew for ages, and he never said a word. Enjoy your food...
Peanut butter alright?
What?
Packed lunch.
Not bothered.
Careful Lauren. If I muck ‚em up Ben won't lend ‚em to me again.
Stupid Doctor Who cards. Who cares?
Me.
Wish this was the Tardis. Get us away from here.
Think I should wake Mum up?
What for?
Can't find any sandwich bags. Hey...
Call it breakfast instead.
Oh good. You're ready.
Mum...?
I told Dot you'd pick Oscar up after school. Don't mind do you?
Would it matter if I did?
Toast? Cereal it is then.
How is she?
You know.
Yeah. Must be rough.
I'll tell her you called.
It's alright. I'll hang around.
Shouldn't you be somewhere?
Like where?
I dunno. You tell me.
What you going on about?
Mornin' gorgeous. Thought you might like these.
Funeral flowers. How thoughtful.
Oh...sorry I...
Ain't you gonna answer that?
Oh...yeah.
Seen my fags?
Hev!
Sorry?
Don't matter. Want a coffee?
No thanks. Gotta be in town in half an hour. I'll drop round later yeah? Sorry about the flowers. What do I know eh?
Shirl...
Put ‚em in some water for me, will you?

Scene_info: VIC DOWNSTAIRS - HALLWAY INT DAY LIGHT
Line: But I've arranged a swap.

Scene_info: VIC DOWNSTAIRS - HALLWAY INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I can't help if it I forgot. I had other things on my mind.

Scene_info: VIC DOWNSTAIRS - HALLWAY INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Sorry. Can we pick them up lunchtime?

Scene_info: VIC DOWNSTAIRS - HALLWAY INT DAY LIGHT
Line: If you like.

Scene_info: VIC DOWNSTAIRS - HALLWAY INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Phil? You up?

Scene_info: VIC DOWNSTAIRS - HALLWAY INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Phil?
Still sore?
Bit.
Not like you to get caught Jack.
Bloke got lucky, that's all.
Thought Jase was supposed to throw out the drunks. That's what you pay him for, innit?
Yeah.
Won't happen again.
It was like having a herd of elephants over my head last night.
Sorry. I tripped over Peter's trainers on my way to the loo.
Meaning Bobby the fidget ended up in our bed. I don't think that loft was meant for three.
No. Bobby'll have to go in with you.
What? Case you ain't noticed Dad I'm a girl. I need my privacy.
They're like sardines up there love.
Yeah but...
Don't argue alright? It ain't negotiable.
Sorry Luce.
Right. Better get to the cash and carry.
Can't it wait till Marie comes in?
We're almost out of salt.
I can help you.
I'll manage.
I've got nothing better to do.
There you go. Sorted. Salted, get it?
If that's okay with you?
Yeah course.
Mornin'.
Ouch. Turning a very fetching shade of blue I see?
Reckon it suits me? It's my favourite colour.
What made Phil lose it like that?
Been asking myself the same thing. If this is what I get for trying to help, I wouldn't want to get on the wrong side of him.
I'm sorry.
Don't be. I'm a big boy now.
Ron. The naked look suits you. GO
Do you want me to cook or serve?
Don't mind. Cook if you like.
I'd rather serve.
Then why did you ask? Not having a go at you, just saying.
Was talking to you and you disappeared.
Bought two doughnuts.
Nice one...
On auto-pilot, wasn't thinking. Kevin liked doughnuts. ‚Specially the ones with that custard stuff.
Right. Maybe you shouldn't go to work today if it's...
I have to.
But it's a heavy weight on those slim shoulders of yours.
I'll manage.
Do you want me to give you a hand?
You?
Why not?
Why? You think I'm gonna crack up?
It's alright to be upset son. You and Kev were close. I mean he was your friend as well as your...
Five minutes...
I don't believe this.
Don't shoot me down okay?
If only.GO
I know what you think...
No point then, is there?
Wait.
I'm not interested in anything you've got to say.
I don't care. I'm gonna say it anyway.
I didn't want to hurt you okay? That's the only reason I didn't come straight to you...
Give me a break. You were protecting your sister.
No. I had it out with her. Stacey swore it'd finished with Max ages before the wedding... It's true. I know Stace.
Not the point.
So I made a big mistake....
You reckon?
Look I thought it was best all round. Honestly. You can't punish me for that...
You know what Sean? All I care about is my kids. That's the only thing that matters now. You, Max, all his tarts...you're nothing.
It's different. We're different.
No.
You know how I feel.
I know that no man can be trusted. Whatever he says, whatever he does. I've been a bit dumb about it in the past, but I think I've got the message now.
I care about you.
Tough.
You don't mean that.
You helped me out when I needed it Sean. Warm body, someone to lean on. But I'm fine now.
So thank you and goodbye.
Tanya...
Can you manage by yourself?
Yeah, yeah I can.
Sean?
Tea.
No please or thank you?
No, just tea.
Don't talk to her like that.
It's alright...
No it ain't.
Not in the mood kid.
I don't need defending thanks.
If you ask me you're best off out of it...
I didn't, and I'm not.
Sean...
You had to open your big gob didn't you?
Tanya would have found out.
That why you told her? Your party was over. Didn't want anyone else to be happy?
Party? My life's been blown apart Sean. You were only consoling the pathetic cow so's you could get your leg over...
Don't talk about her like that! The one thing I had that was worth something, and you had to trash it.
What..?
I could have dropped you in it big time.
Stopped the marriage, had a show down in the Vic, or even better in the church. Yeah, give it the works, why not? I was thinking of you Stace. And her.
I didn't realise, I'm...
Oh sorry Hev.
Alright?
What you having?
Nothing.
Buy me one in that case. What's up?
What do you know about Vinnie?
Let me think. Oh yeah, he's loaded.
And?
And... He's got good taste in earrings. What else is there to know?
Do you like him? I mean...Do you see a future together?
You what?
It's just you've been through the mill lately and I don't wanna see you get hurt.
I won't.
Yeah but what if...what if Vinnie ain't telling you the whole truth?
About what?
I might be wrong. I hope I am. But I don't think so.
What are you on about?
I'm so sorry Shirl.
spit it out, will you?
I think he's married.
I'd got used to the idea of never seeing Louise again, never getting her back. Then he comes along and dangles her in front of me.
He didn't...
What would you call it then? Jack told me to wait, but I couldn't. What father would?
What did you do Phil?
I sat there, outside the school. Wasn't sure I'd recognise her, it's been so long. But course I did.
Louise? You saw her?
I talked to her...
Why didn't you tell me? Why ain't she here?
There was this bloke. She ran to him...called him Daddy.
You should have told her...
She was a baby when Lisa took her. She wouldn't know me from Adam.
So you walked away?
That's right.
How could you?
To her I was just some big scary man.
I don't believe it...
Leave it Aunt Peg.
I'm so sorry but our hairdresser's off today. If you wouldn't mind waiting another twenty minutesI'd behappy to...
I can change your appointment...
If you'd like to go through, won't be a sec. Nightmare. What did the agency say?
No can do.
What?
One of their best client's was in dire need, so they had to prioritise. No temps left.
This is all I need.
I've got a book on shiatsu at home.
Terrific. Oh well. Just have to busk it, won't we?
I think you're amazing. I mean what with... everything.
Thanks. Right, stick the kettle on while I sort this lot out.
I'm sorry about Louise, but how can you blame Jack?
Easy.
He did what he said Phil. He was trying to help you.
Was he?
Of course. He found her for you, didn't he? If you want to shoot the messenger then that's... .
So he didn't know what I was gonna find when I bowled up at her school?
No, how could he..?
‚Cos he did his research. Jack knew Lisa was with this bloke. That they were one big happy family. He knew Ronnie. He knew everything.
But why would he? I mean...
Wake up will you? All he had to do was sit back and watch the show. See the big man fall.
I can't believe he'd do that. It sounds so paranoid. Let's face it, Phil's never liked Jack.
Who's side are you on?
Not you as well.
Ron. Jack's driving a wedge between this family. If you can't see it, it's only ‚cos you don't want to.
That's rubbish.
See? He's got you brainwashed.
You're an idiot.
Better than being deluded. GO
Still wearing that lovely ankle bracelet courtesy of Her Majesty?
Generous of her, weren't it?
Ahhh, all on your own? No mummy to look after you now?
Dunno what your problem is, but if you're hell bent on picking a fight, I'm up for it right now.
Usual?
Thanks.
Sorry you've had to wait.
Oh look. You haven't touched it.
No time. Tell all your friends about us... ...Except the really hairy ones. What you doing here?
For Oscar. Saw it in the market. Babies need stimulating. Gotta start young. Where is he?
Dot's.
Dumping him already?
Make you another one.
I've got to work.
So you are dumping him.
No!
Snappy ain't you? If you can't cope, I'll help.
I don't need anything from you... I said I'll be there in a minute. No, look I'm sorry...
Oh dear. She's losing it.
Get out.
I'll take this round...
No you won't.
I'm closing up for the day.
Oh. But the bookings...what do I say?
Whatever you like.
Come on, I want to get my cards.
Vinnie. Yeah sorry, didn't hear it, I was working. No, everything's fine. See you later okay? No, I can't wait either. GO
You've had all weekend.
I'll do it later.
That's what you said yesterday. I know what it's like with boxes of things. They stay there until you move house again.
Anything else?

Yes actually I'd appreciate it if you didn't play your music so loud after I've gone to bed. Late nights are a bad habit to get into. Especially once you start working again. I don't mean to nag you Chelsea, but I promised Denise I'd look out for you. You understand that, don't you? Oh. And make sure you're home by seven. You're on a curfew, remember?
How could I forget?
I shouldn't leave him on his own...
Steven's worked there before ain't he? He can manage. Half and a white wine thanks. How do you reckon he's doing?
Fine.
Good. I think we should make it permanent.
What?
Reckon it's time he joined Team Beale. Help build up the empire.
Tanya.
Did I say you could talk to me?
I know you hate my guts, but you shouldn't punish Sean for it.
That right?
I shouldn't have said what I did.
Did me a favour. That's a first.
No look...I didn't realise how much he liked you. But he really does... Please. Give him another chance will you?
He's a
Just let him talk to you. I'm sure if you did you'd...
That's rich. A slut like you trying to give me advice.
You ain't exactly top prize. I'd take what I can get if I was you.
If you were me? You tried that once remember?
Well where is it?
Hmm?
The jacket?
I thought it was on the chair.
Why would you put my cards in the pocket anyway?
Because I was going to bring them back to you tonight.
What you doing home?
Have you seen my jacket? It was here.
Yeah.
You should have told me.
No, you should have checked.
Look I'm...
You've messed everything up.
Abi...
I'm going to Grandma's after school with Lauren! It's better there.
What you doing sitting here? You're missing a sale.
Can't do this Dad. Thought I could, but...
I know it's not easy but...
It just don't feel right. I'm not Kevin. It's like I'm taking the Mick even trying.
Son...
Everywhere I look I see him, his stuff.
It's bound to take time.
No! I ain't doin' it.
How's my favourite girl then? Shirl...?
I'm not married!
Liar.
I'm not. Hayley ain't my wife...
Girlfriend, bit on the side. What's the difference? You're still cheating.
I'm not, I swear...
I can swear an' all. And then I can break your legs.
Shirl...
I don't wanna hear it.
She's my daughter you stupid tart!
Who you calling stupid?
Ah this is so sweet.
Yeah, I could really see Louise in it. Suppose I should give ‚em away. Seems a shame.
Maybe Honey could use ‚em eh? Put ‚em away for Janet. Aunt Peg?
Sorry, it's just...I've never stopped thinking about her, hoping that one day she'd come back.
Come here.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: What are you doing hiding in here?

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: I'm not.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: Didn't think I'd see you tonight.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: Why?

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: Mitchell factor. Circling the wagons.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: No-one tells me what to do.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: Which is one of the things I like about you. We still solvent?

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: He's in pieces. So's Aunt Peg. If you'd seen her...

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: What can I do?

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: Phil thinks you set him up. That you knew Louise had a step-dad.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: He's so predictable.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: Did you Jack?

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: I did my bit. If Phil can't handle it, it's his problem.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: That's not an answer. It's all about scoring points with you two. Tit for tat. You win, he loses and vice versa. Boys playing their war games.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: No.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: You know what Jack? You can wind each other up till your ears start to bleed for all I care.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: But there's a six year old girl stuck in the middle of this, and that ain't right.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: Ronnie wait.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: You're on your own from now on. I'm taking a break.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: From this place? Or from me?

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: You're the cop. You work it out.
Can I help you?
Just want Ben.
He's having his tea.
That's alright. I'll have a red wine while I'm waiting thanks.
Thanks for that Heather.
She was just looking out for me.
Sorry.
S'okay. You're a good mate.
How about I get us all fish and chips to celebrate?
I can think of better ways.
Go on then.
Don't you believe me?
Can't see why you'd keep quiet about it.
I was taking it one step at a time. Didn't want to blow it...especially after what's happened. I mean you being so upset and...
How's having a daughter blowing it?
Baggage innit? In my pea-brained way I thought it'd put you off.
You're right. You are a pea-brain.
Oi! What you doing?
You do believe me, don't you? Why would I even try it on with another bird when I've already won top prize? Eh dolly chops? Come on, give a bloke a break...
Any other surprises up your sleeve?
Apart from the sex change?
Vinnie.
Alright, listen...
Help! Help me. Quick!
It's Hev. Come on.
Let go.
I'm making a Citizens arrest. You're nicked.
Help.
Call the old bill.
Ain't got my mobile.
He was nicking your car.
I wasn't.
Right you.
Nice to see you too Vinnie boy.
You know him?
Well...
He should do. I lent him my car. A week you said!
What?
Yeah I was gonna...
While I'm at it, I'll have my house keys as well.
Is this like one of those Candid Camera things?
Shut it Hev.
Oscar okay? Good. Thanks for feeding the girls Dot. I won't be long, I promise. Ben! Can you move it please? Got better things to do!
What is so important?
It's about his Doctor Who whatsits. Got a bit upset.
Sorry?
Why don't I just pop up...
Don't think so.
What's all this shouting about?
Wanted to apologise to Ben about washing his cards. He can get himself some more.
Two quid?
Alright Peggy, don't get your knickers in a twist. Oops.
Steady on sailor.
Yeah, ain't got me sea legs.
What do you think you're doin'?
Told you, I came to apologise.
You're half cut.
No. Only had the one.
In here maybe.
Don't have a go at me. How much can those stupid cards cost anyway?
Leave it. Tanya love, you've got two kids and a newborn baby.
I think you'd better get home to them, don't you?
They're at Dot's if you must know.
I'd go and sort yourself if I was you. You're not a very pretty sight.
Can't we talk about this?
Talking's over Vin.
Richie, Rich, Dick... Hey...
I can explain...
Your mate did that. Ex-mate.
It's not what it looks...
Yes it is! You're a loser as well as a liar.
He ain't worth it Shirl.
No, he ain't.
I didn't know you were my Auntie. I thought you were Mum's friend.
Can't I be both?
Did you come to see Oscar?
Not exactly. Alright Lauren?
Where's Mum?
Having a lie in.
Is that why you're here? To look after her?
Does she need looking after?
Come on.
No, you stand there. Here you go in front ‚cos you're the littlest.
Ian! Will you stop it?
It's a big deal for me Jane. I want it to be right. Lucy hurry up. Trust you to oversleep.
Because someone kept me awake half the night.
Here.
Why are we doing this now?
Why are we doing it full stop?
I've got all my family together at last. Beale and Co. Come on, smile.
It's not high enough Dad. It'll cut our heads off.
No it won't.
How long we gotta stand here?
This is stupid.
Rainey? Rainey!
Just remembered why I hate housework.
Why are you still here?
Make your mind up sis. You were blubbin' all over me last night.
I was drunk.
Gathered that.
Whatever I said...
Called Max everything under the sun. And he's not around. So it don't take a genius to work out.
Yeah well, you ain't that.
I'm right, ain't I?
Yeah, give yourself a pat on the back. Anyway, whatever you're after, you're wasting your time.
That's not why I...
Really? What happened Rainey? Money I gave you run out? Couldn't find another mug to ponce off?
Suppose I deserved that.
Count it. It's all there.
Darren.
Thought you were going to the library?
I am.
Don't let him distract you too much.
Think I could have some of that money Mum left?
What for?
Does it matter?
Well I know Denise wouldn't want you to waste it on non-essentials.
I'm not. I need some new make up.
Might not be essential to you but it is to me.
Listen Chelsea. Me and Patrick will do our best for you and Libby, but it might be time you thought about getting a job.
Yeah but...
Then you wouldn't have to ask, would you? GO
You're giving it up?
You tell me how I'm supposed to stand there, selling cars like nothing's happened. He's gone Lib.
Yeah. But you just have to remember all the good things, all the laughs you had together. That's what I do anyway.
How about you come back to school?
Don't think so.
Then maybe you shouldn't be too hasty. You love that place...
Not anymore.
He okay?
Yeah.
Looks like Max.
Thanks for the money. I'm sorry I...
So you gonna tell me what happened?
Don't matter.
You stumbled out of the pub, on your own, in a total state. That ain't you Tan.
Everyone has their moments.
Maybe, but not you. Not since you've had kids anyway. I'll have one thanks. So what was it eh? Max tell you off for buying the wrong coffee?
Something like that.
You know I've never been one for guessing games...
Okay. You really wanna know? He's been having it off with a girl half his age, who also happens to be his daughter-in-law. Happy now?
Shirley! I know you're there. I saw the curtain twitch! I need to talk to you. Hello, dolly. Gonna let me in?
Been going on for ages...right under my nose. Lied to my face Rainey.
Even for him that's...
I trusted him and he completely betrayed me.
What a git.
Anyway...he's gone now. It's over. I'm fine. Alright. Getting there.
Good job I turned up when I did.
What? It's obvious you could do with some help. Even Abi said...
And who's gonna help you? Last time you were in this kitchen I caught you shooting up.
I don't do that anymore.
I'd rather you left.
Jack. No. I can't. Why would I change my mind?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Why would you walk away from your business? You're the one making it personal...
I swear to you Tan, I'm clean now.
If I had a penny for every time...
I'm not saying it is was easy alright? But it's the truth.
What would you know about the truth?
After I left here...I kept seeing your face...that look...the disappointment. Couldn't wipe it out. So I got myself into a programme. Somehow managed to stay the course.
Rainey...
Hardest thing I've ever done.

Would been so easy to give in. But the thought of being normal for the first time in years...Doing normal things, boring stuff...I'm taking one day at a time, but I'm free now Tan, and it feels great.
I've got the kids to think about.
What do I have to do to convince you?
I've got to get to the Salon.
I'll come with you.
No...
I wanna try being an Auntie.... And a good sister for a change...Keep me out of trouble. Please?
Least she could have used warm water.
Surprised it wasn't a brick. Why did you let her think you were loaded?
‚Cos I'm an idiot.
No argument there. Talk about asking for trouble. You were bound to get caught out.
However it looks, I wasn't trying to con her Hev. Straight up. I felt really bad about it. I mean at first it wasn't important, and then when I started to fall for her...
Really?
Yeah...I knew I had to come clean.
So why didn't you?
I was about to when Rich turned up and all hell broke loose.
You should be telling Shirl this, not me.
And get another soaking?
Be worth it if she listened.
No. She hates me. I've blown it.
Didn't realise you had a sister. You never said.
Didn't I?
Nice to have that support eh? Take me and my Garry. Might have our differences, but we close ranks if someone has a go. Stand solid. That's what families are all about, innit?
Think someone needs changing.
Here.
You're busy. I'll do it.
Staying are you?
I don't know.
Make it quick, I'm busy. Emergency...? What do you mean? Hev?
Shirley?
Gotta go.
Had a skinful before she came in I reckon. Bit of a sad sight to be honest.
And she's telling me to stay away from the kids.
Well done Keith. You should leave her alone.
That right?
Oh, look, that weren't meant to be ammunition...
No it's fine. I need to know if she's behaving like that.
Unfaithful husbands have that affect on women, didn't you know?
You don't have a clue why I...
You're a Branning ain't you? Wouldn't trust you as far as I could throw you.
Hev? Heather?
Here you go. Strong and sweet, just like me.
You've gotta be joking. Heather! Let me out of here.
Calm down will you?
Why should I?
I'll have you!
Let me say my piece and if you still hate me, I'll go and I won't bother you again. Cross my heart and hope to die.
Makes two of us.
See you next month. Not again. Haven't you got anything better to do?
Just had a very interesting conversation with Keith Miller.
Good for you.
How's the head this morning?
Fine, why?
He reckoned you were tanked.
We're not together now. What I do is none of your business.
My kids are my business, and if their mother's incapable of looking after ‚em...
He's asleep at last...
What is she doing here?
Looking out for your family. Like you should have done instead of getting your leg over.
Is she staying with you?
I'm over here Max.
I don't want you within ten feet of my kids. Do you hear?
What are you gonna do about it?
Rainey.
I knew this'd happen. You were never good enough for her. Slimebag.
The junkie's calling me names?
Get out. Now.
How you supposed to do this?
Get on with it, will you?
Sorry. If I'd said I was potless and squatting in a mate's house, you'd have run a mile.
What you've got or ain't got don't matter to me. Fact is, you lied about it.
D'you need a hand climbing down off that high horse of yours, Miss Whiplash?
I know you made out your neck to be worse than it was to con money out of me.
That's different.
Really?
Yeah. You mowed me down. You were fair game.
Okay, I know I did it all wrong. I was gonna tell you.
When?
Eventually.
Right.
You want the truth?
That'd be nice.
I was terrified. I'd only just got close enough to you without having to wear body armour.
It felt special right from the off, and I didn't wanna jinx it. I'm so sorry.
If you're done, I've got a job to get back to. Don't look like no millionnaire's gonna whisk me away.
No wait.
What else is there to say?
I havefeelings for you and I know you have feelings for me. These feelings come along once in a lifetime - if you're lucky.
You what?
You're tough and scary but I need to be with you.
Vinnie I...
Don't say anything now. Just think about it and meet me later okay?
Hev! Open up.
Look I'll be outside the tube, athalf seven. If you don't come I'll get the message and...we'll call it quits. What do you say?
Gotta get back to work.
She didn't say no.
Didn't say yes either.
Hi. How's it going at the Trueman's?
Apart from wishing I was back at Pat's? Fine.
Want something?
Don't suppose there's any jobs going?
Sorry Chelsea.
Yeah there is. But it's only part time.
That's okay.
You'd be on your own but it doesn't get that busy in here at night.
Night?
Hang on Steven.
I'm not looking for a night job.
Better than nothing.
No thanks.
Suit yourself.
I will.
What do you think you're doing? I'd already said no!
Dad said we needed someone.
You've only been here five minutes. Anyway it's not down to you.
I was only trying to help.
Can't stand to breathe the same air as me now?
Don't kid yourself.
Why run away in that case?
I'm not. Vic's short-handed. Promised I'd help.
Sorry if I make you feel uncomfortable.
You don't.
I meant about Phil.
I know that.
Maybe I made a mistake by getting involved, but I knew how huge it was for him. Missing out on all those years ... watching his kids change, grow.
I wouldn't wish that on anyone.
Jack...
But you're right. Phil hates my guts, and you don't deserve to be in the middle of it.
Hi, yeah. I need to talk to someone. It's about my kids. I think they're in danger.
Do we have to?
Just need to post a birthday card. Won't be a sec. Got a stamp here somewhere.
If you're talking monetary value it is a good deal. Depends what's important in life though, dunnit?
What is he doing?
Sorry?
Personally I'd rather go back to travelling on four legs than four wheels. Lot less pollution for one thing.
Oh no.
Least you can stick the by-product of a horse on your roses eh? I believe it was Salinger who once said...I'd rather have a horse. Least it's human. I'm paraphrasing of course...
Dad!
I've been at it for hours, but no joy...
‚Cos you ain't got a clue!
Granted.
I'll take over.
You sure? Only I don't mind muddling through.

It ain't like that. You've gotta know what you're doing. Sorry to keep you waiting Sir. It's got a full service history and nine months MOT. Low mileage. One paranoid owner. Pensioner. Never went above twenty.
Ronnie.
Before you get too excited, I'm here for the hens, not you. If you've forgotten the hen party Jack...
No, course not.
So everything's under control?
Yeah. Now that you're here. Thanks Ron.
If you print out that photo for me later, I'll get a couple of frames. Thought we could put one up in the chippy as well as the cafe.
You know I've been thinking. You might be better off working in the Chippy.
Why?
Yeah I like the cafe.
But we're fully staffed. What with us two and Marie.
We can move things around.
Alright, but it'd save us a wage. Wouldn't have to employ so many outsiders. Plus it's a better job. You could be Assistant Manager.
There isn't one.
Exactly. It's about time we had someone in there in a position of authority.
Ain't a bad idea as it happens.
Stop stalking me.
Just thought I'd walk you home.
Why? So you can give me another ear-bashing about Saint Vinnie?
We both know he's not that.
At last.
But he is good looking, and he's soft inside Shirley. Really soft. And vulnerable. If you think about it, that's why he did what he did.
That must be it. Soft as sh...
George would understand how Vinnie feels. ﬁI'm never gonna dance again. Guilty feet have got no rhythm.ﬂ
Don't you dare George Michael me!
He ain't perfect, but neither are you and he loves you Shirl. Why not meet him eh? See where it leads you. Only get one chance don't we? All of us.
Is Auntie Rainey staying?
Dunno.
She's not like you.
No.
Seems alright. Although she was supposed to be getting me a drink ages ago. GO
Rainey!
Sorry. I'll take it outside.
Right.
If you don't trust me, just say it.
I don't trust anyone.
I know you've been let down. By me, by Max...
You don't know the half of it.
It won't happen again. I might have failed you in the past, but...
Listen to me. You need to stay strong for whatever Max throws at you, and believe me he will. You're my sister and you need me.
For once in my life I can be useful Tan. Let me prove it. Let me stick around.
Hello ladies. Welcome to R&R. Hope you're ready to have a good time?
Depends how good the stripper is eh Caro?
I'm sure he'll push all the right buttons. The VIP room's all set up for you, if you‚d like to go through. Champagne cocktails on the way.
C'mon girls!
Jack?
Shouldn't the stripper be here by now?
Didn't you ring to confirm?
Didn't you?
Jack.
I've had other things on my mind.
Yeah me too.
See I think that one says, ‚Rip it off and take me'...whereas this one says...
Shut your big gob.
No it's more..'I'm no spring chicken, but I can still get away with it.' Oh you meant..right. What time you meeting him again?
Got ages yet.
Not seen you wear that before.
No. Kevin gave it to me when we first hooked up.
Let me see? Better get your slap on. You gotta have faith, right?
Yeah.
Where's my stripper? Got a bottle of baby oil to rub on him, ain't you?
He's...been delayed.
Not very good is it?
He'll be here.
I don't want the blushing bride to be disappointed.
She really does, doesn't she?
Now look...
No-one's gonna be disappointed, I promise you. Next round for these ladies is on the house. Whatever you like.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: ...I know it's short notice but we're desperate. You can? Oh mate...I really owe you one. Get him over here asap will you? French Maid? Ain't a tranny actis he? I told you, I don't want a woman, I want a bloke! Yeah very funny.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: Well?

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: Tried everyone. Nothing.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: We can't blow this Jack. Their company could send a hell of a lot of business our way. It could make us.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: Where are you going?

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: Let you down. Sorry Ron.

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: You're not leaving me to deal with it... Jack!

Scene_info: R AND R OFFICE INT NIGHT
Line: I'm sorting it!
How do I look?
He'll fall in love with you all over again. Ow.
Don't wait up. Hev. What's the time?
Nearly quarter past eight.
Crap!
Don't ask.
What you doing in here so late? Your dinner's in the dog. Couldn't stop him... Darren?
Threw it in the bin. Now it's gone.
Son...
Reminded me of Kevin, and I couldn't stand it. But then I realised...it'd be worse to forget him. I'm so stupid.
It's alright.
No! Bin's been emptied. I'll never get it back.
This what you're after?
How...?
Saw you sling it yesterday. Thought you might change your mind.
Vinnie!
How about some games eh? You know...truth or dare, guess what's in the handbag, consequences...
There'll be consequences alright.
Where have you been? They're gonna walk in a minute.
Ladies. Would you like to take your places for the show?
Jack... you're not... ?
Told you I'd sort it, didn't I?
I love you Shirl. Kiss me Vinnie. Just being soppy. What you doing on your own?
Wonder myself sometimes.
Where's Vinnie?
Wonder how many's in there eh?
Dunno.
Funny innit? Take ‚em off one by one and you could snap ‚em, no problem. But look at that. Look how strong it is? Like a rock. ‚Cos they're working together see?
Wouldn't mind a private show some time.
I'm not a stripper.
Who cares?
Sorry sweetheart, I'm taken.
My mobile. If you change your mind. Night.
Yeah, bye.
You laughing up there Kev? You cheap sod.
Girls have gone away happy. Am I a genius or what?
Ain't it illegal? Using your old uniform like that?
You gonna dob me in?
Maybe I should. So, how did you manage to talk Neil into it?
Let's just say he's expecting a bit extra in his pay packet this month.
Lucky it wasn't ripped to shreds. Women eh? whoever called 'em the weaker sex was having a laugh. The look on your face... you thought it was going to be me, didn't you?
Wouldn't put it past you.
You disappointed?
As if.
Could give you a private show if you like. Come on, I'll let you wear my hat.
Idiot.
Stay. ENDS
You're not getting up to make me breakfast, are you. It was a mistake, right? We shouldn't have done it and let's forget it ever happened.
Something like that.
What if I don't want to? What if I want this to happen again?
You'll be disappointed.
He got you in the end then. He said he would. I thought you were smarter than that but... What do I know?
Not a lot.
Regretting it already though - I know that much. It's 4 am. You're either going cos he's slung you out or cos you've just realized how big a mistake it was.
Yes, that's what I need, Max. Insight. From the man who slept with his son's teenage fiancee -
They weren't engaged when it started. Yes, I know.I'm everything Tanya's called me. I do know that.
And this new found awareness means you'll never cheat on her again. Right?
You don't think much of me, that's fine. I'm just waiting for the moment you realize Jack's even worse.
It's good you're so grateful to him. Helping you out, putting a roof over your head -
He's just storing up credit, that's all. Making sure everyone knows he disapproves but then taking me in anyway - cos I'm family. That great East End myth we all peddle - like the hypocrites we are.
Say the same thing to Tanya, would you? If she asked you to come home? You're right. We're all hypocrites, Max. But it's what you do about it that counts.
I forgot something.
What's that?
This.
Oh. Sorry. D'you mind? I'm bursting.
No, go ahead.
