Thanks. I've got a bladder the size of a pea at the moment.
No. Albert. Albert, come back. Albert.
Albert? Albert, where are you? Albert. Here boy.
What are you doing? Where's Honey?
She's in the loo. Shhh, will you?
Why, what do you want?
I'm trying to get Albert. He sneaked in. Well, help me look for him then.
I ain't got any clothes on. Get out, will you? What's Honey going to think if she finds you in here?
Well, she ain't going to think that. We're cousins.
Cousins can still do it. It ain't illegal or nothing.
Eugh. Is that what you think about?
No.
That's disgusting.
It's not what I think about - I've just been telling you to get out, haven't I?
Billy? What's happening?
Nothing. I promise.
You left the door open - Albert's in here somewhere.
No, he's in the kitchen, drinking some water. I just saw him.
Well, he must've gone out again. I just got a bit worried. You know, with the kids.
No, it's best to be safe. Sorry, Billy, I was half asleep. Thanks Roxy. Oh, isn't she lovely? That was really considerate. I love being here. It's like we're one big happy family, isn't it?
It's ruined. Everything. I keep telling him not to touch it. It's make-up, not paint, you moron.
Lucy -
Well, I want it replaced. You made me share a room with him so you're going to have to buy me all new stuff. There's the school disco tomorrow, I can't go without make-up.
You're too young for make-up.
No, I'm not.
It says here the trials for the Regional schools athletic team will be held next month. Did you know that? We'll have to really boost your training schedule - get you ready in time.
Hello? Still talking. Can we solve my problem first?
This letter's addressed to me. You can't open my post.
Ian.
It said Walford Harriers on the envelope. I'm his coach, aren't I? It's ridiculous. We've only got a few weeks. They should give us more notification than this.
They did. He hid the last letter. He doesn't want to do it anymore.
What?
He doesn't want to be an athlete. He just wants to hang out with his mates. And Lauren.
Shut up, will you?
So what you would have spent on all his running stuff you can give to me for my make-up.
Peter? Wait.
Fifty quid should cover it. It'll get me the basics anyway, tide me over til the weekend.
I'm sure it would. But since Bobby was the one who ruined it, ask him for the money. Okay?
Alright, that's enough disco practice. School.
Ten second freak out to finish up. Go.
That wasn't ten seconds.
Close enough. You'll wake Oscar up. Come on. Move.
I'll pick up some dinner on the way back.
Are you coming with us then?
Yes, course I am. I haven't seen your school yet, have I?
It's pretty rank.
Couldn't be worse than the one me and your Mum when to - it had rats running everywhere.
No, it didn't.
Well, alright boys - same thing though, isn't it? Your Mum punched one in the face once for being mean to me. Made his nose bleed.
And got punished for it too - Because hitting people isn't right.
Except when they deserve it.
Go on. Go and get educated. Properly. Bye love.
Bye Mum.
See you.
I'll pick up your dry cleaning too. I've got the stubs.
Rainey? Thanks.
No, I'm the one who's grateful.
What have you forgotten?
Mrs Branning? Derek Evans, social services, d'you mind if I come in? It's about your sister, Lorraine.
Hey, get back to bed. This is meant to be a surprise.
It's that, alright.

Yes, well, make the most of it. It's your turn next time. If there is a next time, obviously. Which I am in no way presuming. Cos we're business partners, and still very respectful of each other's boundaries -
Shut up.
Whoah, slow down - we've got an audience, remember. Max won't say anything, will he?
You're going to have to tell your family sometime.
When there's something worth telling them about. Yes.
I won't lie about it. If people ask, I'm going to say what's happened.
No, you'll say, ask Ronnie. I deserve that much respect at least.
And what sort of respect are you showing me?
I'm still here, aren't I? Don't push me faster than I want to go. It's my family. My rules. Okay?
How d'you want your eggs? Scrambled or fried?
Poached.
How Ronnie can sleep through this racket beats me. ‚S like being in a zoo. Oh, don't bring that in here, I'm eating my breakfast.
‚S okay, I'm going to take the whole thing out. Hold up. You couldn't lend us a tenner, could you, Phil? We've run out of nappy bags.
And nappies. There's only two left.
Better make it a twenty, eh?
I'll pay you back.
Got a job then, have you? Here, Roxy, why don't you get them for him?
Eh?
Give Billy here time to phone the council. Start hassling them about getting some proper housing.
Oh right. Yes. Anything that helps that.
I am trying. I've been phoning twice a day already.
Make it four times. Squat in their office if you have to. Just get a result. Soon.
That's how everyone feels, is it? What happened to Peggy saying we could stay as long as we like?
Yes, well, you don't have sordid sexual fantasies about Peggy, do you? Or do you?
No. I don't have fantasies about anyone. Just Honey, alright? And not sordid ones neither. Nice ones. Oh, what's the point? Here, I'll get them. Don't put yourself out on my account.
Well, what do you think?
You look fantastic.
I know. ‚S lush, isn't it?
Must've cost you a fortune.

A serious businessman needs a serious suit. It sends a message to the punters - quality cloth, means quality cars. Well, not that pile of junk, obviously. I'll be getting some new stock in soon as Pat sorts out the paperwork. And I'm booking us a table at Fargos to celebrate.
What, for tonight?

No, lunchtime. I'm busy tonight. Wear something better than that though. Oi, you don't have to walk to the shops, darling, get yourself one of these beauties , stick it all in the boot. Price goes down when you smile, remember. I spoke to her yesterday. Says she might be around here for a while. She'll crack eventually.
Quality patter like that. I don't doubt it.
Nah, it's just business. You're my girl, Libby. Always. Fargos. One O'clock. Yes, mate.
Hey Tan, I'm back. I got mince. Thought I'd make shepherds pie.
That sound like a screwed up drug addict to you? Rainey, Derek Evans, social services. Max has told them you leave syringes everywhere and invite my kids to shoot up.
What? No, I'm clean.
I know. And so does Max. He's just stirring up trouble for the divorce hearing so he can fight me for custody - you must realize that.
That may be so but we have a responsibility to investigate any cause for concern, especially when a known drug user is implicated -
But I'm off the smack. I've been clean for months. Ask my key worker. Search me if you like. Search my room. I don't mind.
You see? Do you honestly think I'd let her anywhere near my kids if I didn't trust her - one hundred per cent?
Mrs Branning -
I prefer Ms Cross now, thank you. Or Tanya. Don't call me Branning.
I'm sorry, Tanya, but I still need to talk to Lorraine.
Talk away. Excuse me. I'm going to see to my son.
Hey Roxy. What's up?
Where are you? I've just been in your room, I thought you were still asleep.
No, I stayed at the club last night. I got really drunk, just crashed on the sofa there. I'm coming home now.
Oh right. Good night, was it?
No, nothing special. Bit knackered now though.
I bet. Jack's not the lightest person to lie under, is he?
Fartleks? What's that?
It's Swedish. Means ‚speed play'. It's an exercise programme to help Peter prepare for the school trials.
But he doesn't want to be an athlete.
Yes, he does. What he doesn't want, is to work at it. Which is where we come in. We're going to surprise him at school this lunchtime, take him for a first session in the park.
What about the chippy? It's my first day as Assistant Manager.
And what does a manager do? He delegates. Jane'll cover for you.
Peter is going to realize his potential whether he likes it or not. Same goes for the rest of you. Just be grateful he's first.
Look, I didn't plan this to happen. But I'm not going to apologize for it either.
Not even worth that, are we?
Oh, grow up. Don't make this out as some kind of choice I've made.
Isn't it?
Who I sleep with has got nothing to do with any of you.
So why lie about it?
Because of this. Look at you all. It's like I've hooked up with Jack the Ripper.
He's trouble.
Why is he? What has he ever done apart from try to help?
You think he helped Phil with Louise?
He bent over backwards trying - and then got punched in the face for his trouble. And he still wants to be with me. If nothing else admire him for that.
So are you two an item then? Are you going to keep seeing him?
I wasn't sure. But now? Yes, too right I am. At least til you lot can start being civil to him - you're the ones with the problem here, not Jack.
We don't trust him.
I don't care if you do or not. But it'd be nice if you trusted me. After all, I am family.

I'm training an Olympic athlete. Vitamin C is essential for muscle strength recovery. I need the highest quality oranges not this dried up old crap on the turn. I've told you before Wes, don't try and line your own pocket by selling rubbish. This is coming out your wages. What are you doing? Where are you going Wes?
Looks like you need a new stall worker.
Yes, previous candidates needn't apply.
Oh, come on Ian. Give me a break. I'm broke. We're still having to squat in Peggy's front room.
Doing everyone's head in, is it?
Like you wouldn't believe.
So why on earth would I want to end that?

Cos you're a decent human being, that's why. Or certainly used to be. Listen to yourself. He's on his uppers, homeless, two kids in nappies and you're standing there laughing at him? That how Kathy and Pete brought you up, is it? You think your uncle Arthur would have been proud hearing that?
Pat -

That stall used to mean something. And so did the people who worked on it. I thought that was the reason you bought it? Or did you only buy the wood, Ian? And all it's real heritage, well, that's just some nonsense from the past.
Okay, you're hired. For a trial period - see how we get on.
Thanks Ian. Thanks Pat.
Pleasure.
So what are you going to do for him? Or is it just me that's the Samaritan?
I've already offered, Ian. Billy can move his family in with me whenever he wants.
Eh?
I told Honey earlier. Stay as long as you like. I'd welcome the company. And you'd get a live in baby-sitter to boot.
Oh Pat, that's great. We'll do it. Yes. Thanks very much.
I'll get thespare rooms sorted in that case.
Thanks Pat. You're an angel. I'd better tell Honey to start packing.
You leave that stall, the deal's off. Tell her on your time, not mine. And it's minimum wage.
But that's less than I got last time. I'm more experienced now.
You don't like my charity, don't accept it. Do us both a favour.
She wants to invite Jack over for a drink tonight. See if we can all make an effort to get along.
What do you reckon? She serious about him or just enjoying pulling my chain?
No, she likes him, definitely.
And what about him?
He's a bloke, isn't he? You tell me.
I'd be more worried if it was Roxy with him. Ronnie's sharp, and she'll stay that way, no matter how much she falls for him.
No, I think it's good. She can keep an eye on him for us. Better we know what he's up to than not. What time's Jack coming over?
About eight. ‚S nothing major, few drinks. Phil, he just wants everyone to get on.
You sure about that?
You're the one I'm not sure of.
I won't deck him if that's what you mean.
Well, that's a start, I suppose.
I'm just trying to solve a problem you've caused, that's all. I ain't having my kids living with a drug addict.
Ex-addict.
There's no such thing.
You're the one with a drink in your hand.

Don't get so drunk the profits start to drop at Booty's, will you? Only when I get the kids, you'll have to start paying me maintenance - you do realize that, don't you? Go on. Slap me. Better that than you take it out on the kids.

Scene_info: CAR LOT, OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: That's it. You are now officially in charge of Getaway Motors. God help us all.

Scene_info: CAR LOT, OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: So where's the company cheque-book?

Scene_info: CAR LOT, OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: With me til you're eighteen. Let's not go mad just yet. Have a look at the books first.

Scene_info: CAR LOT, OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I have done, they suck. ‚S why we need some new motors, start boosting business again, get the funds coming in.

Scene_info: CAR LOT, OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Alright, slow down, okay? There's no quick fix in this game, not a legal one anyhow - that's how Kevin got into trouble. You've got treat this like a marathon, not a sprint. Start slowly, build gradually, you understand? Cos I can just as easily tear these up again, withdraw my consent.

Scene_info: CAR LOT, OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Pat, it's cool.

Scene_info: CAR LOT, OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: And no test driving the cars either - get Mickey to do that - your job is to pick and sell only.

Scene_info: CAR LOT, OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yes, I know.

Scene_info: CAR LOT, OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: And make sure you earn your commission before you spend it. I don't want to see a Lamborghini parked out there tomorrow. Or find you've bought yourself another suit, sharp as that is.

Scene_info: CAR LOT, OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Don't worry. You're going to be proud of me, Pat. I promise.

Scene_info: CAR LOT, OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I already am, love. You'll do the right thing, I know it.
Come on, you maggot - call that a sprint? I could crawl faster. Run! Time?
40 seconds.
40? You're meant to beat the previous time, that's the whole point.
Maybe he's ‚tired'.
Dad, I'm trying.
Not hard enough. I want you puking your guts up cos of the effort you've put into this - not standing there whinging about it. Come on, let's go again.
I can't.

What did I tell you? That is a banned word. We are not at home to Mr Negative. Now go back and try again. I'll untie you when you've beaten forty seconds and not before. He'll thank me for it later. That boy's a winner. He just doesn't know it yet.
What do you want?
Garry and Minty not about?
They're getting supplies, why?
No reason. I just wanted to drop by, let you know it's official. I'm in charge of the car lot.
‚S Pat's decision not mine.
Yes, I know, but she said she ran it by you first. Just to check you were okay with it. So thanks. I really appreciate it.
Yes, well, new start then, eh? Don't mess it up.
No. I won't. Although, we ain't got much stock. Or money neither.
Just enough for a suit, was there?
Looks good, doesn't it? Kevin always reckoned a good front got him more sales than a good motor -
Have you got a point to make cos you're starting to irritate me?
Phil, I don't know what I'm doing. I don't know what cars to get, where to get them -
Then learn. I ain't nurse-maiding anyone.
I don't want you to. I just need bit of a help, that's all. To get me started. Get some cash flow - see, I promised Libby I'd fly her out to join her Mum -
I ain't lending you any money -

No, that's not what I'm getting at. I meant more... Well, you know, that bloke, gave you those cheap cars, I thought maybe I could shift a few of those. Just for a bit, til I found my feet, got things ticking over -
You stupid little prat - you think I'm going to risk that again?
You gave them to Kevin.
Yes, and look how he ended up.
That's cos Kevin was an idiot. And I'm not. Just give me the chance and I'll prove it.
You know, when you blagged 200 notes off me to keep quiet about it, I thought then, he's a cool little sod alright. Got even colder now, ain't you?
I'm desperate. One car. That's all I'm asking.
Forget it. From now on that place is legit. No more stolen motors, no cut and shuts - you want to kill someone else, do you?
Okay, just give me the bloke's phone number. I'll arrange it without you.
He'd hang up as soon as you asked. It's too dangerous. The police nearly had us both the last time.
Just one car, Phil. Please.
You ask me again, I won't only have Pat kick you out of that job, I'll kick you out of that suit an all. Go on, get out of here.
Ian, look, she got an A+.
Ms Taylor said it was the best essay she'd read all year.
It's only January 10th.
She meant school year, dog breath. That's got to be worth some new make-up, hasn't it?
Ian?
Look, I'm trying to do this. Here, what are you eating? He can't eat crisps.
Why not?
Because it's not on the list. Only approved nutrition goes in that mouth. And what's she doing here?
We're going to do our homework together.
No. He's going to the gym. Do some Fartleks on the treadmill. Yes, the amusing Swedish word - you won't be laughing at the end of it, I tell you. Go on, get changed.
But I've got blisters from lunchtime - those running shoes really pinch -
So we'll stop at the sports shop on the way, get you a new pair. Go on, hurry up. And you. Come with me. I want a quick word.
Thing I don't get is, Pat said she'd spoken to you already.
That's right, she did. But we can't let Peggy and the others down, can we? They'd be heart broken.
No, I think they'd cope. We can't stay in this room forever.

No, of course not. We're going to get a place of our own place, soon as you've saved up. You've got a job now. But it's better to live here while we're waiting. With our family. That's what it's all about, isn't it?
But...we'll have more space there. And Pat loves little Janet -
Billy, come with me. Come on.
Hello love.
Hiya. I suppose Billy's told you all about Pat's offer.
Yes, that's really kind of her.
Move in tonight if you like. We'll give you an hand.
No, it's okay, I've already told her. It's not like any of you want us to go. I mean, you love having us here, don't you?
Yes, of course we do.
You see? It's family, isn't it? We can't walk out and leave them.
Well, no, but if it's better for you there -
Yes, more room, then we wouldn't stand in your way.
No, I know, but we want to stay here with you too. We love it. Don't we? You've really made us feel at home. It's really special. So, thanks everyone. We're going to tell Pat no. See I told you.
Well, what else could I say?
And then he bans me from the house. Says Peter's not allowed to visit here. Or go to the disco tomorrow - says he's got to train even though Peter hates it.
Well, there's an obvious solution, isn't there? Ow. Ow!
What's wrong?
I'm faking. Tell Peter to do that so he can't train then we'll offer to drive him to the disco - help cheer him up.
Ian still won't let him go.
He will if Tanya has a word with Jane. Get her to persuade him. Then you two can bop away all night. ‚S easy, isn't it?
Okay, I'll text him now.
Oi. Homework first. You can plan your social life later.
We make a good team, don't we?
Oh yes, I love being bad cop.

I'm helping though, aren't I? I really love it, Tan, being here. I was so scared when that social worker came round. All those lies Max said - I'm glad we got it sorted out. That it's not going to be a problem.
No. Although you know what would really settle it? If you took another drug test.
Eh?
Tomorrow. ‚S just a few minutes at the clinic. Get them to send the result over to social services, prove you're clean.
They know that anyway. They've checked. I had one done recently.
Yes, but you weren't living with me then. I want to send it to Max's lawyer. Stop any chance of him using it. You don't mind, do you? For me, Rainey. And the kids. Please?
Sure. Why not?
Thank you.
You're late.
Why, what did I miss?
Don't make me regret this.

Trust me. I'm good. How are you doing? Phil. Good to see you. Look, I'm sorry it didn't work out. With Louise. Just as long as you know - I was trying to help. Let's take that from it and move on, yes? Hey Roxy. Peggy.
So what would you like? Pint?

No. I'm not stopping. There's no point. This ain't about us all having a drink and pretending to like each other for a false half hour - it's about starting again. Properly. I've got to prove myself to you all. I know that. So I've just come here now to say, I hope you'll give me that chance.
Okay.
Whatever.
Takes more than words, mind.
I know. Thanks. Sorry but, like you said, best not to push people faster than they want to go.
No, you're right.
I'm going to go back and start preparing the club. Why don't you stay here for a bit? Talk me up. I think I need it.
And how. He meant it. You don't have to believe him but what he said then was true. He wants this to work. Just trust him on that, okay?
Nice suit.
So everyone reckons, yes. It's great. Thanks.
No problem. Not as long as you've earned it.
More than.
No more stolen motors. No cut and shuts - you want to kill someone else, do you?
You were right. I'm just a kid to him - he didn't suss me as a threat at all. That's Phil Mitchell in his own words - stitched up and ready for jail.
Morning sexy.
Coffee, please. Black, no sugar. I thought it was your turn to make breakfast?
Let's work up an appetite first.
What the hell is that?
Oats, packed with vitamin B, which helps metabolize carbs and fat to produce energy - an essential breakfast for the modern athlete.
So why do I have to eat it?
He bulk ordered. It was cheaper that way.
Ugh. I feel sick.
You're not pregnant, are you?
What?
Ian.
Sorry.
No, I'm sick of you. And his flipping athletics.
He gets new running shoes and what do I get? Ignored, same as always.
Ian, tell her. Lucy, wait. We are going to get you something. A new outfit. For the school disco.
Yes, I was really pleased about your grade. Thought I'd surprise you lunchtime. Take you shopping.
What about my training session?
I'm taking it. Cos Steven needs to be at his job.
If he ever gets up in time. He's like the flaming undead.
Can't I go shopping with Jane?
Make more sense, wouldn't it?
No. It's me you're having problems with - it'll be a chance for us to bond.
What about the make-up you owe me?
See, this is what I'm talking about.
Bobby ruined my last lot.
Whatever I do. It's just never enough, is it?
Alright, forget it. If I'm that horrible to be with, stuff your flipping outfit.
Lucy, wait -
Well, don't get at me. It was your stupid idea in the first place.
Have you got your swimming kit?
Yes, she has. Come on, I said I'd meet Peter in the cafe.
What about Rainey? Isn't she coming with us?
Not today, no. She's got a doctor's appointment - I expect you'll see her later.
Bye Rainey.
Bye Abi. See you Lauren. Have a good day. Good luck with your swimming badge. I bet you'll get it.
Can guinea pigs swim?
We'll drop Marge in the sink and find out - just shift, will you?
You go, I'm going with Ben.
Well, why didn't you say?
Be safe. Good luck.
Yes. Bye. Why didn't you wake me? I could've taken them.
No, you deserve a lie in - they'll be fine on their own. What time's your test?
Whenever. I just go to the clinic and get one.
And how long til they get the result?
20 minutes, half hour.
Well, don't forget to ask them to send it on to social services. That guy yesterday, Derek Evans, he'll be expecting it.
I've not done smack or coke for months, I promise -
I know. Rainey, this isn't about you. It's about Max.
Tell her to hurry up, can't you? Or get another loo. I can't go in the sink with you here. I'm kidding. What sort of bloke do you think I am?
A dead one if I catch you. How about you disinfect it while you're waiting?
Nah. ‚S woman's work, isn't it? Get Ronnie to do it.
You either clean that sink, right now, or get out.
Jack. Relax. I do not urinate in your sink. Okay?
But you like putting that thought in my head. Don't you?
Small man. Still needing his small victories. Even though it costs him his family.
Of course you can fake it. ‚S easy, look.
I didn't say, I couldn't, I said I won't. I can't lie to him.
But you'll miss the disco. It's just for one day -
Yes, but the trials are in a few weeks. If I skip a session -
Oh, turn it off, will you? He's not even here.
You're just jealous cos he believes in me. I ain't going to let him down like everyone else. Look, I've got to go.
Okay, I'll walk with you.
No, I've got to jog there, sorry - it's part of my training.
Don't worry, you can do way better than that loser.
I ain't going to the disco without him. There's no-one else there I like.
Not at the school one, no - but who wants to go there anyway? A load of spotty boys who can't even drive? I don't think so. We'll just jump a tube into Soho, go to a proper club.
What?
I'll nick some booze beforehand - vodka's best cos you can't smell it - you like vodka, don't you?
But my Mum's going to pick us up at school when it's over.
So tell her Jane's going to do it. I'll tell Jane, Tanya will - then we'll deal with the flak later.
You're such a virgin about everything. Don't worry. It'll be a laugh, I promise.
If you want to talk about me at least say it to my face.
Oh, get over yourself, this ain't about you and Jack.
It's about Honey. Not wanting to move into Pat's.
She wants to stay with us cos she thinks that's what we want.
It's not just that - she likes being part of the family, she thinks all of you are great.
Based on what?
Beats me, I tell you.
Well, she ain't exactly playing with a full deck, is she? No offence.
Or maybe she's just nicer than all you lot.
Nicer than you, that's for sure. Billy thinks about having sex with us. Tell Honey that she'd move out.
I do not think about having sex with you. Look, I am a happily married man.
Cousins can still do it, he said. Told me it wasn't illegal. You know, in case it was that holding us back. Yes, right.
You alright? Phil?
Yes. I'm fine. Look, let's solve this once and for all.
Billy, you can have Ronnie's room - Ronnie, you'll have to share with Roxy.
What?
Or get Honey to accept Pat's offer. It's up to you.
Well, he's in a good mood.
There is no way I'm sharing with you. I'm going to talk to Peggy.
Don't worry. You'll be in Pat's by the end of the day. Trust me.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Thanks for coming. This is better, isn't it? We can talk properly now. Say what we want to say. Rather than what people we care about want to hear.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: So all that crap you came out with last night -

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No, that was true. I do want us to get on. I like Ronnie, so obviously, it's in my interests. But it's not in your interests, is it Phil? You're thinking - why should I make the effort to get along with this cocky gitwho I don't even like.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yes, that about sums it up.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Here's why.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: One car. That's all I'm asking.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Forget it. From now on that place is legit. No more stolen motors, no cut and shuts - you want to kill someone else, do you?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Okay, just give me the bloke's phone number. I'll arrange it without you.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: He'd hang up as soon as you asked. It's too dangerous. The police nearly had us both the last time.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: And with all this new evidence - they still might.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You're a stupid man, Phil. You pick fights with people you know nothing about, with no understanding of how they might react. Well, you know now, don't you?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: That ain't nothing.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: It's enough. With what the police already have? More than. You sold stolen cars to Kevin Wicks who then died driving one - Yes, that's it. Keep thinking with your fists. Make it even easier for me, why don't you? No, there's no-one else here. And I ain't recording it neither, but you've had your cheap sucker punch. You want to go toe to toe when my back ain't turned, let's do it - see how long you last.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: What do you want?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: For the tape? Nothing. I'm going to give you it back. It's just a warning, Phil. Take me seriously. Treat me with respect.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: And that's it?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: That and the car lot, yes.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: What?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You're going to sell me the freehold for the car lot. At half the market price. As a way of apologizing. Let's call it a gesture of friendship.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Let's not.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: That's bad news for Ben, isn't it? Cos once I give that tape to the police, you won't be seeing him for quite a while.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You taking the long term view of all this?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: More than you ever did. See, I make it my business to know exactly who I'm dealing with, what they're capable of. Shame you never did the same. Just be grateful all I want is the car lot. You've got until 5pm.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I don't own that land.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I know. Peggy does. That's not my problem.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I tell Ronnie this, it will be. That's you and her over -

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You tell Ronnie this, the tape goes to the police. You threaten Darren, it goes to the police. This is just between you and me. To clear the air. Make things even between us. See, I really did try and help you with Louise, Phil, and now you owe me something in return. So why don't you phone your bent solicitor Ritchie Scott and start saving yourself while you still can.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You really want to do this?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I am doing it.
But this awful, I had no idea.
Me neither. Roxy only told me yesterday.
She's in love with my Billy?
Pretty much ever since we arrived. She said it was one of those, first sight, pow...
Well, yes, it was the same with me. When I looked at him, I could barely breathe, he was just so...
Isn't he. But don't you see? That's why it's been so hard for Roxy, to have you all living here - the man of her dreams. So close, so unavailable -
That's not why she was in our room the night before, was it?
It might well have been, yes. She did say she was finding it harder than ever not to tell him. Not to be near him. Touch him. Although she swears she never will.
So my Billy doesn't know?
No. No-one does. Just me. And now you. But you must never tell Roxy I've told you this - she'd be mortified.
Eh?
Very upset. Honey, Roxy loves you too, you're family and she would never do anything to hurt you - even though you being here, is like the worst form of torture -
Oh, my goodness.
It's cruel really. Not that any of you are to blame.
Well, no but even so... Oh poor Roxy. I know the power Billy has over people. Women especially.
I've felt it too.
It's not happening, I tell you. I am not sharing that box room with Ronnie - I just can't.
Okay. Just calm down.
No, you don't understand. I'd go mad. I'd kill her. I'd kill all of you, I know I would -
Well, none of us wants that now, do we? Look, I'm sure - Oh, hello Honey. No, don't worry, she's fine, Phil's upset her over something, that's all.
Roxy, I just wanted to say, we're going to go to Pat's. Today. I'm sorry but it's for the best. For everyone. I'm going to start packing straight away.
Don't be sad. You're a wonderful person and there will be someone else out there just as wonderful for you too. I know it.
Well, let's go and help her before she changes her mind.
So what are my options?
Without listening to the tape it's difficult to say - how incriminating, is it?
I basically admit I sold stolen cars, cut n shuts -
And this Darren boy who taped you? Why would he have done this?
He blames me for what happened to Kevin Wicks- they were pretty close.
So as well as the tape we can assume Jack's also got a statement from him? What about the man who sold you the cars - could Jack have got to him too?
No. Dougie's solid. It's just the tape and the kid.
And whatever forensics they have, plus all the circumstantial evidence -
You saying I should make a deal?
If you do - will he honour it? Give you the tape back?
After making a few dozen copies for the future, yes, why the hell not? If I fold once he can do it again, go for this place next.
Even so. My advice - for what's it worth - is to accept his proposition.
No way.
It buys us time. And gets us the tape. Even if it's a copy I can work out how damaging it is and find a way to limit that threat. It could even be inadmissable -
He ain't having that car lot.
Just think of it as a loan. You'll get it back -

Too right I will. That's my mother's property we're talking about. The only way he'll get to keep that permanently is if I bury him in it. Right next to Darren. No-one blackmails me and gets away with it.
Hello? Yes this is Lorraine Cross. Yes, I give my consent. Yes, tell her.
Hello? Speaking. Its about the drug tests results yes? And? And what does that mean? No, for me. And my kids, the court case, what does that... I see. Right. Yes, I will. Thank you. Bye.
Well? What did they say?
Peter. It's me. Just so you know. I'll be taking your training today as usual.
Ignore that, I'm still doing it, Ian's taking Lucy shopping as he promised.
After the way she spoke to me? I don't think so.
Remind me - which one of you's the hormonal teenager? Only it's hard to tell sometimes.
I made the offer, didn't I?
And it's not bonding if you then withdraw it. When did Peter ever get an A+?
You can't chuck me out. Not for that.
You said you were clean.
I am. It's just weed. Help me relax.
Marijuana is a drug, Rainey - you lied to me.
No, I didn't. I said I wasn't on smack or coke and I'm not.
Well, let's hear it for the class B drug addict. Congratulations on your down grade.

That as long as I didn't have it in the house, or smoke it near the children, it wasn't a problem and d'you know how I know that? Because I asked. When I took the test. Because I didn't want to be anything but a help to you. Tan, if I was a danger, a risk, I'd go. I promise. You wouldn't have to pack for me, I'd have left already.
He also said I should consult my solicitor. Which means there is a risk.
No.
You think Max's lawyer isn't going to use this? Try and turn it into something more substantial?
But if I'm clean. If I keep taking the tests -

They're so worried she'll slip, your honour, she has to be tested every week, that's how much faith her own sister has in her. I'm sorry, but I'm not taking any chance that jeopardizes me keeping my kids.
Tanya please -
You said, you'd go! If there was a risk. You just promised. So, what was that? Just you lying to me again, yes?
Tell the kids I said goodbye.
Rainey, wait. Look, why not stay til they get back? We can explain it together.
How I'm walking out on them as well? No, thanks. I'll visit them again after your divorce. If I'm still allowed, that is.
Of course you will be.
Don't worry, I'll bring a drug testing kit with me, so you can check me out beforehand -
Rainey, stop - I'm not shutting you out. You're still a part of this family.
It's just temporary, that's all. You've been amazing.
I've been clean, that's why. Fat lot of good that did me.
What's that supposed to mean?
What do you care?
No. Don't you dare slip back now. Don't you prove to me I was right to make you leave. You've got to prove to me that I'm wrong.
For whose sake, Tanya? Mine or yours?
Phil. Come and join us.
We're celebrating Billy's new place. He's moved in already.
Jack helped them.
Did it all, you mean. He's been a star. Cheers mate.
Phil, what are you drinking?
I'm good. Thanks.
Well, look a bit happy about it. Got your living room back again.
Mum, can I have a word?
Sure.
No pleasing some people, is there?
I still don't get why Honey changed her mind. It was a bit freaky really. She just came in, starting hugging me, saying she was going. She is safe, isn't she? You know, mentally.
Yes, course she is, you're the one who's deluded - thinking I imagine you two in the shower, that sort of thing. That's what's mental. What?
I've never said anything about a shower. Have you?
Nope. I think that one's all you, Billy.
You see, you're twisting my words. That's not what... There is no way... I've got to get back to the stall now, alright?
It's just some papers that need a witness signature. For Ben's trust fund. Ritchie's bringing them over this afternoon. You don't mind, do you?
No, of course not.
Hey Peggy? When you're ready. One more for the road, yes?
Coming up.
Phil, come and join us.
Yes, come on. He's really making an effort. You should do the same.
He's still breathing, isn't he?
Same again all round, only let's make it doubles - We're celebrating, after all - and you've got join us this time, Peggy. No excuses.

See, these old models - they're the future - classic design, just begging to be pimped up. Go on, get in there, fire that bad boy up, see how it sounds. Alright, Phil? How's it going? Got a sale here already I think.
Phil, what are you doing?
I'm wondering what your head'll look inside out.
Why, what's happened? What have I done?
Yes, Jack picked a good ‚un with you, didn't he? Enjoy it, did you? Playing me for a mug?
That punter outside, he saw you come in. He's probably calling the police now.
And telling them what? I ain't done nothing, Darren. Ain't going to either. Not yet.
If you're waiting for Jack, he's seeing Ronnie Mitchell now, sorry. Still, I doubt he'd want my cast-offsanyway.
Rainey's gone. I've told her to leave.
That's a shame. I expect she'll be visiting, mind.
No. No visits either. You'll have to find some other way to make me look like an unfit mother.
‚S not much of a challenge.
Abi'll be hurt the most. Lauren too, they really liked her. It's your children you're damaging. Again.
They're why I'm doing this.
Yes, you love that lie, don't you Max? ‚My kids mean more to me than anything' - except a quick romp with Stacey, of course.
That's a different thing entirely.
Why is it? You knew what you were risking. Your marriage. Your children's happiness, peace of mind - but you did it anyway.
I made a mistake. I've said that.
But you don't regret it. That's the thing. You don't regret Stacey. All you regret, Max, is getting found out.
No.

You did it, because you thought you'd get away with it. And deep down, you still do. You think one day I'll forgive you and then you can go back to playing the family man. Until the next girl comes along, of course. Which is why it won't happen. Not ever. Cos I'd hate to think how old that next girl would've been.
There's a lot of other places we could've gone. You sure you want to get something here?
Yes, why?
Well, it's a bit...
Bit what? Classy? Expensive?
Yes, they're exactly the words that spring to mind.
Ignore him. He's about 150. He peaked on style with his haircut. Oh, I like this. That's great.
Is there a finished version? One with sleeves and proper neckline.
Dad, shut up, will you?
Here. It goes with this skirt.
You mean, napkin. Don't you sell any actual clothes?
Does he have to be here?
If you want to get paid, yes he does.
We're meant to be bonding. You said I could choose an outfit.
An appropriate outfit. Do you work in a lap dancing club?
How do you know what lap dancers wear?
What? Do you mind? I'm talking with my daughter.
Yes, but how do you? Have you been to one?
I said, choose something else.
No. I want to buy this.
Tough. There is no way I'm paying good money for that.
Whoops. I suppose he'll have to now.
It's a designer label. ‚S forty five.
Pounds? Right, that is coming out of your pocket money.
Fine.
And you're grounded. There's no disco tonight. D'you hear me?
Nothing like a bit of bonding, is there?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: But what's he doing still out? I thought he'd be arrested, that's what you said would happen.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I know. Change of plan.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: What?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You might have mentioned Phil had bribed you beforehand. 200 notes to keep quiet? That makes you an accomplice, you muppet. I give that tape to the police now you two'll be sharing a cell - is that how you want this to go? Well? Look, you wanted revenge for Kevin, right?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yes. And just that. Make Phil pay, I said.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: And that's exactly what he's going to do. He's going to pay by giving you the car lot. The freehold, it's yours. That's right. He'll sign it over to me first, then I'll give it to you when you're 18.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: If I get to 18. Which right now ain't looking very likely.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Don't worry. He can't touch you.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You think?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Trust me.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yes, I've done that and look where it's got me. I've got psycho Phil Mitchell on the loose wondering which part of my body he's going to crush first.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Darren, listen -

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You promised me he'd go down, that he'd be arrested straight away, you said that, that I wouldn't be in danger, you said they might not even have to use the tape at all -

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Just get a grip, okay? Look at me. You're going to be fine. Phil won't hurt you. I guarantee it. Now sit down. And listen up, cos what you decide here Darren, is going to determine how the rest of your life goes.
Yes, hold on, let me read it.
No, I've done all that. I just need your signature. Get it back over to Ritchie. She's got to get it finalised before the weekend.
I thought we'd done all the trust fund stuff - is this a new one?
No, it's something to do with the new tax laws, bottom line, it's saving us money.
Well, I'm all in favour of that. Where is it? Here?
Yes. And down here.
Well, lift it up a bit, I've got to see what I'm doing.
That's great, thanks.
Don't mention it. Got to protect our future, haven't we?
Absolutely.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I chose you for a reason, Darren. You're ambitious, motivated and you've got a world of guts - not many people would've agreed to take Phil Mitchell on. But you need to prove to me you can live with the pressure of the choices you make. Do that, and you'll be owning a lot more than a crappy car lot in a few years time. See, what I'm offering you here, is an apprenticeship. If you can't handle it just say so now. I'll give you some money, you can head off, start again somewhere else. Or you can accept the risk, stay here, and learn how to really play the game. It's up to you. That or this. What are you going to do?
William's asleep and Pat's reading Janet a story - it's so lovely seeing them together, she's really taken with Pat already.
I told you, didn't I? I mean, I know you liked it at the Vic but this is better for us -
Yes, I should've listened to you earlier, Billy. I'm sorry.
No, you had your reasons, good ones too but... Why did you change your mind?
Billy, you're so special. You have no idea what you do to people, have you? The effect that you have.
Eh?
You've got to be very nice to Roxy from now on, d'you hear?
Yeah? Why's that then?
Well, let's just say I'm not the only girl who's heart you've stolen. If you hadn't chosen me Billy I'd be suffering just as much so don't you make things any worse for her, okay? I love you.
What are you looking at?
Nothing. ‚S okay, I get it now. Sorry. I should've realized.
It's just a slight sprain, I took him to the doctors - there's nothing to worry about -
I can start training again on Monday.
Monday? That ruins my entire schedule.
Yes, well the doctor had a few words to say about that as well. He advised that we consult someone qualified, get more expert advice.

Recommend someone, did he? His mate I expect, probably gets a back hander for all referrals - see, those coaches, they do it for the money, but me, I'm doing this for Peter. Ain't that right, son? Sorry.
No, he's really injured, he's not faking and I've been grounded so you'll have to go on your own.
You're late.
So call the police.
What are you having?
Now? Or eventually.
See, that's sharp. I like that. We could really get on, you and me - if you just gave us a chance.
You're right. I didn't treat you with any respect. Now I know who I'm dealing with, I'll play things differently. Okay? Tape.
That's the original - on the memory card. And that's the copy I made for the sound system this morning.
That better be the only copy. You come asking for something else, you know what you'll get.
Like I said, this makes us even. All I want now, Phil, is your friendship. You need a favour from me, it's yours. Just ask. That's how this thing should work.
I'll bear that in mind.
No hard feelings then.
New slate.
Long term view.
Long term view. CLIFFHANGER
Are you working tonight?
Yeah. We've got some networking event for Eastend business people. Invitation only.
I know!
Where did you get that?
It's Mum's.
Isn't stealing someone else's post like a hanging offence in your line of work?
I didn't steal it. She insisted I have it!
How come?
Mum wants me to share ideas with fellow professionals and potential employers.
Well, there won't much of that going on, let me tell you.
It's just an excuse for everyone to cop off.
She's even bought me something new to wear!
That's just unfair. And I'm gonna be stuck behind the bar all night.
With blokes lining up for your attention!
Yeah to buy other girls drinks.
Oh well, there's always Mr. Monosyllabic.
Someone who doesn't say much.
Jase? Man of little words, even
We're over him then?
Yeah totally.
Excuse me, I think I was first. Job applications.
Sorry, wait your turn, Dawn.
So, I can expect a quiet night then?
It's not really the Vic's trade we'vre targetting, Aunty Peg.
Ta very much.
If I don't over-charge the City lot they won't think they're having a good time!
One for the price of two, eh!
Yeah.
The bathroom was free ages ago.
Yeah. Fantastic innit, not having to wade through stinking nappies? Although I will miss Billy you know. Such an easy target.
You two didn't say anything to drive them away now, did you?
Don't know. Don't care.
You're an Eastend business woman, Aunty Peg. Why don't I leave your name at the door. Family discount on drinks!
Brilliant!
Roxy can look after the bar for a couple of hours.
Roxy's going out. Boat trip. Dinner. Dancing. My call apparently!
Who do you know who uses the phone at this hour?
Somebody who wants to spoil her rotten, by the sounds of it.
Oh look I don't get to see him that often. And when I do, he always goes over the top.
Confirmed by text. Nothing like the personal touch, eh.
Where's your key?
Nowhere to put it, eh. Look I hope you didn't push Peter too hard, love?
No it was just a few gentle stretches.
That gear doesn't
It's ‚Winter training session up at Peter's club. It's our turn to do refreshments.
I thought he was sitting this week out?
No, he's still gonna go along and watch.
Well I don't suppose anything from the cafe or the chippy will be right?
No, you're gonna have to come up with some healthier options. While I go take delivery of those new fat fryers!
Shower. Now.
Women on telly, they find the sweaty look sexy, love
They've all had nose jobs. No sense of smell. Go, urgh!
You worked really hard over the weekend. There's a nice little tip in there for you.
Cheers.
Do you wanna tell Dawn about tonight?
No, you can.
No it's alright, I know, ﬁKnow your place. Smile nicely. It's an important eventﬂ.
Yeah. It is. That's why we had to employ some agency staff.
Professional bar staff.
It's just a one

Since that bloke asked for Sake, you came up with a couple of choice cockney expressions!
Look, it's gonna be a sophisticated bunch tonight.
Well, if I'm not working, I might just come in anyway. You never know, some rich businessmen might take pity and buy me a drink!
Who said anything about you not working? I want you on cloakroom and the loos.
The loos? Are you kidding? What, handing out paper towels?
And a little bit
Look, I'm sorry, I'm not gonna be a toilet attendant.
They're in a bit of state actually. So if you want some overtime, you know where the cleaning stuff is. Just think, at some point in the night, every bloke's gonna have to go.
Oh. Didn't see you there.
Don't mind me.
It's just the Bridesmaid, me in this case, and the Best Man, Garry in this case, usually follow the Bride and Groom, Hazel and Minty, onto the dance-floor.
Uh-huh.
This is Garry.
I think you've just squeezed the life out

Yours, I believe?
‚Been airing my dirty laundry in public again?
Mostly Dawn's. You wanna be a bit more careful.
I'll let her know how quick you were to pick up on the scent!
I'll do you a swap.
You've ironed my overalls!
It's no trouble. We've gotta look our best at all times, Garry. For the competition. I've spent a fortune lately on looking good.
I have actually got a life.
Hasn't your Mum said? We're through to the final stage. ﬁDesign your dream weddingﬂ. The pressure's really on. We were all supposed to put our thinking caps on over the weekend. Come up with a theme.

That's awful.

Chuck it back.

You had your hand on it first.
You've got kids.
‚Probably a bit young for it yet.

Go on, after you.

Come on then Billy. Let's get fruity.
Hey, what d'you mean?
Lemons. Limes. For the pub.
Oh. Right.
So I hope you're not missing us too much? ‚Didn't even see you over the weekend for a drink.
Out of sight, out of mind. We decided that everyone needed their personal space, didn't we Billy?
yeah well I suppose we did get a little bit ﬁon top of each otherﬂ, didn't we.
yeah...We might pop in for a quickie later. A drink, I mean.
Or

With a man?
With a man.
That's brilliant, Roxy. Just open up your heart and let him in.
Okay.
Poor bloke. He won't be a patch on you.
How dare they. I'lll show them. I'm gonna look fantastic.
Show who? a) Ronnie, b) Jase, or c) some totally new guy?
All of the above, Shab. 'Cept I can't really do that properly unless I find myself an assistant?
Don't look at me, Loo Lady!
What is it you're after?
Nothing she's gonna find here.
You've hardly looked.

Afford the real stuff, can you?
After tonight Mo, who knows? The club's gonna be crawling with rich business types.
Your future husband gonna be there, is he?
He's better be. I've decided. I've had it with being a single Mum. I'm gonna find myself a bloke, even if it means wearing something cheap.
Nothing cheap about this range. A bit pricier but why don't you treat yourself to some of this real imitation class?
Well if it's more expensive then forget it. Shab, I might have to borrow something.
Man-eating stuff, this is! She'll be lucky. How many high flyers wanna take on an immediate family?

And since when did baby-sitters not get paid Dot? Now go on - please take it.
She was a pleasure to be with so don't say another word, put your money away, go on.
Right, well next time I see you in the Vic?
Yes. A tomato juice'll go down a treat.
Right, you're on. Er, before I go, is there anything you want me to do? Like put put the kettle on or anything?
I ain't an invalid Mickey - not yet.
Well, thank you again. See you later.
Ah, it's been a pleasure. Ta da.
Here, Tegs - it's that old lady again.
Where?
There.
Check out the zombie!
Boys, look at her face.
When did they dig you up grandma...
... Grandma?
Look who's here.
You took your time.
I've been looking everywhere for you lot.
Well you're here now. Welcome to the gang. Fancy it? It's yours if you want it.
Where you going?
Just seizing the day.
Just gonna slip off were ya?
No, I was gonna leave my phone number on a post it note.
I don't know if I'd call it. Not after last nights performance.
Oi.
Oh come on, Five more minutes.
I can't I've got loads to do.
What's the rush?
I said I'd help Peggy get things ready for Phil's dinner.
That's not till tonight is it?
You're still coming aren't you?
Oh yeah yeah. It's the first thing I thought about when I woke up.
I'll see you later then yeah?
Is that all I get then?
Get off, I've gotta go. I'll see you later yeah?
Right then, so what do you want for your breakfast? Cereal or I can do you some toast.
No, I'm not hungry.
Oh come on, you've got to have something to set you up for the day.
Alright.
You're in a real hungry aren't ya?
Eh Jay?
You know about last night? I'm sorry I weren't there for you.
It's alright. See ya later yeah?
Yeah. Jay?
Jay, you forgot these. You've got history today ain't you?
Yes.
Got everything else?
Yes.
Good morning You're up nice and early.
Yeah, now can I go, yeah?
Yeah go on. Never seen him so keen to get to school. Something's changed.
Well, maybe he's alright about us now.
I don't know about that.
Or maybe he's got a girlfriend too.
Hiya cheeky chops.
Remember we're seeing the accountant later.
How could I forget? It's the highlight of my year.
Who's covering?
Er, I'm leaving Steven in charge.
You're joking?
Nah, he needs to learn every aspect of the Beale empire.
Oh does he now?
So how was dinner last night? You've hardly said a word.
Were they holding hands at the table and kissing and everything like that?
I hope you're not being homophobic. I won't have none of that in my cafe.
I know, it's incredible ain't it?
Do you know what? I was actually looking forward to my first gay wedding.
Well, you'll have to wait a while, 'cause, well I don't know when we'll see Christian again.
So what are we doing?
We're gonna have some fun mate. The world is our lobster. Come on boys, let's go.
Minty. We need to talk about this wedding.
That's my cue to leave. As much as I'd like to stay and hear all about it.
Look, I know you're not keen on this whole line dancing thing...
Whatever give you that idea?
But we have to do it if we're going to win the competition. Where are you going?
Work.
Well when are we going to talk about this?
Thank you.
How long aren't you going to speak to me? You know the sooner we talk about it, the sooner it's dealt with.
Okay. Let me just admire my beautiful twenty fifth wedding anniversary present.
Oh dear.
Which you bought in an antique shop. Oh no no no no,
Shirley.
In jumble that Mrs Trueman was throwing out.
Yeah, you knwo, maybe it was better when you weren't talking to me.
When I look at it I feel so special. So valued by my husband for the last twenty five years.
I've apologised a million times. What else can I do?
Well maybe if you got the money back I might feel a tiny bit less sad.
From Shirley? No way.
Why not? Are you a man or a mouse?
I can't just go and ask her for the money.
Man or a mouse?
She won't give it to
Mouse?
I -
Mouse.
I -
Mouse.
I'm going to get it now.
It's really over, he weren't kidding.
I'm not surprised the way you talked to him.
I did like him Jane, I'd just had a few too many drinks.
You mean you liked his money?
So I took security over passion. But you'd know all about that.
What do you mean? Me and Ian love each other very much.
I'm sure you do, in your own way. So this is where you work every day?
We own it.
I'm not sure if that's better or worse.
What d'you want Christian?
I've got nowhere to stay.
Oh, well, I'm sure you'll find somewhere. You always land on your feet. You don't want to stay with fat, boring old Lesley? And her boring husband and her boring kids.

Just for a week or two. I've got nowhere else to go. No money, no nothing. I'm glad this has happened with Ashley. It'll give us a chance to get to know each other all over again. You're not still mad at me about David, are ya?
Come on love, we've gotta go.
Um, look we've got an appointment. I'll talk to Ian. Any problems give us a call.
I can't believe he's back.
Oh, I'm just glad you two have made peace.
Yeah?
Yeah. Well families should be reunited. I'm just chuffed that I'm the one who got you two back together.
So you won't mind if he stays for a week or two?
What with us? What in our house?
Shouldn't you be at school young man?
They gave me the day off. For good behaviour didn't they? Oh I'm sorry.
Look what you've done.
Sorry.
No just leave it, leave it.
Hey you! You little... Did you see that?
Kids these days eh?
What are you doing?
This place needs a makeover.
Does it? I keep it tidy.
Yeah, a bit too tidy. It needs some warmth, colour
Yeah?
A woman's touch.
Right.
Yeah you know, a couple of cushions, a few throws, a pot plant or two. Make it a home.
Dawn, you don't have to.
No I know, but I want to. Right, help us move this coffee table.
Hi, I'm Christian. Jane's brother.
Oh, you're the... brother.
So you've heard of me?
Yeah, sort of. I'm Ian's son, Steven.
No. I can't believe you come from the same gene pool as him. You're a very handsome man and quite frankly he's... not.
You have the most incredible eyes.
Look can I get you anything?
Stacey! Hiya, it's so good to see you.
Have you got our bacon rolls ready?
Yeah. Are you sure you don't wanna eat them in here?
No, we've got a stall to run. See you later.
Stacey's my girlfriend.
Is she?
Oh yeah.
Oh right.
Done well, didn't he lads. Make a good little team me and you mate.
Get ‚em out and light ‚em up.
We're not smoking ‚em.
You what?
We sell these on and keep the cash.
Oh I like it, yeah.
Come on, here you are boys, let's go.
He can't have said that?
He did. He's going round telling random strangers that you're his girlfriend.
Why would he say that?
You tell me. Is there something you ain't telling your old Nan?
Don't be stupid.
Well, you've got nothing to lose.
Nan, my marriage only fell apart only a few weeks ago.
Well then get back on your horse and you'll feel a lot better.
You really think Steven's good boyfriend material? He ain't exactly
Well who is these days?
Here, that was the bank on the phone.
What did they want?
Just asking me about all the money that's just gone into my account.
What?
Do I wanna put it in a high interest thing.
Oh yeah?
Yeah, I told them I'd call them back. What d'you think they meant?
Oh it's probably a mistake. It weren't one of them foreign call centres was it?
Yeah, I think so, I could hardly understand a word of what the poor girl was saying.
It'll be a mix up. They're useless that bank. I'll speak to them.
Yeah okay.
Shirley, there you are.
Did it do the trick? Bet she loved it.
Initially, yes. But she was less pleased when she discovered Yolande had sent it off to a jumble sale.
You can find some amazing antiques that people throw out these days.
Er, yeah, well it was a piece of costume jewellery and it wasn't worth thirty pounds.
No, I know I should've sold it for fifty.
Well it wasn't even worth thirty pence.
What do you want me to do about it?
Well, if you just give me back the thirty pounds, I won't take the matter any further.
That's really kind of you. I tell you what, I'm going to give you forty pounds for your trouble?
It's a deal.
Get lost.
Oh er, are we still going halves on Phil's present?
You're talking to me now?
Well I've seen a couple of things and I thought if...
No I'm gonna get something with Jack.
Oh okay.
What?
What is this?
What d'you mean?
This is not you. This is not how you are with blokes. What sharing presents, staying over, inviting him to family
I do.
No you don't. You're suspicious, you don't let blokes into your life. You don't trust them.
Well this time it's different. It works and I'm not gonna mess it up.
Hello Garry. Minty. About this wedding Minty.
Oh not you and all.
Hazel's got it in her head that ...
Oi, where you going?
Hazel's right.

Scene_info: R AND R - OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Is this yours?

Scene_info: R AND R - OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yeah.

Scene_info: R AND R - OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I take it not Phils?

Scene_info: R AND R - OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Er, no.

Scene_info: R AND R - OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Who's is it then?

Scene_info: R AND R - OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Oh, it's my daughters.

Scene_info: R AND R - OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Oh, oh right. It's her birthday soon is it?

Scene_info: R AND R - OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yeah.

Scene_info: R AND R - OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Look I just wanna get on with this.

Scene_info: R AND R - OFFICE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Oh, of course.
Yeah, looks nice. I like what you've done with the scented candels.
Yeah, well they're to get rid of the chip fat smell.
So, what you doing?
Oh, I just got this in his room.
Oh Dawn, you know you shouldn't be going through his stuff.
No I'm not. This was all on the floor. Oh have I gone too far? I'll put it all back where it was.
No, you're alright. It probably needs a wash anyway. I'm just gonna make a start on the kitchen.
Jase?
Yeah?
I think you should see this.
So where does that old bag live again?
That one.
Well let's see what she's like when she ain't got a big crowd around her.
Too right.
Let's wait for her.
Eh!
You lot move.
What?
I want a word with you.
If we're going over the Vic, why did you come over here for me?
I thought we could go together.
What like a proper married couple?
No, just... Oh shut up. Come on let's go.
You look lovely.
Thank you.
It's gonna be fine.
Yeah, I know. Come on.
So what have you got to say for yourself?
What's she doing snooping around?
I wasn't Jay, I was just trying...
No. You were going through my pockets.
Well maybe it's a good job she was wasn't it. What are you doing with this?
I need it.
You what?
All the other lads carry them, so I've gotta have as well.
They don't all carry knives alright? The ones that do, you don't want to know. Look if you ever pull a knife, someone could get killed alright?
And that could be you. This is serious.
Yeah and who are you to talk?
And that's why I know. Where were you today? Why weren't you at school? Listen, I'm keeping this right. Now get to your room and I want it clean from top to bottom.
You what?
Move. And I want it spotless.
Oh, it's, er, great. It's terrific, only ... I'm not fifty.
Aren't you?
No not yet. I've got a couple of years to go. I'm forty seven.
Did you know?
Yeah of course I did, but you went to so much trouble, I didn't want to spoil it for you.
I thought it was funny.
Right, well I'll just take all this lot down shall I?
Nah nah, it don't matter.
We can use it in three years time.
Happy birthday, Phil.
Yeah, happy birthday.
Thanks.
I got you this. It's perfect for a special occasion.
Oh here we go. You know Phil doesn't drink.
Yeah, that's why he bought him this non alcoholic wine as well.
Yeah, you wouldn't know it wasn't the real deal.
Cheers.
Eek. Eek. Eek.
Don't think you can get round me by being all cute. It won't work.
She was really scary.
Pathetic.
Look: flowers. Chocolates.
Mmm, so you thought you'd make things all better by spending even more money?
Was that wrong?
Mmm, yes. Yes it was.
Look can we just write off the money and put it down to experience.
It's the principle of thing. Why should she get away with making fools out of us?
Can't we just leave it?
You know what, you can but I won't. I'm going to sort this out by myself.
There you go darling. Now, tuck in and I hope you enjoy it.
This looks amazing Auntie Peg. What is it?
It's pan seared venison with blue berries and shallots.
Yeah?
It's a special occasion.
Mmm, I love venison.
What is venison?
Well it's, er, it's deer isn't it. You know, Rudolph, Bambi and all that...
Ugh is it?
I don't want to eat Bambi.
No it's not Bambi. You mustn't think like that.
I'm not so sure I want to eat a deer.
Don't worry about it, Jack loves it, he can eat it all.
Yeah, I'd be happy to.
Well you'll be glad to know it's not venison. I couldn't get any, so I used beef.
Oh right.
And are these um...
No, they're not blueberries either. I couldn't get them. So I used raspberries.
So there's no blueberries in it, there's no venison. Are there any shallots in it?
Yes, loads of them. Now will you please all shut up and eat.
Oi Steven. Why have you been telling people I'm your girlfriend? My Nan heard you.
Jane's brother was freaking me out. He was really coming onto me.
Are you sure?
He said I have incredible eyes.
Maybe he was coming onto you then.
I just panicked. I didn't know what to do.
Well it's alright, I thought it was funny.
It won't happen again.
If you believe that you'll believe anything. Come on.
I didn't realise you were fifty Phil?
Neither did I.
I'm not. Anyway, forty-seven, fifty, it don't bother me.
You not worred about getting old?
Nah.
Oh, I would. Not being able to do what I used to do. You know, getting tired, losing my edge, losing my...
I still feel seventeen myself.
Well you can see that. You're full of youth.
Well you can come again.
Creep.
Ben keeps me young, keeps me on my toes. It must be same for you, with your daughter? Oh I forgot. You're not allowed to see her, are you? That must be hard for you.
Phil.
How's the wine, Peggy?
It's lovely. I think we ought to have some more.
Oh, watch it, you're going to get me drunk.
Oh there's no chance of that, I mean you can handle your drink can't ya?.
You alright?
Yeah yeah. Just getting some water.
That was delicious, Peggy.
I'd love Christian to stay. But we just haven't got the room love.
It's a big house. Look, there's plenty of room.
He's got no money. So he won't be able to contribute or anything.
He can stay rent free for a couple of weeks alright?
Remember we've got young boys in the house ain't we?
Hah. I hope you're not being homophobic Ian?
He did make a pass at David.
yeah of course, he likes older men, so if anyone should be worried...
Ian, this may come as a bit of a surprise to you, but you're not everyone's cup of tea. You're certainly not Christian's.
No?
Of course not. So he can stay? Yeah?
Yeah, I suppose so.
Great.
So did you really make this yourself?
Yeah.
All by himself.
Oh sorry mate.
Phil!
Dad!
Oh no.
What did you do that for?
It was an accident. You alright mate?
I can't believe you just did that. Here let me clean you up.
It's only a bit of cream innit.
So I thought we were mates.
Yeah we are, we're great mates.
Aren't we? I thought we were, that's why you sold me the car lot.
What was that?
What? Hasn't he told you? Yeah he was desperate, so he sold it to me at a knock down price.
Is this true? Why didn't you tell me?
I think we should leave.
Yeah, thanks for dinner Peggy.
Is no one gonna eat my trifle? I spent hours making that.
Look forget about the trifle now okay.
There's no need to shout at him.
I'll shout at who I want okay?
Oh Albert no!
Ben!
I'll go.
Do you think it's big enough?
Isn't it beautiful? I got it in the sale.
Can I just have twenty of my usual please.
Okay.
Pay day today. I think I've got my priorities right.
Right, that'll do nicely thank you.
What the hell do you think you're doing?
Just getting back the money which you took from my husband.
No, your husband got those goods fair and square.
Ah, which belonged to Yolande here.
Ah yes. You've been selling my nearly new.
No, it was a load of old tut and you were throwing it out.
Yes Shirley, but I wanted it to go to people less fortunate.
Well it did go to someone less fortunate. Me. Anyway, you're not the problem, she is. Oi!
I don't understand. You and Phil can't stand each other.
And?
It was a big thing me bringing you tonight, and yet you've been meeting up and doing secret deals?
Oh it's just business.
How did he even come to sell it to you?
Our paths crossed. Alright? I don't know.
Why would you even buy it though?
Look he was desperate. I was just helping him out. What are you worried about?
Oh, I left my make up at yours.
I'm gonna open up, I'll see you down there.
Okay.
Hey listen, er, I'm just gonna check on Jay.
No leave him. He'll be alright. Just give him some space. Here...
You just can't sell it without me knowing, I own that land. I'd of had to sign something...
Just leave it, mum yeah?
Oh no? Ben's trust fund you asked me to sign it. Tell me it isn't this? ‚Sign it quickly, you said, no need to read it'. You've had a right laugh at my expense.
It wasn't like that alright.
And that phone call from the bank. Oh poor old Peggy, she won't know. Why did you ask him to buy it? Was it to get at me for getting into
No. No.
Then why didn't you tell me?
I just wanted to get rid of it quick, alright.
No, I don't believe you. That's not the reason. I know you. What's going on?
It was a lame duck, it was just sitting there wasting money.
Yeah? Well I don't believe you.
Kevin Wicks couldn't make any money out of it could he?
That was an investment for my future.
Well maybe it's just as well it's out of your hands eh?
What did you mean by that?
Well we know that when it comes to money you can't be
I never mean that right.
Oh yes, you did.
What you doing?
Just catching up on a bit of work.
Yeah, looks like it. Look is everything alright between you and my mum?
Yeah alright.
Oh yeah, yeah that's right. You alone sitting here in the car and her at the flat rocking in the corner?
Is she?
You're both miserable, you're both doing my head in. Now what's going on?
I don't think I can give her the wedding she wants Gal.
I thought that was what this stupid competition was all about?

Yeah well. It's all got out of hand ain't it? I mean she wants cowboys and costumes and madness. I can't do that, it's just not me. I can't get up there and entertain everyone. She wants line dancing. And I can't even dance.
Is that it? well we better see what we can do about that. Pint?
What do you want?
I just wanted to say-
What are you doing with that bloke?
What?
I mean who is he? What do you know about him?
Everything there is to know.
So you knew that I'd sold him the car lot?
No I didn't know that, but-
And all about his past?
I know enough.
About his ex-wife?
Yeah, yeah she's called Selina, they're divorced and they've got a daughter.
Who he, erm, he ain't allowed to see.
So, what happened there eh? I mean what father ain't allowed to see his own daughter? What happened? I mean we all know he's handy with his fists. So, wouldn't you like to know?
I trust him one hundred per cent. I'm not gonna to let some petty macho rivalry get in the way of what we've got.
Oh it's lovely. I love the decor.
Stop it. Hi. Ian's said you can stay.
Ah thanks. You won't regret it.
Yeah I hope not.
Thanks Ian. So you don't mind me sharing a bed with you and Jane then?
You what?
Christian. He's winding you up Ian.

No, no Max is still out. Well don't worry, I'll just find my make up bag and then I'll be down there... No I think i left it in the bedroom... Well that's great, it's great that it's busy, it should be a good night... Oh here it is, I've found it. I've got what I came for.
Hello? Hello?... Is that you Carol? Oh. Who's there?
She'll see us.
look at her face.
She looks really scared MATE.
we haven't even got going yet.
You're alright, we're up.
OK, listen to this right, I've seen an advert in the paper.
Dad?
That's what I thought. You know, you never know where these things might lead. I knew you'd understand. Right, she's been washed and fed, adn she should be alright.
Whoa whoa, what you doing?
Dad? Can you take me for a gut buster?
Hang on son.
Well I can't take Summer with me. Mickey's got a day labouring, Keith's stuck in the loo after a dodgy kebab -
Come on Dawn, I can't look after her. I know nowt about babies.
She'll be fine. Right. How do I look? Wish me luck!
What's that smell, Dad?
Is it too much for him to wear some clothes in the morning?
Hmmm?
What?
The amount of flesh on show. Not everyone's used to half naked homosexuals in the morning, Christian.
Ian getting hot under the collar, is he?
Ian's got certain standards.
Bet he's got all the rules written down somewhere. Laminated.
If you're staying in his house. Better for everyone, if you go along with them.
I was just gonna come over -
yeah? Remember where we live?
I thought we needed a cooling off period, that's all.
Least we know where your loyalties lie. You've made that very clear.
Look, why don't you take Albert back. And we'll go and talk about it in the caff, yeah.
Why? Too scared to face Aunty Peg?
‚I've always thought a good lashing with a buggy whip would benefit you immensely'.
Eh?
‚Gone with the Wind'. Most romantic film in the whole world. There's a showing at a little cinema I've found. Thought we could go tonight?
Frankly my dear, I can't. I've got something planned.
Do something else if you don't wanna do pictures -
With Garry. I can't let him down, I promised him. See you later.
Say you're a muppet Jay boy, or I'll break your neck.
You're a muppet!
Lads think you're alright.
Alright? I'm the bizz, me mate.
Thinking of letting you join. You up for it?
What? Do I get a badge?
Being in the Crew. Makes you somebody. No-one can touch ya. Think of something for us to do, later, yeah. Some entertainment. Then you come find me.
I was joking.
You have to be organised in business.
How can you stand it? Earth to Jane? Don't touch the tuna mayonnaise mate. Affects the hearing.
Thanks for the tip.
What's it about?

Christian! Loads of things. This Greek Island, the war...Mainly about this girl, she promises to marry a local fisherman. Then the army invade an' she falls desperately in love with an Italian captain. That's when she realises. She was never in love with the fisherman at all.
Haddock. Over ordered it again. What?
Nothing.
I only phoned it through the other day. Have you been messing with my paperwork?
Ian, I never ever mess with your paperwork.
Only, I've got a system. Same system I've used for years.
Bet you do -
I'm gonna have to go down the suppliers. Give them a piece of my mind. So that's where I'm going, now.
Do you have to?
Yeah, it's so much fun.
Took you long enough.
What?
Finally swapped that frog of a' husband of yours. For a charming Prince.
That the way you and Jack get your kicks, is it? Set a bomb, stand back, watch fur fly?
When we got back to his, we had words, okay.
Before falling into bed for the weekend.
Alright. Look, bringing him over maybe wasn't one of my best decisions -
Jack sat there and he waited and he waited, an' he chose his moment. An' if you can't see that -
You just can't standit, can you? You can't stand me having a shot at happiness.
Hello? You're his way to getting close to Phil. You're a piece of skirt, notch on his bed post. End of.
You didn't even make it that far though,
You think this is for real? You're kiddin' yourself. You don't know who he is, you don't know what he's about, Ron. You don't know anything about him!
I wouldn't normally ask. But I've got a crisis of the nuptial variety.
Better get that seen to. Go on, off you go. You leave everything to me.
Thanks Dot.
What you doing here?
I come to see you special Mrs.Branning.
It's wrong. Creeping up on people. Ain't no-one ever told you that?
Well I come to say how sorry I was.
The other day in the caff. I should've said something. I should've stuck up for you.
Well they ain't very nice boys.
I know. And I wouldn't like it if they was picking on me, would I?
No, I shouldn't think you would.
They do, you get in their way. They come and find you, an' they give you a smack.

Well you've gotta stand up sometimes, Jay. Stand out from the crowd. ‚Evil pursues sinners, but to the righteous, good shall be repaid.' Proverbs thirteen, verse twenty one. Well, you're here now. You done the right thing in the end... You can stay a little while, if you like? I'll make you a cup of tea.
No no, you sit down, I'll make the cuppa tea. Milk and sugar?
This is a turn up for the book. No sugar coz it's poison, only good for shock.
Oh, if you look on the side, you find yourself a chocolate biscuit.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You can't expect me to get on with everyone. Besides, I'm an ex-cop. Phil's a -

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Mitchell. Same as me.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Same as Roxy, same as Peggy. I don't have a problem with them.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Roxy ain't exactly part of your fan club. Reckons I don't know enough about you.

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: SO what d'you wanna know?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I dunno. Something. Anything. What is your favourite colour?

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Purple. Now, d'you really think this is getting us anywhere? Cos I've got some

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I was just getting warmed up -

Scene_info: R AND R INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You can ask me anything you like. We'll talk, play twenty questions. When I get back. Right now, I've gotta go an' renew my tax disc.
Shifty, slimey little...
Cheap aftershave...Thinks running the chip shop's the nuts.
Who? Jack?
Ian Beale.
My sister ain't going out with Ian Beale.
Think yourself lucky. Mine's married to him. Christian, Jane's brother.
Ah - poor thing. Roxy Mitchell.
Course, you know she nearly didn't marry Beale at all...
