That depends if the numbers are right.
We've got about two hundred members, turn out on a club night's usually around seventy-five per cent. Sometimes more.
Sounds good.
Few times a year we have an open evening as well.
So what sort of club are you exactly, Mr Walters?
It was in the email.
I didn't read any email.
Nah, I just got the phone call.
You mean you don't know what we do?
It's all above board, nothing weird, we're one of the longest-established groups around here.
Nudists.
Naturists.
Right.

It's OK in the summer, there's a fair few beaches set aside these days, but come the winter, meeting up, expressing ourselves, gets a bit more difficult. So this sort of place - totally private, no windows - no risk of perverts trying to cop a crafty gander -
Maybe we could join in.
Think we'd feel like spoilsports if we didn't.
I'm sure the staff wouldn't mind if we explained it to them.
Dawn doesn't wear that much anyway.
Might be a bit cold for Jase on the door though.
No he's from the North, they make them hard up there.
The trouble we have finding suitable places for our members you wouldn't believe. Do you mind if I -
No no poke around. Is this a wind-up?
It's not happening either.
You knew about this -
I didn't.
You had to -
Trust me. Look Ronnie - I just wanted-
Did you get my message?
Yeah.
Coul you, er, give us a few minutes?
Unfinished business, is it?
Couldn't have put it better myself.

Sorry - I've been practising my lassooing. I know it's not very good right now but I will be, honest Minty, I won't let you down. I keep seeing it in me head. The best man, the first dance, leading out the bridesmaid -
Wouldn't look good on video would it, she goes to lassoo him, and ends up lassooing the wedding cake or throttling a waiter.
Look Heather if it's too much pressure you've only got to say you know.
What?
Well, there's no point in making yourself ill is there?
I don't mind.
Look it's only one day isn't it?
Which is going to be the best day of your lives - - and mine.
I think they're going to get on.
And how's Robbie gonna feel? If he does come back and finds a cuckoo in the nest - - well, not a cuckoo but - - oh, you know what I mean.
I know what Jay did was wrong you know - but he was trying to put it right.
He can't. The likes of him never can. He's bad and that's that.
Leopards can't change their spots? Is that what you believe.
I use not to.
Jay's just a child Dorothy.
Exactly what I used to say about my Nick and I was wrong there too, wasn't I? I should never have listened to him all them years ago and I'm not going to listen to Jay neither.
So why did you listen to your Nick?
Because I was a fool.
Because you wouldn't have been able to live with yourself if you hadn't.
Much good it did me.
You've never given up on anyone in your life Dorothy.
There's always a first time.
And you never will.
So I suppose to turn a blind eye? Forget what he did? Let bygones be bygones?
I didn't say that.
Did you book it?
The flight leaves at eight.
Right, I'll sort us out a taxi.
But there was only one seat.
What?
I booked it anyway. You're the priority Mas, it's you your father wants to see.
Well, why don't you come to the airport with me, there might be a cancellation.
No, I need to stay behind and sort a few things out.
Everything is sorted out, Shabnam's going to look after the Post Office.
I'll join you in a day or so.
I wanted you there with me.
Well what do you want me to do Mas? You know get the plane to grow another row of seats? Sorry.
No, I'm sorry. Like you said, nothing you can do.
Um, this is nice to see. You and my brother getting on so well. Hardly seen you all morning, you two spending so much time together.
Yeah, there's a good reason for it.
Which is? Ian?
Not here alright. There's too many flapping ears.
Private is it?
Yeah, look I'll tell you when we get home alright. I've got a little announcement to make.

Yeah that's right, Jay Brown. I mean apparently your Ged's his mate so I thought he might have seen him - hang on he's here mate, thanks again mate, ta ra. So where have you been eh? Settling old scores.
No I haven't.
So what have you been doing?
Can I sit down? Or will I crease the cushions? Hanging offence that'd be.
Go on then.
I went to say sorry, ok?
Who to?
Play Mr Nice Guy.And we all know what happens to them don't we? They get kicked in the -
Jay -
Hiya.
Off anywhere nice?
Away from here.
Have you seen Roxy?
Do I want to?
I can't believe you just left like that. More to the point, Penny was heartbroken - - it's her birthday, Jack.
I'll come later.
She wanted you there first thing, when she woke up - She even made you this, left it in the kitchen so you'd see it when you made your coffee, when she realised you'd gone -
Look I wanted to be there too. But we both know what would have happened if I'd stayed.
Wouldn't exactly have been the first time.
We're not living together anymore.
We haven't been living together for the last two years, that's never stopped us. So what's different now?
There's no future in it.
Because now you can see a future with someone else?
Maybe.
Ronnie.
I said. Maybe.
And from now on, I'm well and truly in the past?
You'll never be in the past, how can you, Penny'll make sure of that if nothing else.
And is she the only reason?
Actually, I've been thinking about that too. The future. I would've told you last night if you hadn't shot off like that.
Told me what?
We're moving, Jack. Me and Penny.
Out of the flat?
Where are you going?
France. Live with my folks.
So, um, what's this, payback?
Don't be ridiculous.
You lashing out because I didn't stay over.
You're not that irresistible, I'm not about to move hundreds of miles away just because you decided to sleep by yourself.
So what is this then? Coincidence?
I've said what I came to say, now I'm out of here -
No, you're not taking her away from me.
I'm not taking anyone away from anyone, I just can't go on like this Jack-
Look - we got it sorted.
Nothing's sorted and you know it.
I've moved out.
Yeah, but you keep coming back don't you? Into the flat. Into my bed.
It's only 'cause you keep letting me.
Which makes this a mess and it's gonna stay that way until one of us does something about it.
What? Cuts the other one out you mean.
It's only France for Heaven's sake, it's not the other side of the world.
Well it might as well be, when you're in this sort of mood.
I just - I can't -
Selina, please -
I just can't go on like this Jack. I just need to get my head straight and yours. It's the only way, Jack. You know it and I know it.
If I don't do something - especially now -
What does this mean - what does that mean?
How can I move on Jack - how can you - ?
I wanna know why?
Why what?
Why you done all that? Got into my house, let my Robbie out of his cage?
I didn't.
You let them in what did.
Seemed like a laugh.
And now it don't? Why? You've had a late attack of conscience?
Look I said sorry, didn't I?
Yeah, you said sorry in the launderette. ‚Sorry Mrs Branning' you said.
And I sent you into me office to help yourself to some biscuits and you helped yourself to me keys. Was that a laugh too?
No.
Lull me into a false sense of security, let your friends come calling again?
They're not my friends, right not anymore and they won't bother you again neither okay?

And I have to take your word for it, do I? I was shaking when I come across that square, I was shaking every step. This is my home, my Square, I was brought up here, the last few days is as if I've been on a different planet.
My Nick use to say he was sorry too. I can see him now, standing there, wide eyed, ‚Sorry Ma' he'd say, ‚I learnt my lesson this time' and every time, every single time I'd believe him.
I mean it.
And why haven't the police been round?
What?
Well, if that's how you got hurt, you standing up to your hoodlum friends on my account, they should have been round, getting my side of the story, building up the case.
What case?
Against these so called friends of yours, these friends who ain't your friends no more, who done that to you and who should pay for it.
There's no point, all that's over now.
Not properly it ain't, not on your say so, not untill you prove it. And you do that by going to the police telling them what happened and letting them sort it out.
That's not the way it works.
And that is? You're just like my Nick, all words, don't mean a thing.
You don't know what you're saying.
You can say you're sorry and you can go on saying you're sorry till you're blue in the face, just like he did and God forgive me for me weakness, I let him ... but I ain't gonna let you.
Not if you really mean it. As far as I'm concerned, it's ain't words that count, it's actions.
Is that all ...
... she said?
That she was getting away.
Did she say where?
Mood she was in, the dark side of the Moon wouldn't be far enough.
Well good job I got this sorted then won't it.
I got the distinct impression it'd take more than a mended necklace to bring her round.
I couldn't do it. She's got her heart on it Haze.
What and Hev's more important than me?
No of course not.
It's my day, and I don't want it spoilt.
It won't be spoilt. Are you alright?
I mean it's not as if she's that bothered about this wedding anyway.
How can you say that, it's all she's been going on about for the past couple of months.
No. It's just a means to an end.
What end?
The best man. Silly so and so's got it in her head it's traditional for the bridesmaid to cop off with him.
I can't wait to see that.
Well you still will, I'm going to find another way to get her and Gal together.
What other way?
Leave that to me.
Yeah, but -
Mum knows best -
Oh you're not alright are you - - it's this diet innit - ?
Just go back and do it, ok?
OK.
Promise?
OK, OK -
What is all this? I could hardly get you and Ian to exchange a civil word earlier in the week and now we can't get you apart. And what's this big announcement he wants to make?
Hidden depths, hasn't he?
What?
Here's me thinking that husband of yours was a retro throwback to the dark ages when all the time -
All the time what?
We had a good long talk last night.
After you went to bed.
We're getting together, Jane.
Civil partnership. Gay weddings. Look I never knew how big they were until Christian showed me. It's a whole new market, just waiting to be tapped.
The pink pound.
Ron -
She doesn't understand alright. You've done your bit. Just keep your head down now. Let it all blow over.
She said it wouldn't blow over, not till I go to the police.
No. Going to the police son, just asking for trouble.
You didn't go to the cops. But your old mates still come after you. Why didn't they just leave you alone?
That was different son.
Well they didn't like you walking out on ‚em?
Something like that.

What about you? Did you? See, if it hadn't have been Mrs Branning - someone who I knew - I'd still be with them now. Only known ‚em a few days. I didn't really like what happened when I did. But I still miss them. It felt good. Like, like no one could get to you, like no one could take us, you know?
Yeah. I know.
Don't feel like that now though. Feel like I'm on my own, feel like anyone can.
No son, you're not on your own, you're not.
So what do I do, hang around with me old man for the rest of me life? Not doing what they wanted, what they said. I felt like bottling out Dad.
You getting away from them right, that took real bottle.
And not doing what Mrs Branning says. That feels like bottling out too.
I told you son, you go to the police right, only brings you more trouble.
So what do I do? Sit here and let it come to me? Like you did.
It's easy for Dot to say you know, but she don't have to live with what happens afterwards. Do you know what I mean?
If she did have to live with it. Do you think it'd stop her?
I'm not sure about this.
It's a good business opportunity.
Yeah, but Christian -

Sometimes, in business, right, you have to get into bed with some unusual people - - well metaphorically speaking - - doesn't mean you have to stay there alright? Once that person's outlived their usefulness you move on.
You knew I was looking for something to do.
I'm just surprised you're doing it with Ian.
I saw the money you were raking in yesterday and that was just from a Council do. When some of my friends start enjoy themselves -
Well, here's to a long and happy union.
A union. Not sure about the long.
Did you get hold of her? Rox?
Come In. My Son made the call. He wants to make a statement.
There hasn't trouble has there?
What?
There's a police car just pulled outside the Dyers flat. Dorothy?
Now what? What, Jack?
I don't know.
You know the worst thing? You don't want me, not really. And I don't want you.
So why this? Why last night?
It was so simple wasn't it? I loved you, you loved me and then -
What happened to Penny. It didn't change any of that. Me loving you. You loving me, did it?
No.

Would have been better if it had. You know half of me wanted to pretend that this can work, and the other half of me looks at Penny and hates you - Do you see why I've got to go away? Can you understand how I've got to try and get my head straight? It's not about payback Jack, it's not me hurting you, we've both been hurt enough. We'll go on like this forever if I don't. Think we were moving forward, going on, next thing we know we're back in each others arms and we both know why, because we're trying to pretend it never happened, we're trying to turn back the clock -
Bye, Jack.
Call me the minute you get there.
You keep onto the airline, the first cancellation you get, you grab it.
Promise.
Has something happened with Dada Ji?
No, no news yet. Just ignore me, Tam. It's just the upset.
Mum?
Tam, I've lied to you. I've lied to everyone.
...You've got to eat something. Most important meal of the day.
I ain't got time.
What about a piece of toast.
I'll grab something later.
But -
Oh stop going on about food, Minty.
I just thought you know -
I just wanna look my best for the photo shoot next week. And you've seen what I'm up against with that Donna.
I like you the way you are.
I know you do. But will the camera? You know what they say. It adds ten pounds. So skipping the odd meal here and there ain't gonna do me no harm. Right, I must get to work.
Have you had a word with Heather?
Er, yeah. All done.
Is she OK about it?
Yeah, she understood.
Oh good. It's for the best. See ya later.
What you doing?
They're for Hazel and Minty. They'll set their costumes off a treat.
Fifty quid?! You need your head examined.
They're worth every penny. If they help me get closer to Garry.
I'll take them over to Hazel and Minty's now, before my shift at the launderette.
Good idea. If you hurry, you might catch Garry before he goes to work.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Still no word? Have you tried calling?

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yes. Of course. Her mobile's off.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: She'll come back when she's good and ready. Roxy, why don't you come downstairs and help me bottle up. You know, take your mind off things.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Now where are you going?
...But you have been revising?
Yes. Of course I have.
Well at least that's something I suppose.
IT's no big deal. IT's just a few exams.
No big deal. Sometimes I despair of you Shabnam.
...Why didn't you tell me about these exams before?
I forgot.
You forgot. What kind of attitude to studying is that? You should take a leaf out of your brother's book. Why aren't you at school yet?
Just on my way. Mum...
Well hurry up. We dont' want my A star student being late now do we.
Yes mum.
Well don't just stand there. Let's go go go.
Lining up the next unlucky victim already are you?
See you later. And good morning to you too Roxanne.
Nice time Friday night?
Yes thanks. You?
I saw you. Oh got your attention now? That's right, I saw you and your ﬁnot so exﬂ wife.
Roxy -
You gonna tell me she was just giving you a hand polishing the office desk? Game over, Jack. Because when Ronnie gets back, I'm gonna tell her exactly what I saw.
Yeah well I suppose you could tell her if you like -
I will.
But there doesn't seem much point, seeing as how it looks like Ronnie's had enough of me and cleared off.
It'll make me feel a bit better. And it might just wipe that smug grin off your face for once. And that is the point.
And there was me thinking you were looking out for Ronnie.
And besides, even
You busy?
Depends on what you want.
I need your help with something.
Cuppa tea to take out, Maria. So you not joining the wage slaves today then? Minty?
What, sorry?
Are you coming to work?
Yeah. Maybe later.
Has Phil introduced flexi-time then?
Gal... You haven't noticed anything...odd...about Hazel lately have you?
Odd? Let me see? she's a fifty odd year old Dolly Parton fanatic who's shacked up with my best mate. Odd's what she does best. Why? What's up?
Nothing, Come on, let's get to work before Phil gets on our backs.
Ooh, Hazel.
Alright Heather. What you got there then?
Hazel. You alright?
Are you OK? Are you gonna tell me what that was all about?
...But I don't know how to tell him, Hev.
Just talk to him. Minty loves you. He'll understand.
But what if he don't? What if he don't wanna marry me any more when he finds out.
Of course he'll still want to marry you. You're Dolly to his Kenny. Nothing's gonna change that, right? So you'll talk to him. Promise?
No, I don't think I can.
But -
No. Not yet.
No, course not.
You're such a sweet girl Heather. And it's so nice of you to be this kind to me. Considering you're not even gonna be my bridesmaid any more.

...yes, I received your letter...yes, I understand the urgency... ...yes fine, now if you'll excuse me, I do actually have a business to run here. Thanks I'm sorry about that. What was...oh yes, that will be thirty two pence please.
Perhaps I can interest you in some insurance while you're here? Travel? Home? Car? Pet? Life?
Destroying company property. What would the owner say?
Well I'm on good terms with the owner. Or at least I used to be. Maybe I still am -
...But if it's over between them, why upset Ronnie any more by telling her?
But don't you think she's got a right to know?
Depends.
On?
On why it is you're telling her. If it's to warn her off making the same mistake again, fine. But if it's just to ease your conscience...
Why are you always so...right.
It's a gift.
So promise me you're not gonna say anything?
Only if you do something for me.
As long as it's not illegal this time.
No. But it might be immoral.
Well definitely count me in. What did you have in mind?
You and me. Up town tonight. Get ratted. Take my mind off things.
You're on.
...I'm really worried about her Phil. It's not like her at all. I think she might be really ill.
Well why don't you talk to her. Instead of moaning about it.
Thanks for your support. Anyway, I have tried talking to her.It's not easy y'know. She's got her head full of this wedding stuff.
I have just had to explain to a devastated Heather why she ain't gonna be our bridesmaid no more.
Something you were supposed to do.
I know, I -
Something you told me you'd done.
I know. I'm sorry.
Sorry ain't good enough this time Minty.
I know, I should have told her. And I should have told you I hadn't told her. But I've had alot of other things on my mind at the moment.
Well you are not the only one.
See what I mean.
Well If you're that worried about her, why don't you go and talk to her doctor.
Yeah, cheers Phil.
In your lunch hour.
Two teas please Marie. Cheer up Heather. It may never happen.
It just did.
What's up?
The world's just ended.
What's, the Minute Mart run out of cheese or something?
Come on Heather. What's wrong?
Hazel's decided she doesn't want me as a bridesmaid any more.
Oh, I see. That is bad news.
And that's not the worst of it.
No?
No. They want Dawn to do it instead.
And you know what that means, don't ya...
I'm sorry. I have to go.
Chin up and all that. You know...every cloud...
You're full of surprises.
Well I like to keep my men on their toes.
Yeah I noticed. I particularly enjoyed that bit.
You know I would have understood. About Penny. If you'd just been straight with me.
Well you shouldn't have gone behind my back.
No. I shouldn't.
But if that's the way you apologise, feel free to mess up anytime you like.
Right, I should be getting back. Face the music.
So does this mean we're back together?
Yeah. Let's just keep it between us.
What, you ashamed of me?
No I could just do without Roxy in my ear right now. You don't mind, do you?
If that's what you want.
I'll make it up to you I promise.
Why aren't you at work?
Why does everything always go wrong for me Shirl?
What's the matter?
What is it they say? Always the bridesmaid. I'm not even good enough to be that now.
I'm sorry. I thought you said two o'clock. I'm sure we can fit you in later...
Where did you get all this?
I saved it. But I still need another five hundred.
And?
And if I ask mum, she'll never say yes, but if her golden boy asked her...
What am I supposed to tell her it's for?
I dunno, you're the brains of the family, I'm sure you'll come up with something.
No. No way. I'm not lying to mum.
Is that right? Well if you don't help me, maybe I'll have to tell mum that her A star student's been skiving off school.
No. Don't do that.
Then help me. Please.
Oh so you made it back then.
Did you miss me?
Actually. No.
Thanks very much.
It's been a nice quiet weekend without you tearing lumps out of one another.
How is she?
Unbearable. And now you're back maybe you two can sort out your differences.
Don't worry. I'll smooth things over.
Good. There's no time like the present. She's in the bar now.
Actually Auntie Peg, is it alright if I have a quick shower first. I'll talk to her later, I promise.
Fine. But when you do, make sure you keep it down to a loud roar, ok.
...But I really don't wanna make a fuss Shirl.
Yeah well you won't have to. Coz I'm gonna do that for you.
But Shirl, you don't understand -
No look, you can't let that dozey bint insult you like that. It ain't right.
Oi, Tammmy Wynette. I want a word with you. What are you playing at giving Heather the boot?
Well I -
If it wasn't for her you wouldn't have entered this stupid competition. And you really wouldn't have got this far without her.
yeah I know. And I'm sorry but -
Sorry. No sorry don't cut it.
I mean I know she's on the porky side and doesn't exactly look like Julia
...None taken Shirl...
...But she's been a good mate to you and this is how you repay her.
I don't feel too good.
You're gonna feel a damn site worse by the time I've finished with you. I always said you were a stuck up...
Hazel, are you alright?
Don't just stand there. get some water or something.
What are you doing?
I'm calling Minty.
No, no, no, don't call Minty.
But -
No, please Hev. Just help me get home, will ya.
...Oh let's go there.
You are joking.
Oh come on, it'll be great. I'll even let you be the master"."
Hello darlin'. Someone's in a brighter mood I see.
Yeah, i'm sorry about earlier Aunty Peg.
That's alright love. As long as you and Ronnie sort out your differences, I'm happy. She's back.
Here. Let me.
Why aren't you at school?
I'm here to help.
You should be at school.
Yeah. I should. But I'm not. I'm here.
Looko Dad said I'm the man of the family now and...
OK. You can stay. But just for today.
Thanks mum. You won't regret it.
When did you get back?
Just now.
Right. Where did you go?
Just away for a few days. I wanted to clear my head.
Of that loser I hope.
Yeah.
So you haven't seen him?
No.
So it's over?
Done and dusted.
Sis. Look I'm sorry about what I said...
It's OK, I -
No, it's your life I shouldn't have interfered. I've got something for you. I had it fixed. Turn around.
I knew you'd figure out what a low life Jack is. Even if it did take you a while to get there.
Here you go. I've brought you a fresh flannel. And the kettle's on.
Why are you being so nice to her? She dumped you as her bridesmaid this morning. Or have you forgotten that already?
Shirley!
Come on, we've done our bit. Brought her home. Go and get Minty, he can do the rest. She ain't your responsibility.
Shirley's right darling. You go. I'll be OK.
No. I can't abandon Hazel. Not in her hour of need.
Fine. You stay here and play Florence Nightingale if you like, I'm going down the pub. There's no helping some people.
I'm sorry about Shirley. She get's a bit carried away.
You could have gone with her.
I wanted to stay. Make sure you were alright.
After I treated you so badly?
It's OK. I understand.
That's your problem darling, you're too understanding.
Shirley tells me that all the time.
Yeah well Shirley's right. And she's right about something else as well. I got too caught up in this whole competition. I just really wanted to win. You know, give my Minty his dream.
And that's the most important thing.
But it's not worth losing our friendship over. Can forgive me, and be our bridesmaid?
Well?
Yeah, yeah ‚course I will. As long as you tell Minty.
No, I've already told you. I'm not ready to do that yet.
But that was before. This is serious. You fainted Hazel. You have to tell him.
Alright. I'll tell him tonight. But don't tell anyone I fainted. Especially not Minty.
I won't. I promise.
That will be nineteen pound and ninety nine pence please. Penny change. Thanks very much. And that's how it done.
That's how what's done?
Cross selling. Came in for a passport form, went out with travel insurance. Twenty quid thank you very much. Well nineteen pounds ninety nine but what's a penny between family, eh mum?
Dad always says, take care of the pennies and the pounds will take care of themselves. Mum?
You're a good boy Tam.
I told you I'd help. Mum, what is it?
My child. My sweet sweet child.
What do you reckon - blue or black?
Black.
See, what would I do without you.
Where you going?
A few drinks here then out clubbing with Christian. Why don't you come with us?
Oh, I dunno -
Oh go on, it'll be great. Me and you out on the pull. I miss those days.
Another time maybe.
Oh come on, it'll be fun.
I know. I just fancy a quiet night in.
I can stay in with you if you like.
I said a quiet night in. Now go on, go and terrorise the male population of London.
Alright. And I'll pull a bloke for you while I'm at it. And if you're really lucky, I may even bring him back for you.
Sis It's good to have you back.
And you actually said yes?
Yeah. Why not.
Well after the way she treated you, I would have told her to stick her bridesmaid's job.
Hazel was really apologetic. And there's no way I was gonna let that stick insect Dawn get her hands on my Garry.
And besides, don't be too hard on Hazel, she's got a lot on her mind at the moment.
You're too much of a soft touch d'you know that. I'm gonna get some fags.
Heather, can I have a little word?
Sure.
I'm really sorry about that bridesmade business.
Oh that's alright. Me and Hazel have sorted it. I'm back on board now.
Oh are ya? Oh great.
Yeah, we had a good long chat earlier.
When was that?
This afternoon.
How was she?
What do you mean?
Well was she in a funny mood?
I don't think so.
Have you noticed anything....a little bit different...about her lately?
It's not really my place to say.
Say what?
Heather. If she's said something to you?
No. It's just. Well. I think you should talk to her.
You know something don't ya?
What are you doing here? Shouldn't you be at home tending to the sick? Mind you, I don't blame ya, she's a right martyr that one. I mean she was only out cold for a couple of seconds.
Thanks for nothing Shirl.
What have I said?
I hope you've got your dancing shoes on, coz I am in the mood to party.
Someone's certainly perked up from earlier. Good job too.
Well, you were right. As usual.
So where's it to be? Vauxhall? Soho? What do you reckon? Rox?
I've just heard. Are you alright?
Heard what?
About you fainting.
Oh that. Load of fuss over nothing. Who told you?
Shirley. And fainting is not ﬁnothingﬂ. And when were you gonna tell me?
I didn't want to worry you.
Well I am worried. I'm very worried. Look I think you and me need to have a little talk, don't we? I've noticed some changes in you recently.
Changes?
Yes. And if you can't talk to me, there are people you can talk to.
Eating disorders. You think I'm anorexic or something?
Oh that's just great.
You're the most important thing in the world to me and I can't just stand by and do nothing if there's something wrong.
Well I'm certainly not anorexic.
Then how do you explain the not eating and fainting. Look, if you can't admit it to yourself -
Minty, I'm not anorexic. I'm pregnant.
Let's go back to bed?
It's very tempting. But I've gotta go.
What's the rush?
I just wanna be back before Roxy's up and about. She thinks I was snuggled up with a DVD and a bottle of Merlot last night.
Why you so worried about what she thinks.
I'm not. I just want a quiet life. Look I really love my sister, but living with her does my head in.
If she winds you up so much, why don't you just move out.
That an offer?
Yeah. Why not.
I was joking.
I was being serious.
It's not the right time.
Sounds like avoidance to me.
Call it what you want, but the answer's still no. I've gotta go. I'll see you later.
...Three phone numbers. Not bad for a night's work. But you've either got it or you ain't.
I thought it was four.
I'll not be calling ﬁTimﬂ. He'll be back home with his wife by now.
Him, him I can understand. Narrow eyed little weasel. He'd shag a lamp post if he bumped in to it. But Ronnie. Why would she lie to me? Why would she do that?
I'm gonna go over there right now, I'm gonna tell her everything.
Haven't we been through this.
Well that was obviously before she had a lobotomy and let that cheating rat talk his way back into her knickers.
I'll tell you what I told you last night. Charging over there all guns blazing is not the answer.
So what am I supposed to do? Keep shtoom while he gets his cheating hands all over my sister?
She won't thank you for it. People always shoot the messenger.
Fine. Then I'll have it out with ferret features. And you're not gonna talk me out of it this time.
Fine. Have it out with Jack. But not in this state.
And the point to this character assassination is?
The point is I saw you with Ronnie when I told you to stay away from her.
Ronnie came to see me.
What? And you didn't have the heart to turn her away? And I suppose it was her idea to lie about the two aswell was it?
Yeah, it was actually.
Yeah, right.
If you don't believe me, ask Ronnie.
Maybe I will. And maybe I'll tell her about you and Selena aswell.
Go ahead.
If you wanna ruin the one piece of happiness Ronnie's had in god knows how long.
I'd rather I did it than you did. Which you will do. Eventually.

See that's the problem, Roxy. I think you're doing this for all the wrong reasons. I think you don't like being side lined. You can't stand not being the centre of Ronnie's universe. And you'd hate any man who got close to her.
That is not true. You cheated on her.
I made a mistake with Selena.
Alright, we got
Hello Jim, it's me, Dorothy...
...So she actually fainted? Out cold.
Yeah, but it was nothing.
Your concern is touching.
Hazel's probably just a bit stressed about the wedding.
Well I hope you're gonna take better care of her once you're married. She's got a very delicate constitution has my mother.
She'll be fine. If there's anything wrong with her, the doctor's will pick up on it immediately.
The doctors?
She's just gone for a check up. Make sure everything's ok.
But you said everything was ok.
Yeah it is.
So why's she gone to the doctor's then? Is there something you're not telling me?
No. Honest.
coz if she's gone to the doctor's it must be serious. Coz she hates doctors.
Now if she's ill I've got a right to know. Fine. I'll ask her meself.
Gal, Gal. She's alright. Honestly, she's not ill.
Well what is it then?
She's pregnant.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Hope I'm not disturbing you am I? Still doing the grumpy teenager act? I hope you're gonna clear this lot up.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yes mum.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Have you seen my pink jumper?

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No. Oh, there it is.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Why do you have to lie?

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Me?

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yes, you.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: It's only a jumper.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: yes but it's my pink jumper.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Well if it means that much to you.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Look it's not really about the jumper.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Well make your mind up.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Why don't you grow up?

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Why don't you?

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You know what, you're not even funny any more.
...So I can't see what the choice is. I can't put Jim in a home.
That's all very well Dot but dad's gonna need constant care.
Well I'll just have to cope then won't I. I mean there'll be the nurses coming in. And friends'll rally round.

Well maybe dad won't want his friends to see him...like he is. You know how much of a proud man he is. Look all I'm saying is you might wanna think about the nursing home. Just for a little while. Til he gets stronger.
I mean there are some great nursing homes out there and if it's a question of money -
No, it's a question of what's right. He belongs here. In his own home. With me.
OK. If you're sure.
With the help of Jesus and his guidance I'll find a way through.
Garry, cars don't fix themselves you know.
All the work in The Arches is done. I'm getting sloshed on my own time.
I still pay you to do a day's work.
I'm taking the afternoon off. On compassionate grounds.
You what?
I can't work with Minty any more.
Let me guess - you've fallen out over the wedding again.
Worse. Much worse. The worst.
Look, you either tell me what's going on or you get back to work.
Minty's gone and got my mother pregnant. It ain't funny.
Well, you gotta admit -
How would you like it
Oi oi, watch your mouth, do you want a slap?
See, not smiling now, are ya. And I know why you're not smiling, coz it ain't a laughing matter.
Just put a sock in it alright.
It's easy for you to say. You're not the one who's gonna have a brother or sister thirty seven years younger your junior.
I'm old enough to be it's dad. The next thing you know I'll be on the Jeremy Kyle show.
Garry -
And knowing them two, they'll probably enter the poor little blighter into some ﬁdream birthﬂ competition.
Gal... Listen mate, I know it's a bit unexpected all this and that. But you know, we just want you to be happy for us mate.
No I can't.
I could just about get my head around you two getting married. But this. This is just sick.
Easy when you know how. Something I said?
No. Roxy.
Honestly, living with her is an absolute nightmare. I don't know how I've put up with it for so long.
Well maybe you should take me up on my offer.
Maybe living with you would be even worse.
Maybe. But there's only one way to find out. Or maybe you're scared. Big step. Living with a bloke. You've never done that before, have you.
No I like to know what I'm getting in to before I make that kind of commitment.
Well sometimes you just gotta take that leap.
Guarantee me a soft landing, can ya?

No guarantees. But I can guarantee you a lot less grief than living with your sister. Unless you wanna carry on living with your sister. I can see it now. YOu two growing old together. Knitting cardies, drawing your pensions.
Whereas you'd rather have me bringing you your slippers I suppose?
Now you're talking. Tell you what - late lunch on me, at Fargo's. Celebrate you moving in.
You're very sure of yourself. I haven't said yes yet.
Well if you turn up, that'll be your answer. I'll be waiting.
...And the hospital said it might help, you know, speed his recovery.
Sounds like he's in good hands, Dot. Must be a great comfort to you, knowing he's being so well looked after.
Yes, he is well lokked after there.
And they'll have him back with you soon, back where he belongs.
I wonder if you could do a little recording for me then, Peggy.
Oh yeah, course.

Hello Jim. It's Peggy here. You hurry up and get well. My takings are well downwithout you around. But seriously though Jim. Hurry up and get back. The place ain't the same without you. And there's gonna be lots of free drinks waiting for you when you do. Lots of love, tata love, ta ta.
Well he's gonna appreciate that, free drinks. Thank you ever so much Peggy.
That's alright love, scuse me darlin'.
Auntie Peg.
Someone looks happy.
Someone has just made a very big decision.
And is someone gonna tell me what that big decision is or is someone gonna play silly buggers all afternoon?
I'm moving out Auntie Peg.
That's a bit sudden, isn't it.
Well, you said you didn't like living in a war zone.
Yeah but I wanted you to sort out your differences. Not move out.
It's for the best.
For you maybe. You're not gonna be lumbered with madam up there, are you. Can I ask where you're going?
I'm moving in with Jack.
You're full of surprises today I'll give you that. Now darlin' have you thought this through?
Yeah I'm positive.
But you haven't been together for very long and -
I know what I'm doing Auntie Peg.
Alright, alright, if that's what you want. And what does Roxy think? You haven't told her have ya.
now you listen to me. You're not leaving me to pick up the pieces. You tell her before you go.
I've got to pack.
There you go.
Cheers...I don't think Garry's gonna come round on this one. You heard him.
You've got to admit, it is a bit of a shock innit.
Oh no, not you an' all.
I'm just saying it takes a bit of getting used to, that's all.
Yeah, tell me about it.
You are happy about it?
Honestly?

It's the best thing that's ever happened to me. I'd always wanted kids, Phil. But I never thought it ever gonna happen you know. I know men can have children at any age. But once me and Hazel decided we were gonna get married, I thought that was the end of that idea. But now, all of a sudden. I can have it all. I've got a beautiful wife. I'm gonna have a kid. My own family. It's more than I ever wanted in the whole world..
I'm chuffed for you mate. You deserve it.
Cheers Phil.

Hello Jimmy boy, it's Yolande. We're all missing you so very much, Jim. But I know that with the love of Dorothy, you'll soon make a full recovery and be back making mischief with your friend Patrick before we know it. Bye bye, take care and God bless you.
That'll make him laugh. Thank you Yolande.
That's a lovely idea, Dorothy. And, who knows, it might help to get him back to you sooner. Still no word on when he might be able to leave hospital?
No. Still no word.
Well I suppose these things take time. I'm sure Patrick would love to make a recording if you asked him.
I forgot all about him. Hold the fort for me for a minute.
Dorothy, don't you think you're forgetting something?
I'll forget me head. I won't be long.
You going somewhere?
Away from you. I'm moving out.
Where to?
I'm moving in with Jack.
Oh Ron, come on. There's no need to move out. I'll clean up.
You can have your jumper back.
The little girl lost act is not gonna cut it. Not any more.
You can't do this.
Er, I think I can.
Ronnie don't. Please. Alrigh. Not with him.
It's too late now. It's already been arranged.
Well unarrange it.
I really haven't got time for this Roxy.
You can't move in with him.
You scared there's gonna be noone around to clear up after you?
You're making a huge mistake.
The only mistake I've made was clearing up your mess for years and never letting you stand on your own two feet. Well, it's time to grow up Roxy.
This isn't about me.
Isn't it?
I'm just thinking of you. I just want what's best for you. And if you move in with Jack, you'll regret it, trust me.
God, you really can't stand it, can you? YOu stand to see me happy. But, I am happy. For once in my life I've got a man of my own and I'm not gonna let you spoil it for me, not this time.
I'm begging you Ronnie, please don't do this.
I'll see you later Roxy.
He slept with Selena.
Excuse me, can I get a bottle of champagne please.
You're lying.
Why would I?
To keep me from going. To break me and Jack up. Because you can't help yourself. Take your pick. You'd say anything to stop me from going.
I'm telling the truth. I swear.
That'll be a first.
I saw them. I saw them with my own eyes. At the club. Friday night. On the desk.
I don't believe you.
What is wrong with you? What kind of hold has he got over you? This is me, Roxy. I wouldn't lie to you. Not about something like this.
I'll see you Rox.
Fine. Have it your way. But don't say I didn't warn you.

Alright there Jim you old devil you, it's your drinking partner here...Patrick, yeah man... ...Dot have me talking into this contraption. But I'd much rather be down the bookies with you cheering on a winner you now... ...So hurry up and come back home man, coz there's a whole heap of trouble waiting to be had. And before you know it, it gona be just like old times, yeah man...
He'll pay for this.
Alright Garry luv. What's wrong darling?
Wrong? What could possibly be wrong?
Garry...
Have you got a minute?
Sorry. I've got things to do.
‚Course. No problem.
Dorothy?
Have you seen Minty?
He's in the loo.
Oh.
And congratulations.
Minty told you?
Yeah. Why? Was it supposed to be a secret? Well go easy on him. He's just excited. You've made him a very happy man.
What's this?
Consider it a moving back in present.
What's happened?
Change of plan.
What are you doing?
Livening the place up a it.
Er, in case you'd forgotten, you don't work here anymore.
I do now. Right girls, what is this a pub or a morgue? Lets
There you are. I was really worried about you. I was gonna send out a search party for you.
I know darlin'. It's just I needed some time. You know.

How'd the doctors go? You've made me so happy, I am so happy. And you know what else, you know I wasn't supposed to say nothing, well it kind of popped out and Phil knows. And Garry's not too pleased. But he'll come round. All that matters now is thatyou're gonna be a Mummy and Im
Dorothy, is everything alright?
You wanna take it easy, young lady. Pace yourselves.
Don't worry about me. Plenty of juice left in the old tank.
Yeah? Well if you say so. So why the sudden change of moving plans?
You really don't wanna know.
Forget something have we? Apart from your brain. Well don't let me stop you.
Do me a favour?
Let me guess. Drop dead?
Help me unpack.

Scene_info: BRANNINGS' HOUSE - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: ...I can't even do a message for him. I mean you could, Patrick and Jack, Peggy, but not me. I mean what use am I?

Scene_info: BRANNINGS' HOUSE - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Don't be so hard on yourself Dorothy.

Scene_info: BRANNINGS' HOUSE - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: But how am I gonna manage if I can't do a simple thing like that.

Scene_info: BRANNINGS' HOUSE - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: How long have you known?

Scene_info: BRANNINGS' HOUSE - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Since the weekend.

Scene_info: BRANNINGS' HOUSE - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: And you didn't say anything to me?

Scene_info: BRANNINGS' HOUSE - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Oh I've been wrestling with my conscience Yolande. And the hospital, they must have an answer. They need the bed you see.

Scene_info: BRANNINGS' HOUSE - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: So what did they say exactly?

Scene_info: BRANNINGS' HOUSE - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: They said they can't do no more for him in there. His condition, it ain't getting no worse, but it's not getting much better. And he'll either have to go to a nursing home or he'll have to come back here. That's if I feel up to looking after him.

Scene_info: BRANNINGS' HOUSE - LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: And do you feel up to it? Dorothy?

Hello Jim....It's me. Dorothy. I'm sitting here in the kitchen and I'm talking to you... You won't be able to see me, just hear me... So I suppose I could be anywhere really, but I'm not... I'm in the kitchen. At the table.

Now the doctors they think it would help you you see, to hear the sound of friendly voices... So everybody's done a bit and it's just me left. So here I am. I don't think I've ever dreaded anything more, I mean it's bad enough talking to a machine without worrying about what it is you got to say... But here goes. Everybody is missing you and they're praying for you... Well, not everyone...not the praying bit... That don't come easy to some round here as you know Jim, and I think there's one or two what would burst into flames if they so much as mentioned the name of Jesus, except when they were swearing... But they're thinking about you, and they're wishing you well, which come to think would very well be the same thing... I'm praying for you of course... Well as I can... I find it's best when you're praying to quote back at him, you know... The things he said, just to jog his memory a bit... Children are easy... ﬂSuffer the little childrenﬂ... And then there's the meek...

And them what hunger and thirst after righteousness... But that ain't you is it Jim? So it's difficult to know what to pray for for you, so I've just done the bits about general sinners.... I'm sure he'll know who I mean... You're not really a believer are you Jim? I know you only pretend you are 'cause of me... But I don't think he worries too much about that... I mean he didn't ask if the Centurion's daughter believed in him did he? Before he... before he cured her. It was enough for him that her father did... This makes a change don't it? Me sitting here talking about the bible and you not looking over your glasses tutting and saying give it a rest woman you're giving him ear-ache... He's only human... hmm... only human. I'm stuck now, first time you can't answer back and I dunno what to say.

I can remember the first time I saw her, I was just a little girl and I was in my front room and I was peering over the window sill and there she was across the road with her skirt hitched up, stocking tops showing, wolf whistling at a Lance corporal with bright red hair and a limp. ﬁShow us your war woundﬂ she cried out. He blushed, went as red as his hair, just like Bradley, he looked like a Swan Vesta. He fled and she fell about laughing... I thought she was dreadful. I saw her later. I was sitting on the step outside the Vic waiting for me mother I caught a glimce of her through the door. There she was sitting on top of the piano her legs spread showing next weeks washing and balling out ﬁRoll out the barrelﬂ just like a

I stared at her. She didn't seem to have a care in the world... I had enough for both of us... If I ever got shot of one problem I just went looking till I found myself some more. So as I'd have something to moan about... Well, I had to moan you see. To explain why I wasn't happy... I loved Ethel... That wasn't so hard to say was it? Not if you say it quick.. Mind you. I didn't approve of her morals... I mean if she got up to half the things that she said she did during the

I asked her why she did that, much later on of course, and she said that she loved the idea of sending them back all free with a smile on their face... And was that such a bad thing to do... when some of them might never come back? I mean she weren't no better when she was older... Many a time I saw her in the Post Office chatting up the old men... Ooh, you are such a flippety jibbet Ethel Skinner I used to say. Brazen she was, I couldn't tell you half the things she said... Make you blush... But I reckon, if she had a pound for every smile she put on peoples faces, she'd have died a rich woman... Doubt they'll say the same about me. Then, I didn't have much to smile about.

I read this thing in the paper, it said if the whole of time since the world began, was a toilet roll.... And you unrolled it and laid it out, your life would be less than the width of a hair, right at the very end... Shows you where we are in the scheme of things. Less than the width of an hair? And how do we spend that time? So I reckon that Ethel had the right idea... Enjoy the time you got... It's over in the blink of an eye... It's no use worrying... I hope you're alright... I can hear your voice now... ﬁWhat you blathering on about woman...?ﬂ

Ooh, that's better. Do you realise that Jim, we'll have been married six years soon... Who'd believe it? But you've been a very good husband, there's no denying it and I dare say I ain't been too easy a person to live with. 'Cause, er, I've got me ways. Good job you come along when you did, restored me faith in men... 'Cause I haven't exactly been blessed in that department. I remember coming back from burying Pauline's ashes and feeling all empty... and you lit candles for me. And you put that record on... It was a lovely evening... And you held me so tight, I remembered thinking... I'm gonna be alright, I don't need no body but my Jim... My husband... And that you was right! I could be happy... But I know it's not your fault, but that's only a memory now... I'm on me own again...

After a while you'll come to accept it... And you think that that is how things are supposed to be. Well there's no use fighting it... ﬁWhich of you by taking thought can add one cubit unto his stature?ﬂ I remember hearing that as a little girl in Wales... I was coming home with Auntie Gwen from chapel and I asked her what it meant and she said it was Jesus' way of telling us not to worry... That what will be, will be... It's funny isn't it? How much easier it is if don't expect nothing out of life. Back then it was a kiss from Auntie Gwen, whether it was sunny enough to go in the fields. Not like now, with their ear pods and PPS's or what ever

All I had could fit into one tiny little suitcase. The whole world was at war and I was the happiest I'd ever been. Well, I'd never had much love you see as a little girl, I was never held or tols I was special... I was just there. Talked about, not to... When I was on a train being evacuated, all the children was crying cos they didn't wanna leave their Mothers. I didn't cry. I think I'm gonna have a cigarette Jim. I expect I'll be forced to give 'em up soon. Can't smoke nowhere these days without catching pneumonia. You see, Auntie Gwen was like them Mothers that you see in picture books, I didn't think they was real.

And I was in a family. A real family. I'd never had that before... I remember sitting between them on the sofa listening to the wireless, right in the middle, snug as a bug in a rug... And I wasn't in the way. And they gave me toys and crayons to do my drawings. And they talked to me. I remember one day. One perfect day. I woke up early and I could hear Uncle Will's tractor in the bottom field and I looked out the window and I saw the sun coming up over the hill, and it was the brightest
You alright love?

Scene_info: BRANNINGS' HOUSE, HALLWAY INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Dot? Dot!
You shouldn't be doing that. You've got precious cargo on board... I don't want you overdoing it.
Listen, Minty...
Are you still feeling sick?
... Now I want you to phone up Tanya and tell her you're not coming in today alright?
Well why would I do that?
Because I've been reading up on it. And babies, they don't like the stress. You see?
You know what Minty, I'm really absolutely fine.
I'll talk to him.
Well what about your breakfast?
You have it. You're eating for two now.
You'll be home for your tea tonight, won't you?
Can I help you? It's just strictly speaking, only employees of Mr Papadopoulos can go out the back. Heather Trott. Deputy assistant manageress.
Where's Dot?
She ain't in today. She's off visiting Jim.
Do people still use this place?
We're the most popular laundry establishment in Walford.
And what about Pauline?
Are you a friend of hers? Mrs Branning, I mean.
Something like that.
What did you say your name was again?
I didn't.
Hi this is Jack. I'm not in right now so leave a message.
Jack, it's me. Listen, there's been a change of plan. We're leaving today.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Is your sister ever gonna get out of that bathroom?

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Poor thing. She's in a terrible state.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Time of the month is it?

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I'd watch it if I was you, Phil. You're outnumbered here.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Then what's the problem?

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Goes by the name of Jack Branning.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yeah, well it's time she got shot of him.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: She already has.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Go on, don't stop on my account.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: He's no good for you.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I don't wanna hear it alright.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I'm making you something to eat...

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yeah? Then you'll be wasting your time.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Well where are you going?

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Back to bed.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I can always count on you for support.
I will never understand what people see in these monstrosities. If someone gave me a picture of a boat with a poem that barely rhymed, I'd rip it up infront of them. What are you looking for?
I thought I left one of my coursebooks here.
You know I was hoping you'd come in today.
I've got to get to the wholesalers and pick up a couple of things before the rush starts. What am I saying? Today is your last exam, isn't it?
It's fine. A couple of hours won't hurt.
Every second counts when it comes to exam preparation.
Just go, mum.
Okay, I'll be back within the hour.
We are doing alright, aren't we?
Yes. Why shouldn't we?
Just wondered.
What has your brother been saying?
Nothing.
Don't lie to me, Shabnam.
He hasn't said anything.
Well good. Because that boy has got an overactive imagination.
Are you, um, planning on ordering anything?
I'm waiting for someone.
Is that right?
The fella that runs this place. Does he still live round here?
He's my husband if you must know.
Bit of a comedown from the one I remember.
And you are?
Bacon sandwich. Please.
