Yeah!
Yay!
Look babe, we got a brilliant deal out of Jack Branning. We're not even out of pocket. Oh come on. Let's not spoil it, eh? We've got a lovely night to look forward to... meal, hotel room...
I'm surprised you two haven't done that as well.

All I've done, the whole day, is pick up after you! At home, at work... we just dug you out of a giant hole, and you're seriously standing there, chucking your toys out the pram? Well you know what? I'm not ‚in the mood' now either! I'd rather have the night out with him than you! So you can ﬁtake Bobby for a bitﬂ ﬁLoveﬂ. See you tomorrow! Maybe...
Right, that's his dating profile. And if he gets any messages they come up there. As long as whoever don't turn their broadband off.
Well maybe you should do a profile of yourself while you're at it?
You've got a visitor.
I'm not that desperate Nan.
And don't touch nothing, eh? I've got to bung Tel his hundred notes.
I thought you was working.
I delegated. Thought I'd branch out, try home delivery. You were right, I can't leave things alone.
You're doing my head in... bringing me chips. I was a cow to you...
Maybe I had it coming. I just thought I was looking out for you.
You should be looking after number one. It's tough out there.
It's tough in here. I'm just trying to make everything right.
And it's really sweet of you, but that's what I'm saying. Maybe you should stop trying so hard...
Fine, stuff you then! You know I can't do anything right, can I?
Well, if you're worried you should call the police, if you think someone's hassling him?
Yeah, well, I will if I have to. I don't want them dragging Jase back do I? I can handle it...
Yeah.
Jay?
Come on, mate. Let's get you in the bath. Get you an early night.
Yeah. Cheers, Mrs Teague. Okay, ﬁTinaﬂ. Yeah, it'll just be good to clear the air you know?...Okay...bye.
Was that's Tegs's Mum? What have you done?

Alright, I know invasion of privacy and all that, but I'm not having him put the frighteners on you. So, bit of lateral thinking! I though I'd talk things through with his Mum and get her to get him to back off...
It wasn't him, it was her you stupid cow. She'll have me if I go to court!
It's alright. I can handle her...
Hi it's me...um... Listen... about earlier on... um... I'm sorry I let you down like that...
Oh gosh. Don't you feel just on top of the world?
Yeah.
Oh! The air smells better, even your food will taste better...
Well I've definitely earnt my dinner.
Like I said, a will of iron. Patrick could learn a thing or two from you about resisting temptation. That man, he just sees something he wants and he just reaches out and grabs it...
Wait, I'm gonna have it.
No you ain't.
Yes I am.
Hell, hiya, did you have a good time then on the karaoke?
Yeah! I won, of course.
Only ‚cause you cheated! She found out on the internet you get more points for humming!
It's not my fault I did my homework. You can always have a go tomorrow if you reckon you can take me...
Oi oi Abi, no one's said anything about tomorrow did they?
Please mum?
Can we?
Well we'll see, go and wash your hands eh? Dinners nearly ready.
Night Dad.
Night Dad.
Night girls.
Sounds like they had fun.
Yeah it was... bit of a novelty, ain't it?
You know Abi said that you missed some of that. You know, having a laugh... with me.
Well she shouldn't have.
What, so you did say it?

What am I going to say? I don't miss anything from the last fifteen years? I never loved you? Would've been easier... Truth is, I've lost something out of my life... And I'm trying to find it again. Night.
Yeah, night.
We don't usually make house calls... but for you, I made an exception.
Ow! Yolande, please! I'm just trying to get a word in edgeways..!
You're not getting a damn thing in edgeways, you pervert! First Peggy and then me?
No!
Keep away from me unless you want to feel the full force of my backhand!
You need a bat to practise, don't you Charlie? How'd he get on?
He has let his appetites run wild, that's how!
Eh?
All those energy drinks he has been drinking has gone straight to his brain! Or straight down to his Patrick! Charlie grab up me bottom!
he what?
My bottom!
Hey? Come on, explain yourself.
Y'see, she had something stuck to her bottom...and I was trying to help.
What was it, then?
It was...
I thought I knew you, Charlie Slater...
if only we had been there longer, I could have tripled my points.
Oh just stop now, Abi.
I'm only saying..!
Well don't, because Dad said...
Dad said what?
Nothing. She just can't keep her gob shut, that's all. You know she blabbed to Dad about what you said... about missing him.
Oh well that's alright. I don't want her worrying about keeping secrets. Or you.
She was just moaning cause she didn't have enough time on the karaoke. ‚Cause we were having a laugh. Sorry... he said maybe next time...
Don't be sorry! Come here. I need to know what's going on, don't I.
Looks cosy. Quiet?
Yeah. The twins are both on a sleepover. And Steven's working tonight.
So, no Jane?
Uh, no. I... had her and Christian running around all over the place, preparing for the event... so I thought I'd let them have the meal instead.
Ahh, you're so sweet. Wish I had a boss like you. So... would you like me to show you my Bird of Paradise? Or I suppose we should wait for Jane?
No... they're staying over at the hotel. There's the room.
Oh.
Oh yeah, nothing like the cheery glow of home after a long, hard day. Forget larging it in some hotel, gourmet dinner, hot tub...
What? You still think they'd have given us the freebie after we cancelled the event booking?
I could have talked them into it. Another triumph for hubby. So he finally got a plumber over! Big deal.
You were a bit hard on him.
Alright, so was I..!
So, whose sorrows are we drowning with my booze tonight? Didn't think you had anything left to mess up.
Maybe I'm celebrating. I think... there's still something there. You know, with me and Tanya.
After what you did to her? Let me know when the drugs wear off.
She told me she missed me. I tell you mate, if there's a chance, I'll have them all back...
You had your chance. You wanna do something useful, you sort Bradley out. You seen the state of him lately?
Yeah well I've tried mate. He don't wanna know. I think I'll come down the club tonight.
See? I told you she was long gone.
I don't care. I know now. I was right to stick my oar in.
How d'you work that one out, Einstein. She still took half your money.
Yeah but she brought the rest back! She took a risk. Doesn't that tell you anything?
Yeah. That she's a stupid cow, as well as a lying little tea-leaf. What, d'you think that saw the light? There ain't no light.
Hey, hang on a minute!
You ain't shutting the door on me...
No I wasn't, it's just I didn't wanna let the dog out...
Quick, get the dog in, and shut the door.
I thought you wanted a chat? ‚Cause it seems to me you ain't got the message I left with your boy...
I did! I do. Just come through, I'll put the kettle on, yeah...
Don't bother...
Sit down. My little girl's toys. She loves them. Milk and two alright? Make yourself at home...
And the bed's going over there. Kingsize, obviously, for when I'm entertaining. And I'd better put a proper hob in, so Noah can have his back...
I'm going back over...
Nah, you don't wanna do that.
I can't leave it. We gotta sort it out...
What, and undo all your good work? Be good for him. Treat him mean, keep him keen. Or just for the fun of it.
Well he's probably still sulking... tucked up with his hottie bottle...Oh go on then...
Here we go. I think you'll like this one...very full-bodied.
Not going to get me too giddy. I've got work in the morning.
No, no. No, you say ﬁwhenﬂ.
Oh, are you still stiff? You shouldn't overdo it... with
No, I'm fine me. Fit as a fiddle...
You know your problem?
No.
Too driven. Maybe you should have another massage. Full-body...
Really? Now you mention it, I am feeling a little...
It's not good for you, all that pressure, building up. Every now and then you gotta let off some steam otherwise, you'll explode.
yeah, wait there,... I'll be back in a mo.
I must put a no riffraff policy on the door.
It's alright, I know the bloke who runs the club.
Who's talking about the club? That's probably the bouncers now.
Yeah well as long as you know I ain't going down without a fight..?
Look who's turned up.
I know it's not what we agreed. You hadn't made other plans, had you?
Jay wass right! She put the frighteners on him and now she's doing the same to us!
Is she still in my chair?
Long as she's not in here. How am I meant to talk to that? Please say something! What the hell am I to do?
Well we don't know, do we? It's more of a girl thingthan a man thing, innit Dad.
That's not a girl! I'ma girl. Thing, maybe...
Yeah well whatever itis, it's got my remote and all.
Alright, maybe it's a mother thing to do.
I can't do this.
Course you can! Look, you whipped us two into shape, ain't ya? Look, you'll think of something, you are the mother of this house now.
Harmless flirting, Charlie! That's what I said! And you go and have to grab her Queen Mum.
I didn't touchher! Not... like that! I didn't!
Yeah, I bet.
Oh! Charlie... had me all a-quiver there...
Sit down, Charlie. I'll get your lentil soup on...
Who gives a monkey's about the diet now?!
Me! And half of Walford! I've invested... a lot of time in this..!
Well what happens if I give it up...
You can't!
No, not when there's so many people who have faith in you. We're all behind you.
Yeah, long as I'm not behind you, eh?!
D'you think we should hold off on the computer dating, then?
Just ‚til we know we ain't going down as accessories...Charlie...Charlie...hang on...
Know what your problem is? You just don't like losing.
Like a dog with a bone, you are.
Go on, It's really nice. I battered it myself.
Why you trying to offload it on to me then?
So, that's it? Tonight's done nothing to restore even the tiniest bit of faith?
In what? The power of the battered sausage?
I dunno... In things turning out okay. In people...
Well you see, my trouble is, I live in Walford, and you live in Cloud Cuckoo Land.
So, why are we mates then? If we're so different... Cause I battered you a sausage?
Just eat your chips.
Yeah man, she give him a what for, y'know.
I had to! Who knows what else he would have grabbed?
Charlie..?
If you don't believe me, ask Peggy! He did exactly the same thing to her last night. Only he got her up top instead of the bottom. Made out it was an accident!
Are we talking about the same Charlie Slater?
Alright, ‚Fingers'? Had a little accident, did we? So... what can I get ya?
Just a slimline tonic. He's watching his figure.
Oh yeah? That's not all he's watching, eh?
Right, where does this go?
They don't go there!
Well how do I know where to stick it?
I could tell you.
You sure I can't get you a drink ?
No, you're alright. I should be getting off actually. Bye girls.
You don't have to go..if you wanna stick around, have a laugh, whatever.
It's probably a bit noisy for Oscar actually. I meant to say... Abi's got a parents evening tomorrow night.
Oh yeah..?
We need to decide which one of us is gonna go.
Yeah, I suppose. Unless... we both go?
I'll think about it.
It maybe. Not that you deserve it. Either that or she's playing you on a whole new level.
Tanya? Nah. She ain't got it in her.
I had to take the girls back over to MAx.
You're just giving in to him now in't ya? You can't let him get to you Tanya...
I'm not.
He must have had a bad dream. I could read to him is you like..?
Come on, mate, come here. Was it a nightmare again?
wE Don't want him raking around for your leftovers, your Uncle Charlie. More tea?
No ta, I'm goNNA run a bath. Gotta go to the wholesalers early. Thanks for the chips.
I owed you. We're even.
Yeah. We are.
She looks really tired.
Thanks. For caring. Being her friend.
Wish I could do more.
Just seems like it's all uphill... like she thinks there's no point trying ‚cause you just get stamped on. She must still be cut up over the whole Bradley thing...
Oh that's not down to Bradley! That's just Stacey, the way she is. Probably how she's survived.
YOu mean she's never had any hopes... any dreams?
Count these up would you, love? Just wanna check that Charlie's not slipping.
Watch him now. To think I even did the charts for his diet. Charlie's pounds of flesh!
I think you might've got the wrong idea. It was a gropathon, weren't it Charlie?
Tell them the diet's off, we ain't taking a penny!
I can't, I've already pledged it to a good cause... ‚Computers, For The desperate and Needy'. Just front them out!
I just thought it would be good to talk, you know,mother to mother?
You ain't his Mum, are you?

No, well... you know what I mean. We both want what's bestfor them, don't we? You know, we love them to bits,but if they're gonna be our hope for the future, we've gottateach them right from wrong... Or they can't learn togrow, and learn to live together. Make the world a better, lighter place than it isnow...
You're a bit light yourself, ain't you? Up here?
I don't give a stuff if some hippy trippy cow wants everyone dancing in the sunshine. My boy ain't going down...
Listen, Clare, I'm not so sure this is such a good idea...
Sorry, I hope you don't mind, do you? Just getting myself relaxed. Must be this wine, it's so nice.
Yeah! Well I'm glad you like it. I chose it at the tasting we had yesteday. It's got a very nice bouquet...
Mm. Well I said I didn't wanna get too giddy, but. Could always resist everything except but temptation.
Tell me you'd do anything for me.
All I'm saying is we've got to set a good example! This is... witness tampering..!
You ain't a witness. Telling me how to bring up my boy, you poncy cow. You ain't nothing...
You don't know who I am... what I've been through, me and my daughter...
I don't give a rat's jacksie about your daughter! But if you wanna do the best for ﬁyour boyﬂ, you keep him home tomorrow...
Mr Bendy-Legs!
Ahhh. Accidents happen, eh?

I think we've got off on the wrong foot... ‚Cause like I said, you don't know who you're dealing with! My name is Dawn Swann! This is my house! This is my step-dad's chair you've had your fat bum in, and this, was my little girl's favourite toy you just mullered! So come here, bloody cheek woman!

Come into my house, with all your scrap metal! Throwing your weight around, poking people! You got any idea how much this lot cost?! Now I tried being nice but YOU OBVIOUSLY AIN'T CAPABLE! Now you ever see this face again you'd better be crossing over, cos I'll be round with my pliers! I'll have the bolt out your neck while I'm at it!
You tart! This ain't over yet!
Genghis! Have it! Now don't go getting the wrong idea. Violence does not solve anything.
The main thing is I've got my chair back in't I. What time's tea, love?
Soon as you can get it on the table. And you're washing up.Now!
Come on Tanya, you stay here. I'll go get them.
No, Sean please... I know you're only trying to help... but not like this. Alright? I've gotta go.
I couldn't leave this in my flat. You never know, do you? Probably have a fit if she knew I still had all this. I put it in here on one of my better days.

Got me in trouble at the doctors, cutting up all their mags. I really thought she could make something of this once upon a time... my little Coco Chanel... The lining off the living room curtains. Was a fortnight before I even noticed. Look at the back-stitching on these seams? She was only 10.
I knew it! So... If this was her dream... what happened?
I put it all in here for her...
Come on, quick Abi. Lauren's beating you in't she.
Hello. Looking all hot and bothered, you lot.
Yeah, it's hard work coming third.
Right well sorry to drag you away, girls, come on...
Oh mum, it's my go!
Please...
You're gonna need a stun gun to get her off there...
Right, I'll get us some drinks.
Baby can't you see, I'm callin'... ... a guy like you, should wear a warning...
Intoxicate me now, with your lovin' now, I'm think I'm ready now... Yes! I won!
Well done! You were brilliant,darling. And I'm sure you were an 'all! Come on...get your stuff together, let's make a move. Make sure you've got everything.
Oh, you used to love this one Mum...
No, I don't think so...
Oh Mum, please.
The game's already over anyway, ain't it?
Yeah, I reckon the boys have shown the girls up enough for one night.
What?!!
You can't let that one go, Mum!
It's a duet!
Oh, so it is.
Come on, you can't lose!
First day I saw her, I knew she was the one... She stared in my eyes and she sighed...
Whoa! See the way I look at it... ... all the men I've known have been too young for me.
You're joking?
No! Older guys know what they want. Like me. I know what I want, and I won't stop until I get it. My last boyfriend said I was a succubus.
A what?
Like a demon, has her wicked way with blokes... sucks all the energy out of them.

I don't know. I probably just haven't kissed the right frog... So, when are we gonna get my magic fingers working? Your massage? Don't tell me you've shy on me now? It's not like I haven't seen it before. Well, nearly all of it...
Now...
Oh...
Sorry, was that me?
I'd better go upstairs and get myself cleaned up... There you go. It's not like we haven't been here before, is it? Hope you've got some bigger towels.
And he can't take a hint to save his life...
Oh, there must be something good to say about him!
Yeah, you're right, there's nothing.
He has his moments!
Yeah, no cure for what you've got with hubby I'm afraid.
Love, dummy! Come on. Let's get you home.
On the third day he took me to the river, he showed me the roses and we kissed... And the last thing I heard...
Mum, come on! The words are on the screen!
Yeah...
On the last day... ... I took her where the wild roses grow... She lay on the bank, the wind light as a thief, and I kissed her goodbye...
Okay come on, that's enough, come on, let's go...
Tan...
Tanya...
Please, let me go...
Please, I'm so sorry, ... I'm sorry for hurting ya. Babe I knowthere's something still between us. Pleas just forgive me.
Bye Dad.
Bye...
Bye, Dad...

Scene_info: MILLERS' HOUSE, DINING ROOM INT NIGHT
Line: Eggs a la Keith coming up.

Scene_info: MILLERS' HOUSE, DINING ROOM INT NIGHT
Line: I could still phone your dad, if you want.

Scene_info: MILLERS' HOUSE, DINING ROOM INT NIGHT
Line: Nah. Busy, in't he? You'll do.
Can you make a start your homework please, girls?
Did it go alright?
Yeah. No problem. Why don't you get us a bottle of wine, eh? Something nice...
Ok.
Go on then . The sooner he's back on track, the sooner I get my money.
Now? You're sure it's this one? I don't wanna mess it up...
Just do it!
I hope you don't mind, I borrowed one of your shirts... Oh... so, this is what you want?
Yeah. That's Jane's. I'm sorry, I can't do this.
Do what? Look, you obviously wanna get comfortable, I think I'd better go...
I'm sorry, I... I thought it's what youwanted?
Why would I want that! Look I just meant for you to book an appointment. No harm done though...
Alright then, ‚night...
It's, Jane! Go, go! Go! Go!
I mean... hi. Ian, what are you doing... in those?
I knew you'd be back...
Ah, you rang the hotel?
Mm-hmm. I love you so much...
Ahh, I love you too. Maybe just a cuddle tonight yeah?
Ahh, just what I need. Must make a few quid, this place?
So?
Nah. I think you were right the first time. Me and Tan... it's too late. Hello?
Yeah, yeah. Whatever you want.
Okay then, well I'll give you a call tomorrow then. Bye.
Who was that?
It was one of the other Mums. Sorry, Abi's got this parents' evening tomorrow.
Something wrong?
No... I was wondering if you'd babysit.
Yeah course I will... If Max can't be bothered.
No. Max is gonna be busy. Thank you.
It's gonna take a bit more than a carefully chosen tie.
She's letting me go with her, ain't she? She's coming round, Jack. I'm telling you. All I gotta do is be patient.
Max. You're dreaming.
Okay, bagels?
Check.
Hollandaise?
Check.
Right, I'm just gonna go and check out the venue...
We'll do the chips last thing. Keep ‚em warm.
Chips?!
In little pots. People love that sort of thing. It's ironic. Remember? Post-modern, self-referencing....Just, leave it with us...
We need more space Ian.Right, staff uniforms, who's collecting them?
Being delivered straight to the club. Aren't they?
I ain't going.
Well I don't think we'd even make it now.
People'll think I'm a grass!
Yeah...An' why would you wanna stand up to someone like Tegs eh?
Look I know what you're doing...
He stabbed you, Jay. I don't think you realise, he could've killed you.
You don't go to the feds. You never ever go to the feds.
It's okay, you know. To be scared.
I ain't scared.
Most heroes are scared y'know. That's what makes them heroes. They're scared. But they go and do it anyway. An' I'm gonna be right there with you. And so's Keith, an' Mickey.
Were you scared? Of Teg's Mum?
Did you see the state of her? Too right I was scared!
Okay. Okay, let's do it.
Right, two biscuits each. They said they're allowed more. They're lying.
Okay.
Oscar shouldn't give you any trouble.
I'm sure I'll be fine.
And once they're through that door, you don't let them back out again.
You always this nervous on parents evening?
I just need to be sure you can cope.
Yeah but you're making ‚em sound like category ‚A' prisoners.
You have met my daughters?
Look I've got your number. If there's any problems. I'll call.
Okay. Ta.
When you gonna get a grip?
Might not bother.
You need to get out the house, Bradley. Get a job.
Yeah? Why?
because you're floating around here like the ghost of Christmas Past. And you smell.
Hi. Got your jacket.
Oh. Thanks.
Quite a night. Silliness.
I won't quite be able to look at you in the same way again.
I need Jane's shirt back.
I haven't washed it.
It's alright, I don't wanna put you to any trouble or anything,
It's no trouble.
I need her shirt.
What d'you think I'm gonna do - keep it and use it as evidence?
No, course not. You and me, we're cool yeah?
Yeah. As ice.
You've got a bit of a flair.
What?
Artistic. The way you did that. I draw. Pencil and ink mainly...I could show you, if you like?
Let's hope your pictures are better than your chat up lines. Come and see my etchings?
No, I didn't mean it like that. I just meant, you know, we've all got something, special. Inside. A dream...
Not me.
You must have.
Wake up, get up, go to work, earn a pittance. Spend it on stuff that I think makes me feel better. But it don't. Then I start all over again.
That's your philosophy on life is it?
That is life, Steven.
So, nothing good ever happens? Nothing out the blue?
Let me think. No.
Ian's gonna need some help with this do tonight. I could have a word if you want?
Serving posh suits? No thanks.
Hundred quid in it. What do you know? Something good just happened. It's a miracle.
You look nice.
Yeah well, I wanted to make a good impression. On Abi's teachers... She's probably been playing up. SO prepare yourself.
You think we're gonna get the third degree?
Long as we don't start arguing.
We won't.
We gotta put on a united front. Show we're sensible adults, supporting each other.
Tan -
Let's just get it over with, shall we?
Alright girls, what's it to be? TV? Board game?
I said I'm going to Lucy's.
No, I don't think so. You're under strict instructions. Come with me. You gotta stay here with me and... My bag of magic tricks. Who's for making....pizza??!!
Hold on a minute, Jane, Stacey and free flowing alcohol? In the same room? not a chance.
But I promised.
It'll just turn into a slanging match.
This is important to me -
And this is important to me. It's the start of my new company. And my once in a lifetime chance perhaps of meeting the Queen of England.
Please.
No.
Here comes the Candyman. You old rascal...
Excuse me.
What don't I even get a ‚hello'?
Do your Uncle Jack a favour. Come down the club tonight. Have a drink.
No thanks.
You might enjoy yourself.
All I wanna do, is go in here. Get some cans. And get quietly wasted on my own, alright. So please, if it's all the same to you?
Things haven't been easy on her.
We've been doing our best.
Yeah.
Keeping an eye on her.
Both the girls.
Beginning of term. A dinner lady found Abi crying in the toilets. Did she tell you?
No. She didn't.
Things weren't very good back then.
But they're better now.
Much better -
And we're working on it.

Can I just say, how refreshing it is to see such a positive attitude from you both. And all things considered, Abi's weathered the storm remarkably well. She's a credit to both of you. Now you're getting back together, I see no reason -
Scuse me?
Now we're what?
Getting back together. That is what Abi's been telling everybody.
Can we get some more glasses over the other side.
Not bad.
We may have had to compromise on the venue. But ‚Fit for A Queen' would never compromise on quality.
Stuff all those olives personally, did he?
Where's Steven?
It's alright, he'll be here.
Well he better be. Well have you felt the weight of them trays?
Look, if you needed more help, you should've said. It's a bit late now. The most important thing is to make sure Edward has the time of his life.
Look I've still gotta go home and get changed Ian...
I tell you what love, why don't you ho home, have a nice long hot bath. get yourself ready and just leave everything to me.
See, what I really wanna get into is Graphic novels. Ever heard of the Preacher series?
Strangely, no...
It's about this Preacher right, who merges with this half angel, half demon. And his best mate, Cassidy, an Irish vampire -
Know when people say you're weird? They're right.
You should see the artwork, Stace.
These are good.
They're just sketches. Gotta start somewhere. If you wanna achieve something. Music, sport...
Fashion....
What's she said?
Who?
My Mum.
Nothing. I saw your scrapbook.
What? Well you shouldn't have.
It's good. I mean if you were doing stuff like that as a kid -
Look I wanted to be a sheep in the school Nativity. I grew out of that ‚n all.
Where you going?
Into the real world Steven to earn my hundred quid.
No, you can't. I'm sorry. It's Jane. I really tried.
Hundred quid? Talent like yours? You should be earning millions.
Oh, just leave it, will you? You might still believe in angels, ‚n pixies an' fairies and happily ever afters. But I don't. Alright? I don't.
You put too much water in.
yeah well, it'll dry out in the oven, won't it.
And you used the wrong flour.
There's different types of flour? Just turn the page, would ya?
Lauren? Lauren..will you..
Lauren?!
Will you turn the page, and turn the music down please!
She doesn't love you. My Mum.
What's she doing here?
Well you said you needed some help.
Not her. She's the last person I'd want here-
No, actually Stacey Slater's the last person you'd want here. And I got you out of that one. Edward!
Ian...
I'll leave you to it - work to do.
I trust everything is to your satisfaction.
Wonderful! Well fit enough for this old Queen.
I trust you'll be cracking some of those with Her Majesty.
Not if I want to keep my head, no. Though I heard her mother's afternoon tea parties were quite something.
Glass of prosecco? You're late.
yeah well I'm here now, aren't I?
Grab some canapes and start doing the rounds - and Steven? Smile.
I bumped into Bradley earlier. Didn't look too good.
There something I should know?
I didn't know who to go to. I am really worried about him. He's not eating properly, sleeping. Half the time, he won't even get off the sofa.
Are you paying her to serve the customers. Or to flirt with them Ian?
What?
We've got something to tell you...
Well whatever it is. I don't wanna know.
Don't be like that.
We've got your best interests at heart, Charlie.
I've never been so humiliated in all my life. Can't hold my head up in my own street.
We've got the perfect solution. In't we, Jean? Tell him.
Cybersex!
Dating.
Yeah, that...
It's safe. Anonomous...
No.
But we've already had a reply.
No. Forget it. I've had it.
Where you going?
Get some chips!
What about my sponsor money?
Clare, hust serve them. Don't give them your life story.
Anyone'd think it was the flamin' Oscars.
Is, for him. Edward, that bloke who's do it is, he's getting an MBE. If all goes well, Ian's gonna be his date.
You look as though
No offence.
None taken. Walford isn't exactly where I thought I'd end up spending my sixtieth birthday.
You think Edward's all right? should I go over to him.
No, relax Ian. Edward obviously still thinks he's in with a chance with you. Then in a couple of weeks you'll be able to tell the Queen your special corgi joke.
Stupid thing is, my whole family are artistic. My
What? Like, fashion?
Well she's a teacher now, better pension.
Here? In London? Can I have her number?
I think I've got her card somewhere.
Thought you might be going out with Steven tonight.
Why would I wanna do that?
Because he's a nice looking boy. Because he's always round here -
Cos you encourage him.
He likes you.
Why did you show him my scrapbook, Mum?
Well, I...
What's it even doing here? Should've been chucked out years ago.
because when I open the pages, I hear you laughing, and that's something I've not heard for a long time.
You know he's in love with you?
Head over heels, I'd say.
It ain't love.
What is it then?
Whatever it is. It ain't that.
Why's it so hard for you to believe?
Cos it doesn't exist Mum. It's just some fairytale. An excuse people use. To get what they're really after.
So, me and your dad? That wasn't real love?
I thought you might've got bored. Sitting in on your lonesome.
Quite happy, thanks.
You not thought about opening a window?
What do you want?
Seeing if you're alright.
Did he put you up to this?
No.
Send you round, test the water.
Is that what this is all about? You sitting in here.
Time was, I didn't even feel like a Branning. Never had him in my life. Didn't want him, I didn't need him. Then up he pops. Like a Jack in the Box...
How many of these you had?
And now I'm seeing double. Everywhere I look there's another Branning.
I'll make some coffee.
No. Just go will you?
Don't you think I know what Max's done to you?
I said, get out. Do you not understand, Jack? I want everything ‚Branning' out of my life. If I could just scrape it out of me.
Bradley. Stop it. What you d'you think you're
Get off me...
Look he's dirt, alright, filth Bradley. He's got problems -
The why did you take him in Jack?! Hey?! Why did you take him in?
I'll have a word with Abi. About ...
No, don't.
You know what she's like, Dreamy Annie. Gets something in her head, says it enough times, starts believing it.
Yeah well she's only gonna get upset in't she. If it's what she really wants. Well i dunno, whatever you think.
Thanks anyway. For letting me come.
It wasn't all for show. Kids, it's one thing I have got to thank you for.
Why don't you just come in for a coffee or something?
No, I better get back. Sean'll be tearing his hair out...
You say it ain't all for show, why don't we just do it, talk to each other. Communicate. For the kids.
Can I top you up?
Are you trying to get me legless?
Canape?
I'd better mop up some of this fizz.
This must've set you back a few quid. If you don't mind me asking?
Well you're only sixty once. Ian's gone to tremendous effort. He's a very, kind, generous man.
Yeah when he wants something.
Really?
He was all over me last night. And you'd be very surprised as to the reason why.
I'm intrigued.
Where else was he gonna go?
I dunno, the street, gutter. Bottom of the Thames'd be nice.
Yeah. That's what I was afraid of. He ain't exactly acting from a sound mind, is he? It's like he wants all this, this chaos. Like he's punishing himself...
For what?
I dunno, I'm not a psychiatrist. Look at ya. Sitting here drinking cheap lager. Not taking care of yourself. What you hoping to achieve?
Achieve? I had it. I had everything. now it's gone.
So you get up. And you start again.
I can't.
You have to.
Everything I had. They've just taken it away from me.

Yeah, if you let them. Bradley, they've mucked up part of your life. You gonna let 'em muck up the rest? You gotta rise above it. Where you go from here. What you take from this, that's up to one person and one person only. You.
So, Jack looking after you is he?
Er yeah, well we just keep out of each other's way. Babe, I'm sorry I just can't do this.
You starting to appreciate how much I did.
Small talk, pleasantries.
It's progress -
Yeah well I want it back, don't I. You, the girls. What we had. I need it back, Tan.
Maybe I should go.

Had this guitar when I was a kid. Saved every penny. Acoustic, nice. I come home one day, Jack and all of his mates had formed a band. We were, I dunno, twelve, thirteen. I saw red. And I smashed it. I loved that guitar, and I smashed it. This is what I do, Tan.
I have been there for you. So many times...
Maybe this time I've learned. I mean, how bad do I have to make things for myself?
Maybe you're just one of them people, who're never gonna be happy.
Maybe it's just gonna take me longer than most, to get it through my thick skull, what happiness is.
Babe, I dunno...
If you smash something into the ground enough times, Max and it dies. It dies.
If I could have your attention. I know, I know. I don't want to spoil your fun.

I just want to say a few ‚thank yous'. To everyone for coming. Especially those from far flung places; Argentina, Ibiza... Barnsley. The older you get, the more rare the occasion, to get so many familiar faces under one roof.

It's a wonderful thing to look around, at so many old, dear and - Trustedfriends. Trust. That's something I've always prized very highly in my life. ‚Where there is no trust, there is no love.' So I'd like to raise a glass. To trust, to love. To old friends.
It's like training a racehorse. He's fallen at the first few hurdles. Up to us to get him back on his feet again.
What if he's gone lame?
There's nothing I can do about that. It's Brenda.
‚It seems like I've known you all my life. Wanna meet up sometime?' Go on then. Answer.
I don't know, maybe Charlie's right, we are meddling.
We're trying to do the man a favour.
Yeah but love, all that doubt and heartache. It's for young people.
Well who said anything about love?
What? You mean, you still - ?
Bit of slap and tickle, keeps a smile on your face - Don't tell me you don't still get ‚urges'.
I wouldn't know. Been on the medication so long...
You need to come down the Legion on a Friday. You get a free Kosovoan with every pint.
She's keen.
Still, if Charlie ain't interested.
Men. Never do know what's good for them.
So. That's it then yeah? Can I still see the kids?
I'd never have stopped you. Not long term. You're a great Dad.
Yeah well. That's something.
Just wish you'd been a better husband.
It's the least you deserve. You're a fantastic woman Tanya. I love you. Always will.
I've got to go.
If there's the slightest chance?
No. There isn't.

All the counsellors in the world'll tell you to go. To leave. But only you and me know what's between us. Please let me come back. One last chance. Foot wrong, I'm out. Please. Please let me come back?
Edward, lovely speech...
How would you like it, Ian? If someone flirted with you.Like you were some kind of a joke?
I wouldn't.
I can't say I'm not very dissapointed.

I guess I got carried away. It was the thought of a lifelong dream coming true. I've got all the books you know. 'Monarchy', 'Diana, Her True Story'... Look Edwards, I am sorry. I really did think of us as friends. If I've ruined that...
All you had to do was ask. Most of my friends are dyed in the wool republicans. I was struggling to find someone to come with me.
You were? I mean, if there's still a chance I could?
Go on then. While you're at it, I've got another spare ticket. Why don't you ask your wife?
I'm going to see the Queen.
Still? I mean, are you? Right, I'm done. So...
Listen Clare thanks ever so much for helping out. I really appreciate it.
Well that's what it's all about, Ian. Loyalty, to friends, Queen, country.
How'd it go?
It was better than expected.
Had to change Oscar. Ye-es. Girls are in bed. Dinner's in the oven. Thought you'd run off with the geography teacher or something.
I bumped into Max. We went for a drink.
Right.
Turns out we had a lot to say.
Yeah well, that's Max for you. Day they put him in the ground, he'll walk his way out of it.
He's moving back in. It's for the best way.
I've got my reasons.
What reasons? YOu know the minute he's back through that door, he'll be back to his old self. All the lying, all the cheating. And what am I? What am I to you? Just disposable?
You think I'm gonna take him back? Into my life, into my bed? After everything he's done? Bit of soft soap, few tears, right back where we started?
No You underestimate me just as much as he does!
Alright then, why? Why you doing it?
Revenge.
You got it bad, mate, ain't you.
We're getting back together.
She's got a cold.
Yeah, I know. She sneezed.
Guinea pigs get colds too.
Marge? Do you need a tissue? She said Abi, stop worrying.
Uhmm..What are you doing up?
I had a nightmare. I dreamt Marge was ill.
Did you now. Go on upstairs right now young lady. You've got school in a couple of hours. Night, night. You're really good with her.
Well you know Dr Dolittle, me.
I meant Abi. Did she ask you why you were here?
Said I was sleeping on the couch.
Go on. I said bed.
I don't think she believed me.
How come you were up?
Couldn't sleep.
We can do this. Look I know you're worried -
I don't care whether your little plan works or not. It's makes no difference to me.
It will. One morning he's gonna wake up and he'll have nothing. I won't even leave him the rat. We'll clean him out.
I just don't want him living here. Alright?
How else can we get our hands on his money? He's got to believe that I want him back.
You and him, here. All nice and cosy.
What do you mean?
When you move him back in. You gonna move him back into your bed, are you?
No. No, of course not. Is that what this is about? How can you even ask me that?
Sorry Tanya. You do this, you're on your own.
No, Sean..
I still don't get it. Round about now she should be cutting the crotches out of your trousers.
Yeah well she loves me, don't she. Always has.
Yeah well what about him?
Steven, I don't want to talk to you so just leave me alone. Oh you alright, mum? I've just come back for some breakfast. D'you want some?
Who was that on the phone then?
No-one. Mum. Leave it. Mum.
Hello?
Stacey it's for you. I'm sorry Stacey's indiscapatiscated at the moment. Oh my goodness. Yes. Hang on hang on. Yes OK this Thursday. Yes. Yes. Thank you. Thank you. Why didn't you tell me?
Walford College. A dress design course. Oh. You've got to take a dress you've made yourself. They said. Will you have time to make one?
I told you. I never contacted them. I'm not going.
But Stacey. They've rung up. Thursday 11 till 4.Open day. I mean, what have you got to lose? And you get to meet the course head. I know she's gonna like you.
Mum. It was Steven who done this. He done it behind my back.
That was kind of him.
You wanna know why he's done this? You wanna know what he's really after?
Look. Look. There is loads of them. He's been watching me, and drawing me. That is one step off of stalking Mum.
Hasn't he caught your eyes well.
Mum!
Morning.
Alright.
Where are you off to?
I thought about what you said.
Yeah. And?
I've still got mates at my old work, thought I'd call round. See if they'll put a word in for me.
Sounds good. You did well there, didn't you?
Yeah. I was only made redundant because my boss left. There must be a way back in.
Bound to be, mate.
I'll let you know how it goes. See you later.
See you later.
Is there anythingfunny about what I'm wearing? It's just that everyone out there seems to be staring at me.
You ain't seen it then.
Seen what? Wow, I never thought it would come out that well. Here Mints. You seen it? You don't half look handsome.
It's all over. I'm sorry, Heather. I can't believe I've been so thick.
No, we look fine. We look great.
Her. Donna. Me and Hazel met her didn't we? She's probably onto them right now, blowing our cover. We're stuffed. I can't believe it we were so close.
Maybe she won't tell them.
In your dreams. You're her competition.
I was counting down the days till I could go and find Hazel.
I'm not giving up. Not now we've come this far.
It's too late.
I'm gonna ring the magazine.
Don't do that. You'll make it worse.
How much worse can you make it?
Where's Jane?
Shopping. She's celebrating Fit for a Queen's taking off. You see. That's how you do it, son. You spot a gap in the market. You go for it. It's what being an entrepreneur is all about.
Cuppa tea please.
What have I done? Did the college call?
What do you think you're doing, going behind my back.
I got the idea off this bloke we catered for, his sister runs a fashion course. It seemed perfect for you.
I don't care. I'm not going.
Why not?
What and have all them college people sneering at me cos I got a market stall? I haven't even got GCSE's.
No-one's gonna -
I'm not interested. Why don't you stop sticking your nose in.
I see... No, you can't fake being in love. No, I can see Donna was never gonna keep it secret for long.
You told them? Are you mental?
It was bound to come out. I'm sorry. Yeah, of course you feel let down. I'll tell Minty.
You could have at least tried to come up with something else.
What's the point? It's best it's over.
It ain't over.
Just face the facts.
Donna's only gone and done a bunk with her fiance's brother.
What?
I was trying to get Donna's phone number. But she's not taking calls. Seeing as they've legged it to Greece. We're still in.
Hang on a minute, if they're out of it, does that mean we've won?
No. They're bumping up the couple from the last round who got knocked out.
Yeah, but they weren't even in the running. You know what this means, don't you? It's in the bag. We've won.
Now hang on a minuite Minty. It only takes one person to ring up that magazine to say that this is not Hazel Hobbs. It's Heather Trott. With somebody elses bloke. And it's sayanora twenty grand.
It's gonna be like living on death row. Never knowing when the phonecall's gonna come to say...
Oh who was the one talking about never giving up? You. Come with me.
Oy. Toy soldier. Had your marching orders yet?
No actually I'm here to stay.
That's what you think. You've served your purpose.
She isn't been complaining about what I've been giving her.
Yeah well she's using you to get at me, isn't she.
Really. Do you even know what she wants, mate?
Yes I do Sean and it ain't you, alright. So get on your bike.
Right you lot. At twoo'clock Heather's gonna make an announcement. So spread the word. She'll even throw in some crisps on the house.
Hang on. I ain't got the staff.
Where's Peggy?
Sals gone and sprained her ankle.
I'll start my shift early.
Yeah? I ain't paying you.
I thought Minty was your mate. I'm doing this favour so they can stay in the competition.
You wanna do them a favour? Tell them to forget about this stupid scam right now.
You've got talent, Stace. They don't care about where you work. You don't need exams or anything. You've just got to make a dress.
Thanks mum.
She cares about you. So do I.
Willo you knock it on the head. I know exactly what you're after.
What am I after?
What. You want me to spell it out?
You think...?
The drawings you done of me.
Drawings?
Yeah I've seen them.
You went through my entire sketch pad?
Why shouldn't I? Don't make out I'm the weirdo. I thought we were mates. But you're all the same, aren't you. Make out you care, but you're only after one thing.
Ian. No Jane today.
She'll be back in a minute.
Don't you trust me?
What can I get you?
Mine's a red wine please Ian.
Yeah, alright, red wine please Phil.
I've rounded up as many as I could.
It's time to make the announcement.
But my mouth's gone all dry.
Stop shoving crisps in it.
They're cheddar flavour. They're all gonna think this is stupid.
Just get on with it.
Hello. Hello. Hello..
Put a sock in it will yeah! Heather's trying to make an announcement.

You've all seen the magazine. Me and Minty, we're engaged, like. We aren't really getting married. Well, we are getting married. Like, you know legally and that. But we ain't getting married. Not properly. Though we are sort of.
Stacey. I don't understand.
Come on. So when's the baby due?
It ain't like that. We ain't doing it for nothing like that. That's why we're in the magazine. See Minty still

For crying out loud. It's like this. They gonna get married and win this competition and get twenty thousand pound. Then Minty goes to find Hazel. Heather goes and has some plastic surgery,and then they all live happily ever after. Only not together. So if anybody from the magazine starts snooping about, you just play along.
Have you told the girls I might be coming home?
No. Not yet. I need to prepare them.
Babe, are you genuine about this?
Are you?
Do you know, if Sean Slater's still in the picture...
No. Of course he ain't.
What and that's the honest truth?
Yeah. What you're accusing me? Since when did I ever look at another man eh? I trusted you. I trusted you all the time I was carrying our child, and you was carrying on with her.
Alright Babe. I'm sorry. You gonna give him the push?
I will. I haven't had a chance, have I?
Well why didn't you do it yesterday?
I didn't see him.
No?
No.
Babe. You can't lie to me, I know you too well. He was round yours last night. I saw him leave. You know all this trust, honesty, all that. It's got to be both ways innit.
I did want to tell him, but I've been putting it off cos I know he's going to take it badly, innit he? What are you doing?
What's it look like?
Tanya. Nothing's changed.
Yeah well that's where you're wrong mate. I've got mywife here. She wants to talk to you.
Sean. I'm with Max. I'vegot something to tell you. I'm sorry, but we're getting back together.
So he swallowed the bait then, has he?
I've thought about it. And it's what I want.
Well. Hook line and sinker. Well done you.
Why? Cos ....cos I still love him.
So you just expect me to sit by while that piece of scum runs his hands all over you. Is that it? Sorry Tan. Like I said. I can't do it.
I'm sorry. Sean. Please You're just gonna have to accept this.
Maybe I should tell him what you're really after.
You wouldn't.
Please Babes. Just let me deal with him, will you.
Wouldn't I?
Now what?
That wasn't my only sketch book, Stace. I don't just draw you.
How was I to know that?
I was gonna show you. You got the wrong idea. We are mates. I know that.
I'm not doing that course.
I'm due down the chippy. Come down later, I'll do you some chips, yeah?
If you keep feeding me chips, I'm gonna be a size twenty.
Hi. You know you said about about the cinema....
Yeah. Look. Now we can get in to any film we want.
Where did you get these?
Does it matter?
I'm not late am I?
For what?
I invited
I thought it was just gonna be you and me.
We can go another time, just us.
I'm not bothered. I was only doing you a favour. And anyway, he won't get into the film. He doesn't look old enough.
I don't want to see a film. I'd refer to go bowling.
We can all do that together.
What me keep score while I watch you two dribble all over each other. No thanks.
Well, if you change your mind....
See you later.
Did I say that chair was free?
No. But I'm not shifting till you let me buy
Alright? Fish not biting?
No. My old mates have all moved on. Even tried ringing my old boss in Japan see if he could put a word in for me, but turns out he's the left the company as well. So...
Something will turn up.
No. I dunno. I thought I'd be fine. I thought I'd walk straight back in. I couldn't even get past reception.
Look you gave it a shot, alright. It's a knock back. That's all. You're gonna bounce back.
Yeah.
Well you're gonna have to get a job before you can afford one of them.
No. I mean. There's bound to be an opening. They're gonna need a salesmen.
Go for it.
You can't smoke in here, Mrs Mitchell.
We're not married.
No. I'm still waiting for him to make an honest woman out of me.
I'm sorry, I shouldn't assume.
That's alright. You'll be surprised at the assumptions some people make about me.
Now Ben. Yes. Ben.
He's fine.
Yes.
He's happy at home. He's a good boy and I wont have anyone tell me any different.
Phil.
He's a smashing kid. He's a pleasure to have in the classroom.
Is he? I know he can be a bit cheeky at times.

Ben? No. He's got a great sense of humour, never oversteps the line. I've got his overall report here. His English teacher says he's making excellent progress. He's clearly got a talent in the subject. I've got some poems here of his.
Poetry? I never knew he did that.
He achieves well across the board.
How about mate's. He's not a big lad. He's not getting pushed about is he?
Not at all. He's a popular boy. And bright. Very bright.
Bright? Blimey. Where's he get that from? Cos it's not from you.
What do you think you were playing at?
What am I playing at?
He was sitting right opposite me. What if he'd heard you?
You take him back, I'll have him gloating in my face.
So? You know the truth.
And what about when he tries to crawl back into your bed eh? What you gonna do? Have a headache? For how long?
The thought of him touching me makes my skin crawl.
Tanya. We don't need his money. He's losing you. The kids. Come on. Isn't that enough?
If it was just me, I'd live out of a suitcase but I cannot ask the children to live off nothing. And if he's broke, he can't come after us.
I don't care if he does. We can manage. Let's just go, now.

He has got to pay for what he did. And I'm gonna hit him where it'll hurt him most. He's not like you Sean. Underneath all the trappings, there's nothing there. So you got to decide. Are you going to help me?
What's he doing here, Tan?
He showed us your poems. They're terrific.
Yeah?
Come here.
He's well cool, Mr Ackroyd.
He's a nice looking geezer.
I got you some fish and chips.
Do you fancy Mr Ackroyd?
No. He's not my type.
You made dad go didn't
No. He just needed a little nudge that's all.
Right. There you go. Oy.
You should have seen your Dad up the school Ben. I had to hold his hand, he was like a little four year old on his first day.
Don't listen to her.
I'd better go and see what's happening downstairs.
She was great at the school.
Dad. Has Shirley got a boyfriend?
No-one in particular. Why? You worried she's after your teacher?
No. He wouldn't be right for her.
I've had enough of you. Get out of my house.
Your house?
Yeah. Like she told you. The party's over. I'm moving back in with my wife.
Don't do this.
I tried to explain but you wouldn't listen.
Yes. Why don't you listen to me. She don't want you.
Yeah. I'll hear that from her, thanks.
Sean. I want Max to come back.
Why do you think she was ever with you? It was to get at me. She ain't interested in you. She never was. If I ever find you sniffing round my wife ever again...
You'll what?
Stop it. Stop it. Both of you.
So you've made up your mind then?
Yes.
I get no choice in it?
No, course you don't get a choice. She's my wife. Now get out of my house.
I want to be with Max.
Well there you go. She can't say it any clearer.
It's what I want.
Nothing I say is gonna change your mind, is it.
No. Nothing.
Fine. If that's the way you want it...
So if I ever catch you..
Stop it. You shouldn't provoke him. He's dangerous.
You gonna be alright? I should get back to work.
You go. I'll be alright.
Listen. Are you gonna tell the girls I'm coming home?
Yes, I'll tell them tomorrow. Then I'll give you a call.
He deserves whatever's coming to him.
So when does Max move back in?
When I've talked to the girls.
Today?
Yes, today. Why?
Just don't need it dragging on, do I.

What you think I do? Sean. Look the sooner Max moves back, the sooner he signs everything over, sooner you, me and the kids can get away from here. That'll be Lauren. Come on. I don't want her finding you still here. Sean, we need everyone to
I'll call alright.
No. Wait for me to call you.
So, when's the first showing? You could do a catwalk up and down the hallway.
Mum, I ain't even started pinning yet.
Oh, don't worry about that, the first bits are always the fiddliest.
Yeah but the Open Day's tomorrow and the rate I'm going you can forget about catwalks. There's no point even going.
Well, silly, why didn't you say?
Say what?
Stacey, if there's one thing I can do it's make
Hang on, mum.
The two of us will get this done in no time. Oh now, we need to put a couple of darts in there. You know what will set this off - some sequins...
No, mum..
Oh, I know what you're going to say - too much and it'll look like that strictly ballroom thingy. Well maybe a bit of braid would be...
Mum, stop! That's really kind and everything but....
But you don't want me to help. You think I'll mess it up.
No. Course not...
No, you're right. I'll get out of your way.
No, mum, listen, I love us doing things together. Honest. Actually there is something you can do. You can cover the stall for Mo while she goes to the wholesaler?
The stall...
Yeah. Please mum.
Well... I want paying mind. First pick of your new collection every year.
Like that's ever gonna happen.
So that's it then? You and Sean are finished?
Yes I thought you'd be glad.
Well I just thought you and him were getting on.
Well, sometimes things aren't how they seem.
Like what?
I don't know. What we want and how we feel.
What's that mean?
It means. Maybe I was wrong. I've got responsibilities. You two. Oscar. There's something else. I spoke to your dad and we talked about giving it another go.
That's great!!
All I'm saying is we've discussed it.
Thanks, mum. I love you. That is like the best news ever!

Line: Papier-mache?

Go on, go and be with your friends. You do my head in anyway.
I don't know what is wrong Shirl but if you just say you want me to come with you, I will. You just have to say.
Why would I want you to stay with me? Eh? I don't even like you.
Has it stained Clare?
No it's fine.
Oh, how an earth did she manage that?
It was just an accident, it'll wash out. Bradley looks like he's having a good time.
Yes, he does doesn't he. Thanks to you.
Oh he's such a lovely guy, I really hope this job works out for him. He deserves it.
Have you got feelings for Bradley?
Of course not, he's a lovely guy but... No, I dunno...
You have, haven't you?
He's had such a horrible time. I wouldn't... Stop it.
You and Bradley. Aw, that'd be wonderful.
Don't you say anything to him ok.
Love is in the air.
Oh, no, oh...
Bradley mate. What you want, yeah, you wanna nice Audi or silver beemer.
I'm selling office units not robbing banks.
Or how about a Porsche. I could just imagine myself cruising up the Kings Road, top down.
Yeah I'd get a Porsche. Bradley I'd definitely get a porshe.
Yeah mate. New job, new wheels, new woman.
Yeah. Yeah yeah right. Yeah, another woman messing with my head.
I'll give Shirley five years. All that booze and all them fags, imagine what her insides must look like.
A bit like the outside. Urgh.
Well you don't see blokes getting that bladdered do you? And mean how's she gonna look anyone in the eye from now on?
Like this probably-
Give it a rest will ya?
This ain't right, I shouldn't have left her. I've gotta see if she's alright.GARRY/
Oi oi oi!
Oi, what about me birthday?
Oi come on, come on, look stay here - have some peanuts...? And Phil can do us a lock in hey?
You are joking ain't ya?
What are they all looking at?
Oi, you call this a party? Come on, who wants some?
What's this?
It's Max's.
Yeah, I know that. But what's it doing here?
Well I dunno, it's been there ages. Don't start getting jealous - I told you he's sleeping on the sofa. Anyway the girls'll be back soon, you better look sharp.
Well what if I don't
What, you don't think I can make you?
Turning down free drinks?
Yeah well, me and mum are going out, so...
Yeah, the cinema, she said.
Yeah, I did just happen to mention it.
Late night horror film, sounds cool. I'd be up for it, if you want-
Take a hint Steven? Come on Mum.
So did you have a few drinks on the plane?
Sssh! Roxy doesn't like the word plane, she prefers flying bar.
This, this is all the way from Austria. Well, it's from the airport, but it is set in Austria.
What did I tell you about disturbing Ben eh?
‚The Sound Of Music?'
Girl's film in'it?
It's a war film. It's about a grumpy old man who falls for a girl who just wants to have fun.
Like Shirley?
Yeah, yeah not exactly like Shirley. And um, why ain't she working anyway?
Dad sacked her.
Come on let's get upstairs, yeah?
Rox, where's Albert's lead?
Er, hanging by the phone.
Hang on, we're busy.
No, you're busy, I've got a headache. And er by the way - welcome back.
Oh Jack, you got my message then?
Listen, why don't I get you a drink?
Actually, look, why don't you all come down to the club? Free entry.
You can't do that.
Minty?
I can't I've got to look after er...
Come on Gal. We're on a mission - we've gotta get Bradley back in the saddle.
Yeah yeah, alrightwell it is me birthday so if
Oi, there's laws against nicking punters! Oi!
Oi, come on, get out of it. Come on you, you filthy mutt ain't ya. Mmm.
Are you taking the Mick?
Just go.
Sorry about that darling, I had the hair dryer on.
You're back early?
Yeah, well you know, they've got the attention span of goldfish ain't they? Where's the charger? Upstairs?
Er, I think so, I'll get it.
It's alright babe I'll go. Lauren's making drinks if you want one.
Are there it is. Babe what's that doing open it's freezing?
Sorry. Ahhh! Ahhh, ahhh, ahhh.
You alright?
No I'm fine, I'm fine, just think I pulled something bowling. What?
Well how old do you sound eh? ‚I hurt myself bowling.'
Yeah well, sleeping on the sofa don't help does it?
Mum, come quick, Marge's eyes are all covered up! And her cheeks are all swollen.
Alright darling I'll be there in a minute.
If you did let me sleep up here, you know, I'd take things slow.
I'll think about it eh. No promises. Come on Granddad.
You must've done something wrong, 'cause you never buy flowers.
Jane likes them. I thought it would be a nice surprise-
Can you read me a story?
I'm a little bit busy mate. Oh, no no, no, please that was the last one in the shop.
Now there's a surprise.
Well as long as the Queen likes it. That's the important thing. I tell you what, your sister'll read you a story, won't you Lucy? I'm going to the chippy to cash up.
How come Peter gets to go out and I have to babysit?
Because... Peter is a good lad who doesn't bring strangers into the house without permission.
Oh, it's so sad. Even Jane's out clubbing.
Jane is not out ‚clubbing'. Okay. She is just ... at the club.
Oh great, look who's here.
Ian with her?
I know he says he didn't do anything, but, well, look at her.
Men don't own up unless something's gonna come out.
Oh. It makes me wanna - Oh I dunno.
Go snog the face off the nearest bloke?
Drinks on me all night if you snog one of that lot.
Yeah, right.
Yeah maybe not. Last thing you need's a knock back.
Oh what what, you think I can't pull anything these days?
What ‚these days?'
Alright, you're on. But I get to choose.
Come on boy. Hi mate, I'm a... a friend of Shirley's, lives upstairs. Shirley, it's me. Look...
... I'm not here for a row, alright?
Come on Shirley, this is stupid, I can hear your phone. Come on Albert, Albert come on.
Hello? Shirley?! Come on out, go on get out. Shirley! Shirley!
Shirley, Shirl. Shirl? Are you alright, are you alright?
Oh Phil. Phil, Phil don't leave me. Don't leave me Phil.
S'alright, s'alright, s'alright.
These are Garry's so don't blame me. Connect Four... Kerplunk...
How can I play games after what I done to Shirley? I feel like a traitor or something.
Buckaroo.
Last time I played that was with Shirley- It was when I was ill. She'd let me win I reckon. She was good like that.
She's a mouthy, sour-faced, old crow, I thought we weren't gonna to mention her?
Anyway cheer up, you're making the donkey miserable, look.
What you looking at?
Bride of Frankenstein?
Aw, what is this?
Just shut up and get it down ya.
Get me that bottle.
Get it yourself.
You're jealous.
Of what?
Jealous that some people can drink for a laugh.
Oh, and this is a laugh is it? Making a prat of yourself and scaring me half to death?
Just get me that bottle!
Here you are then, go on ‚ave it, ‚ave the lot. Do us all a favour. I mean look at the state of you. You're just living like a pig-
What have you just come round here to wind me up or what?
No, for some daft reason I was scared you might be dead.
Well you better go tell everybody the bad news.
You're still here?
At least put a bandage on it eh?
Um, can I buy you a drink while I'm here?
I'll let you into a little secret, I can get ‚em half price. D'you want one?
I'd love one.
Eh Gus, put your tongue away, there's people trying to get past.
We're well out of her league.
You lot might be cos you ain't got no self belief.
No, we just look in the mirror in the morning.
I tell you what, she's proper looking at you Bradley.
Oi, just remember whose birthday it is yeah?
Yeah, I mean if she's looking at anyone, she's looking at Garry.
Yeah and I'm gonna get in there before them other vultures do. Look and learn.
I've er, I've fixed your door. For now anyway. Shirley? Shirl are you...
What you doing, go away from me?!
Alright, calm down, I didn't do anything-
Get away from me...
Just go. Please get out!
I ain't going anywhere. I'm gonna call an ambulance.
No Phil. Phil I ain't going to hospital. I don't want to-
I don't care what you want alright.
No Phil I ain't going to no hospital!
You might be concussed you idiot-
I'm alright, I'm fine, please
Phil...
Alright, alright. Just hold on, alright, just hold on? Yeah, I need an ambulance. Yeah.
So are you thirty six or forty six?
What?
Are you thirty six or forty six? D'you fancy a dance?
Ey?
A dance, come on let's have a dance?
Dance, yeah, yeah, yeah alright.
Is she like that with everyone?
Not with me. We talked Greek philosophy. Yeah, that and who her favourite Tellytubby was.
Jack?
Oh ‚ere we go. D'you mind?
No, no, go for it. I'll be right here.
He's only toying
What's the matter, jealous?
Can you wait here a minute?
Why, where you going?
I'll be back. Stay right there.
Sorry luv, look I'm waiting for someone here.
Go on Garry.
Get in there my son.
There's so many creeps in this place. Will you just stand by me or soemthing, pretend to be my boyfriend?
I don't think we make the most convincing couple do you.
Hey, I could so pull you.
Well, no no, what I meant was...
Look I'm joking. And what's a normal couple anyway?
I've got no idea anymore.
Exactly. Hey look can you put your arm round me.
You what?
Put your arm round me. Quick.
Are you ok? We can go if you want.
No I'm here now ain't I.
I'm glad we can still talk though. You know, after... The other day?
It was a kiss Steven, get over it.
As long as we're still friends yeah?
Stace? Hello?
She's not going to die is she?
Course she ain't babe. Just gotto keep her warm that's all.
We'll take her to the vets first thing, they'll sort her out.
Yeah, similar sort of thing happened to when you were a baby. Your little eyes got all gunked up with something.
Gross.
You couldn't see, and your little arms were waving about.
Your dad was up all night putting drops in.
Don't worry Marge, you'll be ok.
All this fuss over a hairball.
Oi, Lauren. She's part of the family, in't she Abi?
She's my baby.
I'll do us all some hot milk for bed, shall I?
You alright Tan?
Yeah, no I'm fine darling, I just stubbed my toe, that's all. What the hell do you think you're doing?!
Was gonna ask you the same thing.
They're only next door.
Yeah I know, you Max, happy families, I heard it all-
Sean please I'm begging you-
Yeah, how's his back by the way? I mean I've told some whoppers in my time but I mean-
He is not getting into my bed alright.
Promise me...?
Yes. I promise you. Please will you just go. Sean.
Closing time, it's like a freak show out there. Anyway, theysaid it won't be long.
Good, you can go home then.
Told you, I don't mind staying.
What if I don't want you here? Phil I really wanna be on my own. Am I talking to myself or what?
Well it's only fair in'it. You got to laugh at me when I was off me head.
Oh, cheers. I didn't have much choice did I.
It's weird in'it eh? I mean what's the matter with us?
Doesn't matter now does it?
It's Kev in'it? People, you know, they react different I suppose. It was the same with me you know, with Ben. Well look, I know it's not
Yeah... look what good it did him. All that worrying about family and money. What's the point?
That's life in'it.
Is it? 'Cause I don't know. I ain't done anything. Screw up - screw other people up. And I always think, you know one day it'll sort itself out. But it never does. And I mean... It's like Kevin...
Hello - Miss Carter?
Yeah. That's us.
You'd better go.I'll see you later Phil.
I'm Doctor Kahn, let's have a look.
See I reckon that marriage is like a bicycle. I mean you get a puncture, yeah sure you can repair it. But then you know at some time or later it's gonna burst again.
Garry, what you on about?
Just saying - sometimes it's nice to ride a new bike.
Garry, d'you mind, I need a word with my brother. You're pathetic, do you know that?
What? I unearth a secret admirer-
No, you just told the local lech that I've split up with Ian.
All I want is for you to wake up and start having some fun that's all.
Oh right. You mean you wanna start having some fun?
What?
'Cause again I'm the one who's with someone and you can't stand it.
I'm sorry - but that coming from ‚Mrs Ian Beale?' Fairy tale come true.
So you do what you always do, you try and mess my life up to make yourself feel better. You couldn't even handle seeing me with Jack.
I am trying to get you to see what an idiot Ian is.
Yes, well I want it to stop.
Yeah well.
No Christian! If you dare try to ruin my marriage-
Like I need to-
You dare. Then you can leave Walford right now.
You're not looking for Bradley are you?
No Steven.
Yeah well he left a while ago.
What?
I was just seeing if you wanted another drink?
Oh well why don't you have this one.
Oi, what are you doing?
Jane?
Hang on. I'm really sorry.
Thanks.
Extra pillows so you're not complaining about your back tomorrow an' all.
Thank you. You're amazing.
I know.
But I just wish I could lie with you that's all. Babe, I wouldn't do anything, I'd just lie with ya. What d'you say Tan? Please.
Oh great, go on I could do with a laugh.
I saw you watching Bradley.
... What?
I'm sorry, I just thought the last thing you needed was me in there as well.
So you just left?
Not the best idea was it.
What happened to your top?
Jane. Another Beale that's off their head.
I borrowed these off of Lucy. I thought seeing as you missed your film. I am sorry. It won't happen again.
Look Steven if we're gonna try this going out thing you've got to stop all this weird stuff, I mean it.
You mean it,you wanna give it a try?
I just said didn't I.
You can come in for a coffee. I must be off my head.
Bradley ... You've got to move on, you know that?
Yeah. Yeah I know. It's um, it's just a bit hard you know -
Look, it'll be ok. You can do it. Come on. Let's go home yeah?
Oh, steady, steady..
I did it! I am the champion - I am the champion.
I don't believe you, you beat me at every single game.
I did do the right thing didn't I? About Shirley. I can win on my own.
There's still the heart to go yet. Get the heart and then you win.

Well there's no sign of any serious head injury so that's good. Take this through. Okay. You've got some bruising. So I'm just going to check for any fractures, okay, it might hurt a little. Can you take a deep breath for me?
Loser, loser, loser, loser!
Next one, come on next one.
Okay the next one is...
Kerplunk!
Okay.
Gal...Gus reckons that you were so ratted last night you were all over Jane like a rash.
Didn't hear her complaining.
Let's phone her up and see.
Oh no you don't - come here you doughnut. Get off, get off!
Hello.
Shirley's phone's gone straight onto voicemail, it was ringing before.
Maybe her battery's flat?
She's probably still too angry to talk to me.
She's probably indoors polishing her cauldron.
Anyway I thought you were gonna let things lie for a couple of days?
Its been on my mind all night. We're mates and I turned my back on her.
Well it still don't give her right to be such a cow.

Minty, the intricacies of the female friendship are a mystery mate. They're not governed by any sort of logic, that is why it's impossible to try and understand them. I mean you take Lynn and her sisters right, one minute they'd be screaming blue murder, the next doing each others make-up!
Not sure me and Shirl will be making up so easily this time.
Hello, what's your name and where d'you come from? Marni? Yeah. Today?
Come on, you've got to keep running all the way through the line.
That's pathetic.
We're only training.
You have got to give one hundred per cent all the time if you're gonna shine at Sport Relief.
Course.
Come on.
...high on a hill was a lonely goatherd...laydl...laydl
Oi Ben, couldn't lend us twenty pence could you?
Does he look like a cash machine?
I just didn't have enough for a bacon roll. Cheers mate. You're a bit chirpy ain't you?
It's from a musical, The Sound of Music. Do you know it?
Who do you think I am. Billy Elliot?
You'd love it, Julie Andrews is brilliant.
I'm a sporting man, me.
Oh yeah?
Yeah. Boxing's my thing. Dad reckons I'm a natural so he put me in for some competition.
Boxing competition?
Some Sport Relief thing down at the Community Centre. No-one stands a chance against me.
Your grandad was a boxer, Flash Eric they called him. Had a good right hook, him.
Maybe you should have a go, Ben. Might be in the blood.
Sounds boring.
Listen do us a faviour, grab us a table, I won't be a minute.

Line: I know it's early but I just..just wanted tohear your voice...remind me whatI'm missing.

Line: I know, I miss you too, darling. I've only got aminute, the girls'll be down soon.

Scene_info: SQUARE/GARDENS/INT TANYAS HOUSE EXT DAY LIGHT
Line: Hello.

Scene_info: SQUARE/GARDENS/INT TANYAS HOUSE EXT DAY LIGHT
Line: Right now, I should belying next to you, feeling yourskin and thinking how beautiful you look in the morning.

Scene_info: SQUARE/GARDENS/INT TANYAS HOUSE EXT DAY LIGHT
Line: Just Jane.
This milk is disgusting I'm not eating this. Don't see why I should have manky milk and he gets the works.
That's part of his training programme, innit.
It's not fair. Golden boy.
Dad says I've got Olympic potential. It
You'd understand if you'd shown potential for anything besides getting into trouble. That reminds me,love. We can't leave these two on their own while we're away.
If you're that bothered I'm sure Christian can keep an eye on the kids. Didn't you say you wanted to spend more time with the family the other night?
Can we go to the new theme park?
Why not, I love watching overweight tourists throw up after they've been on one ride too many.
Excellent.
Listen I thought I'd have a little dress rehearsal for Monday, OK. So, when I meet her Majesty, shall I smile like this? Or like
Depends, are you auditioning for the Joker?
Look I just wanna look reverential, yet at ease. I don't want her thinking I'm some local yokel.
Well, you look constipated.
Just try and relax, look natural.
These trousers feel a little bit looser, I'm sure I've lost some weight?
...I should've known something was wrong when you didn't answer your phone. Are you sure you're alright ‚cause you're really quiet.
No permanent damage.
Only you hear these stories about people getting post traumatic stress days later. Why don't you put your feet up, aand I'll look after you. I'll get you something to eat?
Will you stop fussing!
I'm only trying to help.
What you doing here anyway, hadn't you better get back to loverboy?
I was worried about you.
Yeah? Well you turned your back fast enough on me when Minty clicked his fingers.
But I'm here now. I thought near death experiences changed people for the better.
Look, you've cleared your conscience, now go bother someone else. I've got things to do. And Heather? Take these back!
Thanks Mum!
Morning.
What's wrong with madam this morning?
She was up late looking after Marge. I said I'd take her to the vets later.
I was thinking maybe we should get in touch with the solicitors, let them know we're putting the divorce on hold.
We haven't agreed that.
Well no we ain't. Not in so many words, but I'm home innt I. It's only a matter of time innit.
It's a bit sudden that's all.
Is it? if you change your mind...?
No. I'm not saying that. But just...um I don't think we should rush things, you know. I don't want to let the kids get their hopes up. Or mine. I couldn't go through all this again Max.
Baby you won't alright. I told you, I'm one hundred per cent committed. The only question is, are you?
...you hang up.
...no you.
No you.
No you hang up.. What's your problem?
She's in trouble. Again.
Oh shut up Peter.
I'm so sick of those two acting like I'm the evil twin. I'm gonna teach my dad a lesson.
So, you're alive then.

Yeah course. Hard as a rock. I'd have to be, the number of times I've crashed out after a night out. Anyway, I expect the punters have been missing my sparkling wit, so when are you going to give me a shift?
Have you forgotten what happened?
About you sacking me, I won't hold that against you.
You drink too much. You only turn up when you feel like it. Now you wanna come back to work as if nothing's happened?
Careful, you sound concerned.
If you're gonna be behind the bar I need to know you're not gonna lose it.
Who are you? Flipping Mother Theresa!
Hang on, where are you going?
Anywhere. Away from people suddenly concerned about my welfare!
I bet you're wonddering if he's gonna be a chip off the old block?
Hope so mate.
Running around the Square, breaking hearts all over the place. Just like his old man.
Ian. Look I made a mistake alright, granted, it's all out in the open. Tanya still took me back, didn't she.
It's like water off a duck's back to you.
You reckon, do you? Or is it that blokes like you are too gutless to admit when you've been tempted?
Haven't seen much of you lately, how are things at home?
Yeah they're great. They're great. Max is being really attentive, you know. And the kids are happy to have him back.
Look. It's ages since we had a proper catch up. Why don't you come round to ours this week, we can have a chat, a drink. Make a night of it. How about Thursday?
Yeah that'd be great wouldn't it Max.
Sorry, what?
Drinks, ‚round Ian and Jane's on Thursday?
Drinks with Max and Tanya? That'll be fun, yeah. Why don't you invite your brother along as well, the more the merrier.
That's a good idea, innit. We'll get all the local movers and shakers together, mix a bit of business and pleasure.
Take it things didn't go too well then?
I tried talking to her but she didn't wanna know.
Oh well. She's a big girl, she'll get over it.
She's not as tough as everyone thinks. She needed me and I let her down, and all because of this stupid competition.
Yeah, about that. Marni's coming over this afternoon.
Oh. Not today Minty, I can't. It doesn't seem right with Shirley not talking to me. She was supposed to my bridesmaid.

Look, I'm sorry you've fallen out but you've gotta put it behind you now, alright. You've gotta help me convince Marni that we deserve to win this wedding. Otherwise... ...you can forget about bridesmaids dresses, ‚cause we won't be needing one.
How the hell did you get in here?
I rang the bell but no-one answered.

‚Cause I don't want any visitors. Is that what you do, is it when you think no-one's about? You come in and snoop around? Oh. Bet you love rummaging through my underwear drawer, don't you. Fiddling with my knickers.
I'd forgotten, this ain't a bad little flat. Make a nice get-away.
What you on about?
The missus caught me in a compromising position with her best friend and now she can't stand the sight of me.
What's that gotta do with me?
She needs some space and I need somewhere to lay low for a few weeks.
No way!
Like you've got a choice. I kicked you out, remember? Heather Trott's on the lease. And by the looks of things wherever your mate is, she ain't staying here.
Look, this is a really bad time for me, can you just give me a couple of weeks to find somewhere else?
Not a chance. It's been a pleasure Shirl, but I want you out. Now.
Come on Babe. I thought the whole point of having a day off was to relax?
No chance, I've still gotta take Marge to the vet's yet.
You haven't stopped have you. Tell you what. Why don't we knock Thursday night on the head?
Eh? And what, miss out on the chance to have some good conversation, some nice wine It'll be....
...about as much fun as sticking my head in a bucket of ice.
I know that! I don't wanna play happy couples with Walford's answer to Cassanova, either!
They why didn't you say something!

I know all this competition stuff can be pretty intense but there's been a development I had to pass on in person. It has emerged Donna, from one of the other couple's, was having a bit of fun on the side with her fiance Paul's brother and they've run off to Greece!
Oh! No way! Oh dear.
So, it's down to you two and Craig and Sammy from Gravesend. Should you be the lucky bride, Hazel, we'll have to check availability for a four page 'bride-to-be photo shoot' in your dress.
Isn't it bad luck if he sees me in the dress before the wedding? Like we haven't had enough already.
It won't be the outfit. We want to keep the readers guessing.
Of course.
We'll probably do some editorial too. Your views on the wedding. Bridesmaids, hen night, that sort of thing. I'm sure you've thought about it? Hazel, are you okay?
It's my friend, we've fallen out and...
It's just the wedding. She's just a little bit emotional.
Don't worry, you wouldn't be the first bride to be to find it a little bit overwhelming.
It's not the wedding...well it is ‚cause Shirley, she was going to be my bridesmaid and... Shirley! Shirley
Aah, so you're the bridesmaid? I'm Marni, from the magazine.
Look. Now's not a very good time. So maybe...
From what Hazel was just saying, now's the perfect time.

Hazel's so excited about the competition. And you know, I was sitting at home, and I was thinking, as a mate, what's the best way I can help her support her needs? And then it came to me. Hazel is in this competition to win, and I'm her best mate. So I decided to move in and help?! So, we'll all be one big happy family!
I don't know what you think you're playing at but you ain't staying here. Alright?
I've got nowhere else to go.
Well, I'm sorry but...
If I were you, I'd keep me onside at the moment, cos I can go in there and say anything.
How does someone as lovely as Heather, end up with someone like you as a mate?
Sorry, but I've got no choice.
Minty! Darling? Is everything alright?
When I came in here, I saw her face and she needs me. And if she does, so do you.
Now. It's all coming together.I have one last competition update.
Oh?
Tomorrow's the final round of the competition. And you'll be taking The Lurve Test!
The Lurve Test?
It's a quiz we've put together to see which couple knows each other the best. Whoever wins is the perfect love match!
...your grandad won this going up against Pretty Boy Graham. North East London Divisional Championship. Champion of the whole of the East End, he was.
Why do boxers have those funny names?

It's just how it's done ‚Iron Mike' Tyson, ‚Baby' Joe Mesi. Y'know boxers earn their names ‚cause of their reputation or their style. Only Graham wasn't so pretty after doing six rounds with Flash Eric.
Did grandad win any more trophies?
