Alright then, not that I've got any choice. Three conditions, OK. I don't want anything we need to walk. I don't want anything too noisy, or nothing too dangerous, alright. Go on then.
Alright madam. Happy? Let's go. Thank you.
Well, thanks for visiting. What the view out of that window better than the one in your own gaff, is it? Is someone after you or something?
No, I think that's your problem. Steven Beale's on his way over.
Well he's not after me, we're just mates.
No, course not. I'm going to nip out. Give you love birds some privacy. You alright, stalker. She's in there.
Why's he calling me a stalker?
Just ignore him. What's up?
D'you want to go to a party?
Yes, alright. Where is it?
At our house. Lucy's gone into meltdown. Invited half of cyber space.
Babysitting a bunch of fourteen year olds? No I'm alright thanks.
Oh come on, Stace, I've got to be there, make sure the house doesn't get trashed.
Well you go, then come and meet me down the pub when you get bored.
What's in this?
Everything. Have some more.
Is this it? Bit crap, innit?
Well get lost then - it's just starting alright.
Well, let's liven things up a bit, shall we? Want some?
Drop dead.
'Ere d'you hear that, love? It's only a fifteen minute walk through the park to the Palace.
Yeah.

Nice little morning stroll before the investiture. Obviously, if it's raining we'll get a limo. Here you go. Thank you. It's alright. You're welcome. I tell you what. That is the last time they get a tip off of me. Obviously they're paying them too much when a fiver's not worth a thank you. Right, how about a nice bit of bubbly?
I think you'd better check how much it costs first.
Don't worry love, I brought some with us. If I stick it in here, it should chill it down nicely. While we're waiting for it to chill, how about a nice regal gin and dubonnet, ice and a slice?
Oh, lovely. Very posh.
I'll get that ordered. I tell you what. Why don't you choose something off the room service menu and um...slip into something more comfortable?
Well, um, actually, I was thinking about having a bit of a soak. It's a beautiful bathroom, and I thought, well, it'd be nice and relaxing - get me more in the mood. D'you mind?
No, I might even come and join you. Right. I'll get those drinks ordered. Don't make the water too hot, though, makes my skin go all blotchy.
Come on, Minty. Stop brooding about it now eh. Come on, let's go down the pub and drown your sorrows.
Heather was right.
Eh?
It was a message. I phoned round all the cruise companies. This ship was in dock at Southampton all week. It set sail for the Caribbean today.
Maybe it's just a coincidence.
Is it? Look, at the postmark. This card came yesterday, right. It must've got caught up in the junk mail - if I'd seen it I could've got down there in time.
It don't mean to say my Mum was on that ship.
I'll never know now, will I. I've blown it. Again. Story of my life.
Tanya, he's playing you, all over again - why can't you see that?
No. He will. He'll sign them.
Oh, wake up -
He's got no choice.
If that was true he would have already done it, wouldn't he. Look he's got everything he wants. He's back here, he's got his home, his family -
No. He hasn't got me. And he never will have.
Just kick him out. I don't need Max's money, all I need is for us to be together.
And we will be babe, as soon as he's signed those papers.
Well how long's that gonna take? A week? A month? Years?
No. Today. Alright. I promise. It's you I want. Just trust me. Yeah?

Alright, alright, I'm coming, I'm coming. Come on in.- those should've been here when we arrived. Just stick that over there, anywhere will do. Yeh that's fine, fine, fine. I gave your mate a tip. Half of it's yours, yeah? See ya.
Was that lunch? I'm starving.
Close your eyes.
What for?
Close your eyes. I've got
Yeah. You can open them. I love you.
I love you too.
Right, I've told Lucy, that's it now. OK? She can't keep letting people in that she's never seen before. So that's enough, OK?
Yes, like she gonna listen to me.
I'm just saying, don't answer the door to anyone else. If it gets any bigger, I want you to come to the pub and get me.
Yep.
Right, have you finished being forty? They're fine. Just leave them to it.
I know. What an eddie.
It just weren't meant to be, mate - and that's that. Isn't that right?
Absolutely. There's no point in moping about it. You gotta live every day as if it were your last.
The world's your oyster. And you do anything you like.
Except go to the Caribbean obviously. You don't want to meet up with you know who.
There's an idea - I could go into the Caribbean, and meet her boat when it docks.
Oh, that's so romantic.
Yeah. If she'd had been on the boat to begin with.
Yeah. Which she weren't. And besides, anyway, you can't afford it. It's gonna cost at least a couple of grand. You haven't got that kind of money.
We've got twenty grand coming from the wedding magazine.
Yeah that's right. All I have to do is phone up Marnie, and ask her for an advance on our wedding -
They'll never give it.
No chance.
There's no harm is asking though, is there?
Oh, will you shut up.
I'm going to do it. I'll phone her now. Ask Phil for the time off. I could be on my way by tomorrow. You are a genius.
So you going to pay for the therapy?
Doughnut.
It's a chinchilla. His name's Gilbert. Do you want to hold him?
No, I do not.
I'm going to keep it him in my room, because he needs lots of space to run around, and he can jump up to five feet.
Oh, well, isn't that practical?
Right, you want to go round Dots then - play with him round there.
Oh yeah, Dad's already phoned her. I think I'll stay there for dinner.
Yeah. Give us a bit of time on our own.
Great.
Oh thank you for letting me have him. He's the best chinchilla ever. Come on, Gilbert.
Right. Come on. See you later Gilbert. Go straight there eh?
I will. Bye.
Mind the road.
It's getting a bit lively over there. Over at the Beale's. I think Steven's having a party.
I don't know why they put up with him. He's been nothing but trouble has he.
Yes, well, you love them, what can you do?
That was Marge. I'll never forget her or Rolf. Come on, let's go and see grandma.
Let me get this straight. You want two weeks off work so you can fly to Jamaica to get on a cruise ship that Hazel might not even be on.
No, she is, I can feel it. It's like a...I can't explain it. It's like a love thing, you know.
You need help, mate.

No, I know it sounds crazy but it's fate, believe me. Which is why I've got to take this. Wait, this is it. Hi Marnie. Yeah. Thanks for getting back to me so promptly. Yeah. So you got my message? Yeah about the cheeky little advance on the winnings.
What? Oh no, you're joking.
What's she saying?
She says the twenty grand isn't a cash prize. It's for the wedding and the honeymoon, and they arrange all of that. Isn't there even any spending money?
You better cancel that liposuction.
I think he could do with another drink, don't you?
You might want to think about locking them doors before they start coming in here - go and have a look. It's carnage out there.
I knew it.
Wow. It looks like we've got ourselves a party. Brilliant.
That's my Dad's house.
What the hell do you think you're doing?
Well, maybe that's Banksy. Excuse me mate. Are you Banksy?
Right, that's it, everybody out.
What the hell are you doing?
What you should've done. Right, everybody out or I'm calling the police.
Don't worry, party'sstill on.
Lucy
Why are you such a wimp. What are you doing with this loser? Must be charity week, eh?
It's out of control.
No, it ain't. No-one's done the tv yet. Come on let's party.

Is it Marm or your Majesty? Suppose I'd better ask one of the footman on the way in. 'ere. Hope she don't bring them corgis with her. You know what I'm like with dogs. One of them'll probably growl at me. Blow my chance of getting close enough to the Queen to say hello.
Ian?
Yeah?
Is this how you get in the mood? Cos it's not how I do.
Sorry. Is this working for you cos my thumbs are killing me.
Mate I tell you what. This is the best party ever.
I suppose one of us is going to have to call the police at some point.
Nah, it's just kids letting off steam, innit. I mean, no-one's getting hurt. Where's the harm in it eh?
Live and let live. You're a persuasive man, Phil. Whose round is it?
I'll get these. Same again, yeah?
Cheers Charlie.
Yes, cheers Charlie, thanks.
Police. Hello police? There's a riot happening. Albert Square.
So that's it is it? I sign these, and that makes everything alright. I give you a hundred grand and everything's back to how it was, is it?
If you want to call me a prostitute,....
I didn't say that, did I Tan. It's quite a fee.
I'm quite a woman.
Which is why I want you. Want you back - what we had. A proper marriage. No holding back. And if this is what it takes .. I'll pay you to love me.
It's not about the money, Max. It never was. All I've ever wanted is you. That's all.
Just ignore it. It'll go away. I told them, we don't want to be disturbed.
Oh, for goodness sake, just answer it Ian.
What? Yes, that's my son, put him through. Steven? No, me mobile's switched off What's up?
Look, I'm sorry about this. It's just that we've had a bit of a situation. No, it's fine now, and I can handle it. it's just that there's someone here who wants to talk to you.
Is that Mr Beale?
I love you, Tan. It's all going to work out alright, I promise. We've made the breakthrough. No turning back, alright?
No turning back.
Yes, take your time - don't hurry on account of my piles, will you, you fat lump.
Mum. What are you doing here?
You sent me a postcard, didn't you? I've come to meet my future son-in-law? What is he? Some kind of half wit?
No.
There's got to be something wrong with him. Who on earth'd want to marry you, pig?
You are joking.
It might not be her fault. Thanks. Let's just try and keep rational and find out what happened.
This is what happened.
Oh, no. No Lucy.
You should see upstairs. Your room particularly.
I'll go up.
Welcome home.
Dad, I'm sorry. I tried to stop it -
Yes, he was a good little boy, you've got him trained really well. Maybe if you lock me up in a mental asylum, I'll behave myself too.
It was a private clinic and don't think I haven't thought about it. Why Lucy?
I don't have to answer to you.
I've had enough of this.
Get off me.
You are going to change and I am going to make you, d'you understand me? This has got to stop or you can just get out. You are ruining everyone's life including your own.
No. You ruined my life. You did when you drove out Mum.
Oh, I drove your mum away, and your life would've been so much better if you'd have gone with her -
Yes, actually -
Well I wish you had.
Dad. What the hell are you doing?
Lucy, I'm sorry. So sorry.
Thought you were going to join me in the shower?
I was a bit tired.
Last night was better than ever. What's all this? Anything interesting?
It's nothing important.
It's from the solicitors.
That don't say anything about cancelling the divorce. I thought you were going to call her.
We've had a lot on, haven't we. I just haven't had a chance.
Well, it's important, isn't Babe. Call them this morning.
Alright. Just leave it. Stop pushing. I'll do it in me own time.
I just thought things were sorted, you know, we were moving on. Babe, come on, I've signed these, aven't I.
Look, I'll post them on my way to work.
No I tell you what. You call the solicitors and then I'll post these share forms. Alright? Yeah, deal?
Deal. Yeah. I will ring, promise.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: These are totally ruined. What sort of people do this?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: ‚People' our daughter calls friends.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: They weren't Lucy's mates, they gate crashed.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: What did she expect, advertising a party on the internet?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Our lovely home. The window, the telly. We've only just finished

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Maybe the insurance will cover it.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Paying out for a teenager's party - no chance.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I can't believe the police didn't arrest anyone - I mean, look at that, it's criminal damage.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You know what. I hope you're grounding Lucy for a year!

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Make that two years.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: My room stinks of smoke and I got no sleep!

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Get your sister down here. It's her mess, she can clean it up.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: She's not in her room.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Lucy's gone

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Probably gone off in a strop.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Did Bobby see her leave?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Dunno. He's still asleep.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Oh. Do you know what. Typical Lucy, sneaking out early to avoid clearing up.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Sometimes we all go too far. Maybe if you both said sorry.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Excuse me. She's the one who needs to apologise. I hope you made her realise how upset we are, Ian.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yeah, yeah. I think we should go start getting ready. Don't want to be late for the Palace, can we.
Look we've all got to get to work, so..
Don't let me stop you. Heather knows how to look after me.
Course I do mummy.
Look. The thing is Mrs Trott, I don't mean to be rude but this was a one night deal.
Can't mummy stay a bit longer?
It's like a tin of sardines in here - no.
Well I'm going nowhere till I get some answers. You run out on me and the next I hear, you've changed your name to Hazel and you're marrying this porky baldy?
You said I'd never get married. I thought you'd be pleased.

Look Mrs Trott, Heather's been a real mate, OK. Now, I was supposed to marrying Garry's mum but she kind of did a runner. Alright, now Heather stepped in and saved the day. Now if we win this wedding competition, we stand to bag a couple of grand, right.
He's only marrying you to get his hands on the cash.
I'll call you a cab. You're going home.
I can't go home! When you left, your sick old mum couldn't keep the flat clean. I've been evicted, I'm homeless!!
Dad, where's Marge gone?
Listen Babe. Don't be too upset, alright. It looks like a fox has had her.
Marge has been eaten. Will she still go to heaven?
Yeah course she will. You alright, son.
Alright Abi.
Bradley, I've got some bad news. Marge died, we buried her here but it looks like a fox has had her.
Oh I'm sorry. Poor Marge. Well you gave her a great life - that's all that matters really.
I'm going to have a proper memorial for her tonight. Can you come? And then I can show you my new pet, Gilbert the chinchilla. He is so cute.
i would. I would. It's just it's my first day in a new job, you know.
I've hardly seen you lately.
Alright, listen. How about I take you and Lauren down the ice rink this week.
Thanks.
That sounds good, dunnit. We should all come, you know, make it a family night.
I think I'll just take the girls, you know.
Abi, go get yourself some sweets. Don't tell your mum. She really misses you Bradley, and Lauren, we all do.
Yeah. Well it's not like I can just drop in anymore is it?
You can't take what happened out on your sisters.
I'm not.
But it looks that way to them. Why don't you come for Abi's sake not mine. Hello, yeah, I'm phoning on behalf of Tanya Branning, yes she'd like to make an appointment.
We sold any of this stock?
No. Word needs to get out about our new lines. Do you remember Jalil Iqbal from when we used to visit uncle Amir in Slough?
The nerdy little geek with the big ears and the braces?
Oh come on he was such a cute little boy.
Are we talking about the same Jalil here?

He has just finished his Masters in Business Studies and your father's convinced him to work here in the post office for free, to get experience. I hope he doesn't go poking his nose round in our books!
I thought I was helping now?
Oh well it's a shame that you were too busy out partying all night to get a business degree! Anyway, it's too far for him to travel so he's going to be staying with us.
A strange man is moving into our house and I wasn't consulted?
He's not strange. You and him go way back.
Mum, Jalil's not really my type.
Of course he is. A man with the world at his feet. You never know, he might be the one.
Alright Shab?
No. Mum's playing matchmaker.
A new fella's just what you need.
You haven't seen him. He's got a face only a mother could love!
Shabnam get back to the house please. I want the whole place spick and span ready for Jalil's arrival.
Eh. So how did it go last night? The papers - to control Max's money. Did he signed them or what?
Yeah.
Hey. Hey that's great. How did you convince him? Tanya, tell me you didn't.
Tanya. Tell me you didn't sleep with him, please.
I had to, right. He was about to walk. It was the only way I could make him sign 'em. I'm sorry. We're free now. You can book the flights, cos we're leaving.
You remember when we were in Chicago and they dyed the river green for St Patrick's day?
Yeah. Looked amazing. You reckon Phil's up for trying that with the canal?
We are going to kick the club's butt tonight and we're going to pack this place out with fit Irish boys - result.
Ooh. It's nice to see you made an effort.
Slept in a hedge?
Look I couldn't have a shower. Heather's ogre of a mother used all the hot water. What could I do?
Have a cold one. What you letting yourself go or something?
They're only having a laugh, you can take it can't ya?
That's me Phil - I can take anything.
Max?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Cheers luv. I've dreamed of this day all my life. Meet the Queen, write the Beale name in history.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I can't believe Lucy managed to ruin it for your Ian.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: IF I could just find her. If I could just talk things through with her.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: She'll waltz back when school's out, pretend she's had a hard day. Look. I'm all for treating the kids like adults, Ian. But after this, you've got to lay down the law.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Maybe I've been too hard on her. Perhaps we should try that counselling you suggested, see if that works.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Well you've got to sort her out! The way Lucy's going it'll be an ASBO next.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I don't yell at Peter, do I. Don't get this grief off of him.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Well Peter's different - he does what he's told and he hasn't utterly trashed our house! When she comes back - you've got to put your foot down Ian. It's the only way.
Tan? You alright babe, you back for lunch?
Yeah. You posted those forms yet?
Yeah. Course, I have. They went first class, we had a deal didn't we?
Yeah we did.
That's why I phoned your solicitor's secretary - arranged a meeting for Friday.
You did what?
You and me were always going to get back together, weren't we? You're not going to divorced me. Take the kids. I won't let it happen.
So has Jabba the Hut done one yet?
No chance. Queenie's gonna take some shifting.
We've got to find some way of getting her out.
I've got it!
Check em out sis. Few outfits for tonight. With these on, look we're gonna be pulling all night. Top of the morning to you.
Tell you what. I'll really be fighting off the boys with this on, won't I.
Irish Rugger shirt for you Phil.
Do me a favour.
Spoil sport. And, Shirley, look, check out your new outfit.
There's no way you're getting me to look like a Riverdance reject.
Come on. I thought you were the original party girl.
I'm not wearing it - end of.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Hello. Jane. Jane. Sorry. I did knock.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Sorry, babe. It's absolute chaos in here.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yes. Jane. You should have seen Lauren, after the party, she threw up all over the place. She was in a right state.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: If Christian had looked after Lucy properly nobody would have got drunk!

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No one's to blame.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I don't know what we've got to do to make Lucy grow up, she's running completely wild. Sorry, look at me going on - are you alright, you look a bit tired?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No. I'm fine. I'm fine. Things have never been clearer.
I've got to get out of here.
You've got no chance.
Tell mum a friend's called and she really needs me. I can't let her down.
I'm not lying to her, what's in it for me?
Shabnam, let's pick out what you're going to wear tonight - you want to make a big impression.
Cover my back and I'll treat you to a science magazine.
Make it two and we've got a deal.
Okay. Just be convincing, yeah.
Shabnam? Shabnam?
She had to rush off...something about helping a friend.
She's got you lying for her hasn't she?
No.
Well maybe my stopping your pocket money will help you tell the truth!

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Dad, is Lucy back yet?
Heather?
Queenie?

Right. First rule of negotiations Minty, alright. Always get your hands on what the enemy want. Now Queenie will do absolutely anything for Orville over there. OK? Trust me. Hello Pretty, Pretty, Pretty. Come to Uncle Garry.
How was the Palace Ian? Get yourself knighted?
I'm looking for Lucy.
Well Lauren's grounded, I mean, she ain't going to be here, not after that party. The sooner you reign your Lucy in mate, the better.
Max I need to find her.
Lauren, seen Lucy babe?
She wasn't in school today.
She should be home by now. I mean. You two are best mates, yeah, I mean has she said anything to you about where she might go?
Lauren. Now's not the time to cover for your mate. So if you know where she is, you let us know, OK, please.
She text me. She told me to meet her this morning at the swings. But she never showed.
Did she say anything about me and her arguing?
No. I'm sorry I didn't tell you.
Cheers Max.
Good girl.
Psst.
Shab, what are you doing lurking behind there?
Hiding from mum.
Oh. No sign. Operation ‚get you down the aisle's in full swing is it?
She had me cleaning all day. The house is fit for a royal visit.
And Prince Charming's on his way.
Don't. I was hoping to hide out with some of my uni mates but no one's around.
Well Keith's looking after Summer so how about we go to the club later?

I've settled in really well mummy, the Square feels like home now. And that's where I work. Very responsible job washing people's smalls. And Mrs Branning's ever so friendly, everyone is. Walford's lovely.
Lovely! It's dog rough. She was a right tart.
People are really nice to me around here.
But we know what they really think, Pig!

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Oi! You've been gone an hour. It's heaving down there.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I'll be down in five minutes.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You'll be down when I tell you. Now shift.

Scene_info: VIC UPSTAIRS, KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Alright. Alright. Keep your hair on.
Look what I've got for my favourite birdy. Pretty? PIGGGGG!
Nice one Bradley, Abi's gonna be well chuffed you're coming. you staying for tea, are you?
Can you give this to Abi - she can plant it for Marge or something.
That's alright. Just give it to her yourself.
No. I'm not staying.
Right, well Abi's gonna be upset.
Stop making me feel guilty for splitting up the family. You did that - not me.
Bradley, I'm not trying to make you feel guilty, I just don't want Abi and Lauren cut off from their brother, what's wrong with that?
You're at it again. I'll see them on my terms, not yours. Just stop trying to play dad with me.
Bradley, please come on.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No, I've tried them. listen if you see her, please tell her she's not in any trouble, we just want her home. Thanks. Bye. Alright that's everyone off the list. Nobody's seen or heard from her.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: None of the hospitals have got a record of admitting a Lucy Beale. So at least that's something.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I don't understand why she hasn't come home. Something feels wrong.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Maybe she's scared after everything that happened ...with the party.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: We need to start looking further afield, places she might be.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Well let's split up, meet at the park in a few hours, and see how we're doing.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Ian, I'll come with you, cos Bobby's on a play date.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE, LOUNGE INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No someone's gotta stay here, in case she comes back. We have to find her.
Right. Keep your eye out for any Colin Farrell look-a-likes - and I've got first dibs right?
Alright, but if the real Colin Farrell walks in here, he's mine. Sure we can't tempt you with that lovely shamrock hat Shirley?
Go on. It might cheer you up. You look like someone's died!
Well it's been a while since we've had a bird down the arches innit eh?
She's here.
Now no matter what happens we don't give Pretty back till she's gone - agreed?
Agreed.
Give me my Pretty now.
What are you on about?
This!
I didn't think
Mummy's homeless - she's got nowhere else to go.
I didn't write that and I didn't nick your stinkin bird!
Just let me take Pretty back home!
Mummy you can't go home, you've been evicted.
Course she can. You've been having us on, ain't you, you lying old cow.
I am really sorry Marge, that the foxes dug you up and ate you but whenever I see this flower I will remember you and so will Bradley.
Abi, is this going to take long, babe?
Everybody deserves a proper grave dad!
Paying your last respects - not exactly the perfect night out, is it.
yeah. We're back together, that's all I'm thinking about.
I'll get us a bottle of wine, yeah, to celebrate?
Oi! Come on then Shirl eh!
Come on you Biddy give us a chorus.
Get off me! I aint singing nothing!
Come on, tonights supposed to be a bit of fun. Why don't you get into the spirit!
Cause I'm not in the mood for this or you so get out of my face.
I'll get out of you face when you ditch your attitude.
Oi will you two pack it in. You're giving me a headache. Alright?
The barrel's off so why don't you sort it.
LUCY.
LUCY, YOU THERE?
Dad, I don't like this.
Anything?
Nobody's seen her at the canal.
I was at the bowling alley, the cinema - nothing. Dad, what if she's been abducted?
Is she's back home?
I've been in her room. Her bag's gone and so are some of her clothes.
Dad, you need to call the police, let them know what's happened.
We'll find her luv. We'll find her.
Police please. Yeah. I need to report my daughter missing.
Go on boys. Ave it.
Those two would give Michael Flatley a run for his money.
Two beers please.
Here and instead of a shamrocks can we have West Ham badges on the top please?
Do I look like Rolf Harris? Barrel's off.
Can't be, Shirley's just sorted it out.
Oh do hurry up, we're rather parched.
Bloody Shirley, she's skiving again.
No Leave it alright. If you go there'll be a blood bath. Let me handle her.
I pay you to work not sit on your backside, puffing away.
I was due a break so I took it. Smoking ain't barred in here, is it.
You couldn't wait till you'd changed the barrel. I got punters going thirsty in there.
Oh, have I ruined StPatrick's night? Tell Ronnie I'm so sorry.
What's up with you today, eh? You've been trappy all day. You're doing everbody's head in.
Maybe I'm sick of seeing people enjoy themselves.
It's a pub - and it's your job!
Well then sack me.
You know, I would have thought tonight would have been right up your street. I mean normally you're the life and soul, ain't you. What's so funny about that?
I might not be life and soul for much longer. I've found a lump and it could be cancer.
Your mum's been on the phone. Apparently you have to go home. It's past your bedtime.
Oh great, you've been rumbled, again.
Guess I should go.
We need to talk.

I know. I've been trying to talk to you all day. Don't worry about a thing, alright. Everything's sorted. I've got the flights booked, we're all checked in. I've got champagne on ice for after we take off tomorrow. We're out of here, we're out of here in style. Don't stress alright.
I've been on the internet all day. I've found this great school for the girls. They're gonna love it, we all will.
No. It's too late - we ain't going anywhere.
Jalil, you remember Shabnam, don't you?
How could I forget.
Hi.
It's a pity that you're too busy to show him around the square, isn't it Shabnam.
No, I've got time.
I knew he'd get out of this.
We were stupid to think he'd just sign everything over. I mean he's too smart, he's too devious. What was I thinking, trusting him.
This doesn't change anything - we've got the tickets, let's just go.
Oh how we going to bring up three kids with no money?
I don't know. We'll work it out. Come on please.
No, no. It doesn't matter where we go he'll find us. He'll find us. He'll take Oscar. He'll take my girls.
I won't let him.

No. You can't stop him. Getting away isn't enough anymore. I'm sick of Max always controlling me, you know, always winning. I want to destroy him. I want to take away everythinghe's ever cared about forever. There's only one way of doing that - we're going to kill him.

Scene_info: [NAME] & [NAME]'S HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: What?

Scene_info: [NAME] & [NAME]'S HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Nothing. It's just good to have you back.
Have you been looking for Lucy all night?
Yeah. Nothing.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: What's happened?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Nothing, um... This is Steven, Lucy's half brother.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: DC Hughes. Mrs Beale. I've just brought round the description of Lucy we've been circulating.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: It's good.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Look um... What about these? Do you need any more or anything? I've been showing them to people...

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: This should do it.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Alright. I don't know where else to try. I mean she's been gone two nights now. I mean, where do they go? I mean, what sort of places do teenagers go?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: She sounds a clever, resourceful girl, and with her history...

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: History? What d'you mean?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Well she's gone missing before and she came back.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: That was just with that idiot Craig, for one day! Oh I get it. You're just gonna cross your fingers crossed and hope for the best aren't ya?!

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Ian, Ian. They're doing their best. You've gotta keep calm.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: There's been plenty of enquiries...

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You are not doing enough. I want a detective inspector on this. Now.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You need to get some sleep. He's been up all night, looking for her.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: This kind of thing happens everyday... and chances are she's somewhere nearby and perfectly safe. Now if you can think of anything esle that you've forgotten to tell us...

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: We've told you everything!

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Alright. Here's my card. If anyone does think of anything that could help us understand why she left, then give me a call.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I'm gonna talk to every single person in school.
Still no sign of your bird, Queenie?
No.
Do you want me to help you look for her?
That won't be necessary. I know it's either him or that other ape who's got my Pretty, but let me tell you, I'm not moving from this flat until I get my bird back. Now, how do you like that?
Dunno what you're talking about.
If they force me out, you know what'll happen.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You didn't tell the police about hitting her.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: We don't wanna bother them with that! It'll just confuse the issue alright and I don't want you calling them. Right, go on. Go!

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: What was he saying?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Oh crazy theories.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: If Steven knows something, he should tell the police.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: He doesn't know anything.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Oh you're gonna keep me in the dark like you usually do?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No, no love, of course not! Listen there's still some parents I haven't spoke to at school. I'm going to go down there.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Okay.
Is it just you here?
Yeah.
Right, I've only got a few minutes. I'm going out of my mind. Tell me what you're thinking.
I'm thinking, she's had a night's sleep, maybe she's calmed down a bit.
I'm calm.
Alright then, so tell me what you're thinking?
I haven't changed my mind.
Have you any idea how mad this is?
I've thought this through...
No, you haven't.
I have, I have. What you think Max is gonna let me go? Let alone his kids? No, he's gonna keep on lying and twisting. He'll go on and on until he wins right... 'cause he always wins.
Tanya, no matter how bad it gets, no matter how much you want Max gone, you won't do it. You ain't got it in ya.
Yeah, I have.
Okay. So, Max is dead, Lauren and Abi are in pieces, the police are all over you, and we start playing happy families?
Yeah, we could do it. Couldn't we?
Oh, Tanya, we'd never be free of it. It's a dream.
It's all I've got Sean. Please.
What do you want from me?
I want you to help me.
I thought you were going for the biopsy today?
I didn't feel like it.
What are you? Six years old?
And what are you? My dad?
D'you need any help?
No, no, thank you, Jalil.
I can check your accounts, sort out your cashflow...?
Yeah. Um, why don't you rearrange the envelopes for me?
Not sure that's is the best use of my MA in business studies, but you're the boss.
Thank you. He's smart. A bit too smart, but I like him. What about you?
I don't know.
For once, I think we're in agreement. Why don't we all get together and have a special meal tonight?
Yeah alright, but can we be cool about it? No. I'll ask him.
Okay, we'll be cool.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Er, can you just put it over there, thank you.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Hello.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Oh come in Tanya.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Hi. I just came to see if Lucy had turned up?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Er no. No sign. The, er, TV got smashed at the party. Ian ordered a new one, thanks. Well, before we knew about Lucy...

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I can't imagine what you're going through. I mean I know Max has already grounded Lauren, but I wouldn't want the kids out anyway, not now.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I've racked my brains, trying to think where she might be.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I've ransacked her room, but all I've found are these ticket and programmes, they're just mementoes of things she's been to with Steven.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Well they're pretty close. He not got any ideas where she is?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: He says not.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: And you believe him?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: What d'you mean?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: It's just after everything that happened with you...I mean...I'm not sure if I'd ever trust him again.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I've gotta get off and get Oscar. So I'll...

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No no no. We should have a proper chat. It's working out, with you and Max?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Are you alright?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Am I mad? Have I completely lost it?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No. Tanya what's going on?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: It's ... I can't ... I'm just being silly, you've got enough on your plate. I'll go anyway.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No, Tan wait.
What is wrong with you?
Do you want the gossip.
Yeah, alright. I want the gossip.
Well there ain't no gossip. Time for everyone to get on with their lives.
Sean, this isn't good for you, you know. Brooding. You don't stand a chance of getting Tanya back. Not now.
Is that right?
Max is what she wants, the thick cow that she is.
Stacey, stop talking.
Sean. I don't want to hurt you, but you need to get it straight. It's over.
Oh, it's over, is it? Just drink your drink, okay.
You're still seeing her, aren't you?
A drink on the house for Queenie.
What's this?!
It's called a Sour Old Boiler. I made it especially for you. It's got fag ends and beer dregs and something personal from me.
When oh when are you going to stop being such a tart, Shirley?
And when oh when are you gonna die?
Are you going to let her talk to me like that?
Shirley, that's out of order. You take that back.
Oh come on - the old coffin-dodger's been keeping us waiting for years.
I'll live to see you in your grave, you tramp.
Yeah well we'll see about that...
Oi oi oi. Just leave it will ya. Now take your break, go on, now.
Take me away from here, Heather, this terrible place.
Nice mother-in-law you're getting there.
Yeah I know. We're trying to get rid of her, but Heather wants her to stay.
Close, are they?
Not really. She's horrible to her.
You better sort her out, before someone ends up strangling her.
Look at us eh? What a pair. The Slaters. Hard as nails. You can't get one over on us.
So?
So look at what Max did to me. I believed all of his lies Sean. And now Tanya's doing the same to you.
Stacey, what are you talking about?
This is what you really want, is it? Sneaking round behind Max's back? Getting a little thrill every now and again?
I dunno, maybe, maybe it is.
She has got everything she wants, Sean. She's got her kids, her marriage, that snake back in her bed, and now, just to make herself feel extra special, she's got you hanging on to her every move.
No no no. It's not like that.
How is it not like that?
Because you don't know...
How is it not like that?
Because she loves me.
She doesn't love you,
Phil, can I have the afternoon off?
If you wanted time off to go to the clinic, you just had to ask.
I don't want time off to go to the clinic. I want time off to get bladdered.
The Sour Old Boiler. I like it.
I have my moments.
Listen I was thinking, it's a nice afternoon. I might go to the dogs.
So what? You mean I've gotto work?!
No, so you can come too.
I don't like dogs.
Neither do I. But I like gambling, you like drinking. We'll be well catered for won't we.
I don't want to sit in some crummy place surrounded by losers.
You are one stroppy cow you ain't ya?
That's rich coming from Mr Chuckles.
I'll be leaving in five minutes.
Mum wants to have some special meal tonight. You gonna be around?
Why? Does she want to give me a grilling?
No. What d'you mean?
She's got me lined up as the new son in law! She thinks I'm a catch.
No. If she likes you so much, why's she got you selling staplers, Mr Business Studies?
Shabnam, I'm only teasing. I'd love to have a meal with you all.
Oh. Right. Sorry.
And don't mock the business studies alright.
One day I'm hoping to become Postman Pat.
Take me to the races, Philip.
Get the TV warmed up. And I'll want a blanket.
Heather, this can't go on.
I know she's difficult and I know she's demanding, but you don't have to worry about it. I'll do it all. I'll cope with everything. I'm used to it.
She can go back to her flat any time she wants.
Yeah, but she doesn't want ... I can't tell her to go.
What? Are you scared of her? Does she hurt you?
No. No. Mummy would never hurt me. Well not, not physically. Well, sometimes physically, but that isn't it. It's something else.
What?
Well, I suppose she's sort of blackmailing us. If Mummy doesn't get her cut of the £2000, then she's gonna grass us to the magazine.
Very funny.
Mr Chuckles strikes again.
You can't make me go in there.
Can't I?
I saw you come in. Look I need to talk to you. What's that?
I'm gonna go. Use the ticket to Spain.
What are you saying?
I'll be waiting for you.
No no, that's not gonna to work.
It's all I've got.
Look Sean, let me explain...
No, let me tell you something alright. I love you, If you feel the same way, then you'll sort things out here and come with me.

The thing is ... this hospital... is the one my mum died in. And it was a horrible, drawn-out thing. When I walked out of there, I vowed I'd never go in that building again. I admit that I'm scared. So I'll make another appointment at a different hosptial. Understand?
You know, if you was any good at lying, you'd be a menace. But the fact is, you're useless. So useless in fact ...it's ... er... what's the word? Endearing.
So I made it up. It was worth a try though, weren't it?
You're scared, I'll give you that. Now come on, out!

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Anything?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Alright, well I've now spoken to just about every other parent in the school and nothing. I'm shattered, I'm gonna go get some kip.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Look um... I've been thinking ... about what might have made Lucy run away. Don't be angry.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I won't be angry.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Do you think it might be something to do with Steven?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Steven?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yeah. I thought there was something funny about him this morning.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yeah.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I'll talk to him.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No, no, I wouldn't do that. I mean you know what he's like, he's volatile. Best we just keep an eye on him.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - KITCHEN INT DAY LIGHT
Line: If that's what you want.
You didn't need to wait.
I didn't. I went to the dogs.
Right.
You OK? You didn't slip out the back and go to the pub?
My next appointment card.
Good girl.
It's like having my own personal prison officer.
Prison officer and chauffeur. Come on.
Can I just say, in advance, sorry, about anything my mother, or my brother, may do, or say.
Hello. Well, I hope you have a good evening. We'll see you later.
We're having a special dinner, aren't we?
What do you mean? I'm taking Tam to his school. It's his parents evening.
Mum!
We must have got our wires crossed.
Never mind. Some other time maybe.
No, no no no. Please don't be silly. Let me think. We MIGHT have some food you could eat...
Where you been all afternoon? Not in here?
Yup.
Well I need to talk to you, about Jane.
I already know all about it!
Steven! Are you going away?
That was the plan yeah.
But what? You've changed your mind?
I can't go.
Why not?
I just can't.
What is it?
Ok. Tam has left a casserole in the oven and there's ice-cream in the freezer.
This is so embarrassing!!
Only if you make it embarrassing. Shabnam, now listen to me, if romance was left to men, the entire species would die out. They need a little push.
Where's Dad?
He's upstairs, asleep. Is something wrong?
You think I made Lucy run away.
No...
I heard you, talking to Stacey.
I'm just trying to think if there's any reason she might have for going...
And if anything goes wrong in this family, it's got something to do with me!
No.
You said you were going to keep your eye on me. You said I'd mess up again.
That was months ago.
And you still don't trust me.
Steven...
You don't trust me!
No.
Come on.
That's a bit desperate ain't it? Can't you just wait for 30 seconds?
Yeah well it looks like I'll have to don't it?
Yeah it does yeah. Still, I know how it is.
Do you?

Yeah, everything looks a bit grey, a bit drab. Nothing's going right. You feel a little bit jumpy, and there it is - the pub. You just want to dive in don't ya. Before you know it, the whole afternoon's gone. You're trolleyed and it's only ... ... half eight. Still, what is it to you eh? It's only another day ain't it. What else you got in your life?
No.
That smile! It's frightening. Right, well, I've got a business do. It's boring I know, but when you've got a family to support...
Look I'm the problem, I should go.
Let's just sit down and talk.
I mean, I only called you back on Sunday ‚cos they were trashing your house. I only saved the day.
Yeah I know that and I'm grateful...
If you're looking for a reason why Lucy might have run away, maybe you should talk to Dad.
Why?
Oh forget it.
Look I am fed up with all these lies and secrets! What is going on between you and your dad?!
The night she left, he hit her. He knocked her down. Yeah. But it's me you don't trust.
Why've we got chips? What's going on?
Your sister has a very babyish attitude towards relationships. That is why I have brought this.
A baby monitor!
Shut up. Listen.
I'll be back in a minute and I don't want anyone to change the channel when I'm gone.
I can't take much more of this. I'm gonna say something.
No, Minty. Please don't.
Well, I tell you what; I've got her bird and the way she's going now, she'll be lucky if she doesn't get it back stuffed.
You took Pretty?!
Yeah I did. It serves her right, she's blackmailing us, isn't she?
Before Mummy came, I was going to say, you should have all the spending money for the wedding.
What d'you mean?
The truth is, I've given up on Garry. He wouldn't want me, even if I did spend £2000 on me self. I mean, who would?
Don't say that!
It's true though.

Don't run yourself down alright. Don't let that Queenie blow your confidence. There's thousands of men who'd want you. The funny thing is, I was going to say the same thing to you. Hazel don't want me. I know that now. So I was gonna give all the money to you.
If Hazel doesn't want you, she's a fool. You're the sweetest, loveliest man I've ever met.
I'm on the toilet. Can you help me with my special pants.
No, I know. When your mum comes home, let's tell her we got engaged.
Yes! She'd love that. ﬁIt's all down to me you know.ﬂ
Sorry. Hey ... Sweetness, you know I'm always thinking about you ... You don't have to tell your mother everything....
Let's keep some secrets for us...
He's a fast mover.
Yeah.
That was my girlfriend.
Oh. What's her name?
We're home.
Mum?
Did you enjoy your meal?
Yes, it was lovely.
Good, then you won't mind doing the washing up.
No, of course not.
Why are you back so soon?
Maybe not soon enough! Eh... Mmmm.
Oh thank god. I thought you'd gone.
Yeah, well I couldn't could I?
The kids are all in bed.
Alright. So - talk.
Right... um... I just want you to try and see this from my point of view. Alright.
That's my trouble Tan - 'Cause I don't do I?
Look, I know you WANT to hate me, alright. 'Cause that way you can get away from all this. Right. And I hate myself. I do. But I have got no choice.
Everybody's got a choice.
No, they haven't. People like you have, with no ties to anything. But my kids ... I've got my girls, I've got Oscar...
Well think about what this do to them?
He's gonna take my kids away from me!!
We can stop him.
No. No we can't! 'Cause he's got the courts on his side, right, he's made me look bad with everyone, with the Social, with everyone. And he, he just keeps twisting everything that I'm doing.
We can fight him.
He's never gonna stop. He's never gonna stop. No matter where we go, no matter what we do, he is never gonna stop until he's destroyed me.
Come on, come on, come on. Shhh. I know you're scared. I know you're scared. But I'm not. I can deal with Max.
I wish I could believe that.

Scene_info: VIC DOWNSTAIRS - HALLWAY INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I've been a right little git all day, haven't I? But, thanks.

Scene_info: VIC DOWNSTAIRS - HALLWAY INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Listen. You know, Mum's been through the same thing. You could always talk to her.

Scene_info: VIC DOWNSTAIRS - HALLWAY INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I don't want anyone to know. Phil?

Scene_info: VIC DOWNSTAIRS - HALLWAY INT DAY LIGHT
Line: What?

Scene_info: VIC DOWNSTAIRS - HALLWAY INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I'm really scared.

Scene_info: VIC DOWNSTAIRS - HALLWAY INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Come here.
Sometimes I think he's controlling me.
Well he's a smarmy git. He knows how to push people's buttons. I'll give him that.
It's more than that. It's mroe than that. It's like he knows what I'm thinking. It's like he knows what I'm gonna do next. Maybe...
What?
Maybe this is his doing? Right, maybe he wanted us to meet tonight?
No Tanya.
Maybe he knows we've been seeing each other? Maybe he knows what I've been planning?
You're being paranoid.
No, I slept with him! I slept with Max, after
Yeah well you did that for a reason.
Maybe I did, maybe I didn't. Maybe I did it 'cause he wanted me to.
Well you need to get away from him.
Can't you see, Sean? I am, I'm almost lost here. Maybe I'll sleep with him again. Maybe I'll go on sleeping with him, Maybe I'll spend the rest ofmy life with him. Maybe he's already won.
Come on then Tanya. Let's just get out of here!
No I can't!! Not without my kids. You see, there's no way out for me.
I've been over this a hundred times. A thousand times. I mean it's all I've been thinking about. It's like I'm sleep-walking. And I jus... I need to wake up. I just need to wake up and do it.
No, Tanya.
Yeah, yeah. There's no other way. And if we do it right, you know, we'll be together, with plenty of money, no worries.
Tan. This is crazy.
Yeah. I'm going to do it. With or without ya. Please don't make me do it on my own. Sean, Sean. Will you help me?

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT NIGHT
Line: Ian, this morning, I asked you if you were keeping me in the dark about Lucy going, and you said no.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT NIGHT
Line: Well I'm not. I don't know what you...

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT NIGHT
Line: Then this afternoon, I asked you about Steven, and you implied he might be involved with Lucy going.

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT NIGHT
Line: I may have been a bit hasty with ...

Scene_info: BEALES' HOUSE - LIVING ROOM INT NIGHT
Line: Ian ... Steven says you hit Lucy. Is that true?
So, how come you're back so early?
You know how it is. I showed my face. I thought; what am I doing with these losers, I've got a beautiful wife at home.
Coming to bed?
Yes. I'll just lock up.
When?
Friday night.
Give me back my toothpaste!
Make me!
Shirley, we're late.
Yeah, we're all late.
Don't you dare go back in that bathroom!
Why? What have you left in there?
Heather!!
I know, Mummy, I know.
Open that door!
Get stuffed the pair of you.
Oh this is lovely this, ain't it. It's like the Playboy Mansion, with all the lovely bunny girls scrapping over make-up.
I don't know what to do!
Look is two grand spending money really worth going through all this?
If you're going to stay in there all day then pass me out my incontinence pads!
What's that? Question answered. So why go through with it? I'll tell you why. It's 'cause you have got feelings for Heather.
I have not.
Yeah. Alright. Well this is our lad pad ain' it. Right, let's get the baggage out and get the babes in eh?
Oi, oi, oi, oi, oi. Where you going?
I've got to get the girls ready.
They'll be alright.
Are you mad?
Oscar's asleep.
Look I'm serious.
What's... what's changed?
Just... Don't push me.
Look babe, I ain't pushing. It's just the weekend was good. I thought it was a new start.
It was. It's gonna be alright.
You can't keep searching all night, every night Ian.
I have to.
Have you told the police - about you hitting Lucy?
No, not yet.
Ian what is this? They need to know everything.
How can I. I mean for all they know I've been knocking her around every day. I could become a suspect...
Anything?
No. I'm sorry Pete.
I don't understand. What else can we do? I want Lucy back.
Tanya...
We, um... seeing the solicitor tomorrow, what, it's Good Friday?
Yeah, I mean it's all she could do, I mean she's going away for two weeks. Sorry...
No, I'm sorry. I'm sorry about earlier. Listen, I was thinking... um... You know tomorrow night, after we've been to see the solicitor, how about we have an evening eh? Just us?
Well, that'd be nice.
Yeah.
What about the kids?
Well can you find someone to look after them?
Yeah. Bradley or Jack...?
What? What have you got against him?
He was just ...er... giving me a hard time that's all.
What? About what?
I dunno. Maybe he can't stand to see anyone else happy? Tomorrow. Once you've got rid of the kids.
I'm gonna get them adopted if I have to.
You couldn't do it, could you? You couldn't just listen to your mother and stick to the plan.
What plan?
The dinner. You admitted that it was a set up, didn't you?
How d'you know?
Never mind how I know. But, I mean, where was the romance after that?
Er, maybe between him and his girlfriend?
Girlfriend?
He was talking to her on the phone, all lovey-dovey.
Ooooooh.
It's on for tomorrow night. Right. The kids will be out.
Alright.
Can you get a van?
Yeah.
Right. We're going to be together very, very soon. Max, the girls - everything's gonna be sorted.
Tan. We should sit down, talk this all through.
No I know what I'm doing.
I can't help you if you don't tell me what's going on.
The less you know the better.
No. What are you planning?
It's not going to be quick, that's all.
What was all that?
Oh... He's just hurt that's all. Can't leave it alone.
What? Is he giving you hassle...
No. He'll get over it. We don't need an argument do we. So what about tomorrow night?
Er, yeah, Dot can't do it - she's seeing Dad.
You need to find someone, yeah?
Do you wanna know a secret?
Go on then.
Couldn't say in front of Mummy, but me and Minty, we came that close...
That close to what?
Kissing again! But for real this time! I think I really like him.
That's a surprise.
Yeah, but, he might still be hung up on Hazel. And we're all living together. It's complicated.
You're telling me.
Sorry about this morning, Mint.
Yeah. It's er...not really working out, is it?
It's not going to be for long now though.
Look I'm sorry Heather. but I'm going to have to pull out of the wedding.
No!
It's just got too much, with you and Shirley moving in and all the lies, and now your mother getting involved...
She'll keep her mouth shut, I promise she will.
I think things have got a little bit complicated between me and you. After all, it's only money isn't it...?
Yeah.
You know when you went to the dogs with Shirley yesterday?
Yeah?
Was that a date?
Ben, this type of talk is liable to get right out of hand, so let's just get one thing straight. I am not going on any dates with Shirley. You got that?
Yeah.
Now I'm sorry to disappoint you. But, let this be the end to it, yeah?
What was that about?

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I feel like I should ask for a solicitor.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Really? Why?

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No, I'm, I'm only joking. It's just a police interview room... seen it on telly.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: There's no need to be nervous, Mr Beale. We're only talking.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I know. I'm sorry. I'm just a bit tired. I've been out every night. Soho, Camden, Waterloo, I've been trying different hostels. I keep thinking I've got to do everything I can to try and find her.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I know.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Um, the thing is, um, before she left, we had an argument, like I told you and... well it got a bit out of hand.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Out of hand?

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I hit her. It wasn't hard, I man, she fell over.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: You didn't mention hitting her before.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No, well, I, I didn't think it was that bigger deal. No, well, I know hitting your kids is a big deal, I mean, but honestly I, I've never been violent to any of my kids, I mean, that's all. I mean, Lucy lashed out. I know it's not right, but, you don't know Lucy, you don't know what she's like.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: She's a handful.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yeah. I mean she started going off the rails last year. Not like her twin brother. He's an Olympic prospect, a really good runner. Nice lad. Pleasure to be around.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: So, you spend more time with him.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Well, yeah, yeah, I suppose so.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Would you say there's an on-going battle between you and Lucy?

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yeah. I mean she's clever. She's opinionated. She's always .... getting her belly button pierced, or throwing wild parties or...

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: The usual teenage stuff.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yeah.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: But that doesn't usually end in a punch up, does it?

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No, but she doesn't just do the usual teenage things. We had an invite to go to the Palace, to see the Queen ... The Queen yeah!... and she ripped up the invites.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Was this the occasion you dragged her from the market?

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No, no that was something else. How have you heard about that?

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Well, we've done some asking around. So, this was a separate occasion.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Have you been checking up

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: The point is, Mr Beale, when you said that this was the first time you'd ever had a violent altercation with Lucy, that wasn't true, was it?
Oi! Golden Boy. What have you been saying to Tanya?
I'm just looking out for you.
yeah, well I don't need you to.
Well, don't you think it's a bit weird, the way Tanya's suddenly turned round?
Well I'm sorry why, what do you know about our marriage?
I know what you did.
We love each other Jack. That's all that matters.
Well I've been through a divorce remember. From my experience - watch your back.
What? So that's what you're doing for me is it?

Yes it is! I can't help myself. It's just like when we was kids and you'd give me a whistle when Mum was coming round the corner. Or I'd give you a shout if I thought the teachers were on to you. I mean that's what brothers do.
Yeah. Beautiful.
Well maybe you don't remember.

Nah, you see, what I remember is you always having all the attention, all the best sweets, and all the best toys. And if ever I had anything good, you'd go crying off to Dad. ‚Cos I was never allowed to be happy. And that is what this is all about.
Listen to me...
No, you listen to me alright. You leave us alone!

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Why do you keep going on about this little slap that I gave her. I only told ya because I want you to know what state of mind she was in when she ran away.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Alright. But we need to know exactly what happened when you hit her.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I've told ya...

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Tell me again.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I slapped her.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Did it draw blood?

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: No, nothing like that...

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Was it a slap, or a punch?

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I slapped her, alright... Fairly hard.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Hard enough to knock her down.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Yeah. Look... I only lashed out because she hit me.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: So you said. But why did she hit you?

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Because, I said some harsh things.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: What, exactly?

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Oh, look does it matter?

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: It might.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Look, it was an argument. It was private.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Not any more.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Look, it had been a big day. Well, she trashed the house.

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: And?

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I, I said to her that when... when her mum left that she would've been better off is she'd gone with her. Oh God, what have I done?!

Scene_info: POLICE INTERVIEW ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Right, bring her in. Well, it seems we've found a girl, living rough, who says she's seen someone who matches Lucy's description. They're bringing her in to the station now.
Oi, oi, what's this?
It's an address.
Of what?
You need to go there tomorrow night.
And do?
You'll see.
Tanya what's with notes?! Wh..wh...why can't you call me? Why can't you just...
Max saw us together this morning. We need to be more careful.
What, so this is how it is now is it?
For a while, yeah, but then we've got the rest of our lives together eh. Just think about that...
No...
We can get away from here. We can forget about everything that's happened. What d'you want to do with your life, Sean? Whatever it is, we'll do it.
Well, yeah, I do have a lot of plans in my life actually Tanya, but the main one is staying out of prison so...
What plans? Tell me.
No. 'Cause you know what, I don't like being kept in the dark. So if you wanna do all this on your own? Go ahead.
No. Don't be like that, Sean. Please, I need you. I need you.
Oh, it's a friend.
No personal calls, please.
Right. Is there anything I can do? Check the takings? Do a financial projection?
Sure, why don't you mop the floor?
Okay.

Here it is. Now, I'm sure you'll be wanting to get back to your flat, so as soon as you're packed, give us a nod and I'll put you in a cab. And as far as the money's concerned, I really appreciate you keeping schtum, so I thought maybe a three way split would be fair. Yeah?
Alright, now it's my turn to talk.
Hey...

Sit down!! ﬁGive us a nod when you've packed.ﬂ Turn it in, you fat fool! I know you want me out. I know you hate me. But I don't care. And you're going to have to lump it! And do you know why? Because you don't want to hurt Heather's
No.

No. And if you don't want to hurt Heather's feelings, then you don't hurt my feelings. Have you got that? And if anyone's leaving this flat, it's not me, it's Miss Mini-Skirt. Either her or that spud in overalls.
Garry?
Yeah Garry. I'm not going anywhere until I've got my money AND your money in my hand.
Hello.
You alright? What are you doing?
You found a baby-sitter yet?
Sorry?
Baby-sitter
Er, no, no, no. Bradley's being funny, well they're all being funny.
You know people.
So where you been?
Nowhere. Just round at Jane's. Look, I've gotta get back. But look ... ...Remember, no baby-sitter, no night in.
Alright, don't worry about it.
Didn't go well?
I think the upshot of it all is, Garry's moving out?
Oh. Sorry Minty.
She's a very forceful woman.
Dad used to say Mum learnt to be tough when she was in the parachute regiment. He was joking.
He must have been quite some man, your Dad.
Yeah, he was a great Dad. It's because of him I always wear Alice bands.
Yeah?
Yeah. He bought me one, when I was eight. I was going to a wedding, and I didn't get chosen to be a bridesmaid, so he bought me a special sparkly Alice band. He said I looked pretty.
What happened to him?
He walked out on us.
That must have been tough.
Yeah, it was my fault, as well.
Why?
He couldn't stand living with me.
He couldn't stand living with YOU?
I'll er...I'll take the girls tomorrow night.
Right, well good... They'll be happy about that.
I just don't like being manipulated.
Yes Bradley, I get it alright.
It's almost as if you never know when to stop pushing.
Why, why is everyone so keen on giving me a lecture today?
Maybe because we all know something you don't.
And what does that men? What, what, what? What do you know that I don't?!
That you've got to give us some time Dad! You can't have it all back. People have got to
Yeah. I know alright, I'm sorry.
You seem a little jumpy, Dad. You know, maybe you should go and lie down.
yeah right, I am jumpy alright. I just want it all back. I want you back.
She did do alright by me really. Bringing me up with no money.
Yeah, well I'm sure your mum had a really tough time.
Yeah.
But that's no excuse for the way she treats you.
But if Dad hadn't left, everything might have been different.
Yeah, but it's not your fault is it?
It was. I was horrible. I was a greedy lump, always in tears, always in trouble. He couldn't stand it.
You were only a kid. How could you know?
Mummy told me.
Your mum ... Your... Your mum is... is a liar!
What?
A nasty, selfish, liar!
What's all this then?

It's just a family meal ain't it, as in cooked by the whole family. Apart from Oscar, he's having a little kip upstairs. Plus, the good news is Bradley's gonna take you two ice-skating tomorrow night.
Really?!
Aren't I grounded?
Nah, not tomorrow.
What about you two?
No, he don't want us does he? We have to make our own entertainment, don't we?
Yeah. We will.
I can't do it, Mint.
Heather, I'm not giving you a choice. Either she leaves, or you both leave.
Don't be horrible.
I'm not being horrible. But this is the only way you're gonna be free of her.
But she's my mummy.
Heather...
Alright. I know. If you say it's for the best... Then I trust you. I'll do it for you.
Alright, well, I'm gonna take you to the door and the rest is up to you alright.
I need some more dutch courage.
No you don't. You've had enough dutch courage you've nearly turned orange. Now come on, up.
Go give her one, Hev! Then give him one too. She'll be back in here in ten minutes in tears. I'm gonna go get her some cheesy snacks.
My god, she is gorgeous.
You been talking to Ben?
No. In all seriousness yeah, I know I might have said some nasty things about her in the past, about her being a scraggy old witch and that, but listen, I think you should go for it.
Do me a favour.
No, you should. Phil. Shirley. BOOM! The biggest car crash of the millennium. I'd like to see that.
Abi won't even be able to stand up.
Yes I will.
No you won't. I've seen little girls like you trying to skate. Everyone just laughs.
Lauren, give it a rest please.
Well I don't care. Because the best bit about the ice rink is the pick and mix.
Oh yeah, like you can't get that in any other sweet shop.
It's better at skating. Becuase I can get a little bit of everything in a really big bag.
And then sit in the corner and stuff your face
Well I know someone who won't be getting any of my pick and mix.
Listen to me alright... When i was a kid I used to love sherbet lemons. Alright, I use to get them in this big jar, get them by the quarter pound. Jim'd get them. But he never use to give me any.
Why not?
Did he eat them all himself?

No. He'd give them to Jack. All of them. And he'd just look at me. And I'd feel ... I dunno... I'd feel all sorts of things. I just don't want you two to end up like me and Uncle Jack alright. So would you please, for me, try and get on?
Alright.
Well can't you find someone to look after Summer? I wanna go out... oh hang on.
You're talking to Dawn about Jalil?
No!
I saw a picture of his girlfriend on his phone. I don't think we have anything to worry about.
Why not?
Because she's ugly. Looks like she's had her make up done by Edward Scissorhands.
Mother!
What? I'm sure his family love her, but I don't think he'll be settling down just yet.
Look I have to get out of here right now!
Wait, Mum, I'm coming with ya. I didn't mean what I said. This has all been a big mistake. Look let's go home. I'll make us a nice cauliflower cheese?
Get off me!! I never want to see you again!
Mum?
No-one will ever love you, Pig!!
Shirley.
Yes, Boss.
I just wanted to say ...um... ... Well, it seems like you're bearing up?
I can put on a show. But yeah, I'm alright. I've got no choice really.
I knew it!
What?
You two are gonna do it.
Ben! Don't be so rude!
Ben, that's out of order.
You are.
Well I hate to disappoint you, but I like a bloke with some hair.
She's not my type son. She's too hard.
I've never been into short men either.
Oh yeah, like you give a monkey's once you've had a skinful.
It's like Jalil's been sent here to take the mickey out of me. ﬁWhy haven't you got a boyfriend?ﬂ ﬁWhat's wrong with you?ﬂ
Well, there's plenty of blokes here.
Right, tonight, I pull.
What about him?
Who?
Over there.
You should have seen her, I mean I'm not just talking about her hair and her clothes, it was... it was her eyes - there was nothing there.
Lucy's smarter than that. She'll be fine.
I've been the worst dad in the world.
You've only been doing your best.
You know what I forgott in all of those battles ... She's just fourteen. She's only a teenager. And I should have been loving her and instead all I did was fight with her.
She's gonna be alright, Ian. I know she will.
Night night darling.
I'm so glad Dad's back. He's gonna stay, isn't he?
Yeah.
For ever?
Yeah.
Lauren says she loves you more than she loves Dad, but I love you both the same.
Go on, go to bed. Night night darling.
Night.
Oh no.
This is what you want!
It's a bit silly, both of us pretending we can't see the other one.
Yeah.
I didn't know you drink.
Just a bit.
Do you wanna join us?
Mmm. Shabnam Masood.
I feel like I've lost three stone or something.
Well you have. You've just shaken off the biggest dead weight in history.
You alright, Shirl?
Bad day at work. So, what you gonna do with all this freedom?
I'm going to marry Minty. And d'you know why? Because I love him.
Max.
Tan...
Tomorrow. What was all that about at dinner?
I've had a bad day alright. I'm on edge. Babe, what's going on with us?
I'm too tired for this.
I need to ask you something.
What?
Something serious.
What?
Well look at me would you. I feel like I haven't looked you in the face for days.
What d'you wanna ask me?
I dunno.
Max...
Just tell me alright, to my face, we're gonna be alright.
Look, I know you've had your doubts, but by tomorrow night I promise you they'll all be gone, everything will be sorted between us, for good.
Thanks.
Cheers. She's here, babe ...
You're doing the right thing. You do know that don't you.
Yes.
This is a little unorthodox to say the least.
Yeah, well we're just keen to get things settled.
So you've come to an arrangement?
Yes. I've behaved really badly, and Tanya found it in her heart to forgive me. We're just trying to make a go of things. We just want to make this marriage work.
Well, if you're both sure.
Sign both copies and the divorce proceedings will be brought to a close.
This is like getting married all over again.
Till death us do part.
Yeah.
Yes.
Hi. Any news?
No.
Have you checked the answerphone? Any calls?
No there hasn't been.
What's Oscar doing here?
I told you we were baby-sitting.
He's my godson. Look Ian, sit down. I'll make you a cup of tea.
I'm just gonna call the police.
Any news Ian. They'll call you.
Bobby, will you stop that. Bobby, will you please stop that. I'm not joking. You carry on doing this. I'll stick it in the bin.
Ian ...
He's doing my head in.
He's four years old.
No. He's selfish. His sister is out there, somewhere, I don't know where and he's just trying to rub a car up and down my leg. I've had enough of it. No.
Why don't you raise your hand to him ... ... it worked on Lucy.
What worked on Lucy?
Nothing.
Jane?
Where you going?
The park. A walk. Get Bobby out from under your feet.
It's alright luv. You don't have to.
Come on Bobby. We won't be long.
Cheer up. Worst is over.
Sorry. I'm just a bit tired.
I know. It's exhausting innit. It's all this stress. But it's all sorted now, innit. And that is why I'm taking you out for a fancy meal tonight. Champagne. Posh frock the whole lot.
I told you. I'm gonna cook.
Not any more you ain't. It's all sorted.
Just like that, without consulting me?
I thought you'd be pleased.
I wanted to cook you dinner. I've got all the ingredients. I've got a really nice bottle of wine.
I don't want you slaving over a hot stove. We've go to start this off right.

Some things aren't so simple, you know. You can't sign a few papers and buy a girl a posh meal and think that everything's done and dusted. We've got to feel our way back into it. haven't we ... being a couple again ...
Yeah well I thought we were a couple again.
We are. We are. Tonight, I just want it to be you and me, in our home. My husband eating the food I've cooked for him. That's as special as I need.
Babe you're amazing.
What's that?
Easter Eggs. For Sunday. Thought we'd really go to town this year, hide ‚em all round the square, I got clues worked out and everything. Make ‚em sweat for their chocolate.

Scene_info: [NAME] & [NAME]'S HOUSE, HALL/LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Right. Come on girls, get yourself together. Bradley's gonna be here soon.

Line: I can't find my gloves.

Line: Why do you want gloves?

Scene_info: [NAME] & [NAME]'S HOUSE, HALL/LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Durrrr. Ice skating. I don't want my fingers freezing off.

Scene_info: [NAME] & [NAME]'S HOUSE, HALL/LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I'll get you some then. You need to wear two pairs of socks so you don't catch cold, alright.

Scene_info: [NAME] & [NAME]'S HOUSE, HALL/LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: I've already got a cold.

Line: What're in the bags?

Scene_info: [NAME] & [NAME]'S HOUSE, HALL/LIVING ROOM INT DAY LIGHT
Line: Nothing.

Yeah ...
